<DOCNO> AP881107-0009 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-07-88 0032EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-FangLizhi     11-07 0796</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Fang Lizhi,0820</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Astrophysicist Emerges As Communist China's Top Dissident</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Monday AMs report.</NOTE>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN BIERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Astrophysicist Fang Lizhi is happiest pondering
the mysteries of the universe, but he has become embroiled in the
more worldly affairs of politics by fearlessly speaking out against
China's communist government.
   Fang, 52, has emerged as China's top dissident by publicly
championing democracy and questioning Marxism in this one-party
state.
   ``We hope we have a good government, but there is no guarantee,''
says the Beijing Observatory professor with the easy manner and
impish smile. ``The only guarantee comes from people's pressure.''
   ``I like to speak freely,'' he said in a recent interview in his
airy Beijing apartment. ``I think I just show ... we have the right
of speech.''
   Fang emerged during pro-democracy student demonstrations that
rocked major Chinese cities in late 1986 and early 1987. Authorities
said speeches he gave to students at the University of Science and
Technology in Hefei helped incite the protests.
   When China's leaders cracked down on the protests, Fang was
kicked out of the Communist Party and fired from his university post.
   The demonstrations died down, but Fang refused to be silenced.
   Since his purge, he has given a series of interviews to foreign
journalists, criticizing one-party rule and claiming Marxism is
outdated and widely unpopular. No other Chinese of his stature has
dared to publicly launch such attacks on the system.
   During a summer visit to Australia, Fang mentioned rumors that
many Chinese leaders and their children maintained foreign bank
accounts. Chinese authorities, reportedly displeased with his
statements, subsequently withdrew permission for Fang to travel to
the United States later this year.
   Fang said he does not regret any of his comments and will
continue to speak out. ``I'm a soldier who already crossed the
river,'' he said. ``There's no way to turn back.''
   Authorities are reluctant to allow Fang to speak before an
audience, even on non-political topics, he said.
   At an informal gathering on the Beijing University campus to mark
the school's 90th anniversary in May, he was treated like a hero by
several hundred students who came to hear him speak on science and
democracy. When Fang was leaving, a crowd formed around him and
students thrust forward books, envelopes, handkerchiefs and even
money for the professor to sign.
   Letters of support come to Fang almost daily from around the
country. He says they encourage him to continue his activities.
   The last person to embody support for democracy in China was Wei
Jingsheng, a former electrician at the Beijing Zoo. He was sentenced
to 15 years in jail in 1979 on charges of supplying military secrets
to a foreign power and agitating to topple the Chinese communist
system.
   The government, however, generally has attempted to show leniency
toward Fang in an effort to improve the country's image.
   When reporters last year suggested his apartment on the Beijing
University campus was too small, authorities immediately gave him
new quarters about twice the size.
   ``They want to use me. I know that,'' Fang said. ``On one side
they don't like me, they criticize me. (On) the other side, they
want to show they are open.''
   The official Beijing Review in May published a lengthy feature on
Fang and other official media ran articles about his scientific
work. But the Hong Kong-based newspaper South China Morning Post
says Chinese publications recently were instructed not to mention
the professor's name.
   Fang was born to the family of a postal clerk in the southern
coastal city of Hangzhou and was admitted to Beijing University in
1952, at age 16, to study physics and nuclear reactor theory.
   He became one of China's pioneer researchers in laser theory and
won international attention with his research in cosmology, the
study of the universe.
   Fang said his break with Marxism began over cosmology.
   According to the professor, former Politburo member Hu Qiaomu had
questioned the need to study cosmology since Marxism already
maintained the universe was infinite.
   ``This is an open question right now,'' Fang said. ``In
cosmology, Marxism is not right.''
   Fang lives with his wife, Li Shuxian, a professor of physics at
Beijing University, and the younger of their two sons in an
apartment about 780 square feet in size _ huge by Beijing standards.
   A poster of Albert Einstein hangs near the entrance and the
apartment has a new personal computer and a video cassette recorder
_ both rare items in China.
   Fang, who earns $73 a month, receives $2,688 a year for research.
He devotes much of his energy to writing scientific papers, and the
14 published this year include ``Physics and Beauty'' and ``Why
Doesn't the Universe Go Into Heat Death?''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
