<FILEID>AP-NR-11-07-88 0036EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-HouseRdp     11-07 0882</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-House Rdp,870</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Likely Bush Win Seen Helping Few GOP House Hopefuls</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Election Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Knox White wants the good people of South
Carolina's 4th Congressional District to think of him every time
they hear George Bush's name _ a strategy many Republican hopefuls
are pursuing this year.
   White, 34, a city councilman from Greenville, S.C., is trying to
oust freshman Democratic Rep. Liz Patterson in a district that the
GOP presidential nominee is expected to sweep.
   So White's speeches and advertisements are studded with
references to the vice president and, like Bush, he repeatedly
pledges to oppose tax increases, protect jobs and battle illegal
drugs.
   ``Every Republican south of Washington, D.C., is linking himself
to George Bush,'' says White's campaign manager, Bob Knight.
   Maybe so. But on the eve of what national polls indicate is
likely to be a Bush victory over Democrat Michael Dukakis, few
people expect either candidate to provide much of a boost to more
than a few House hopefuls.
   Politicians and observers unanimously expect the House to remain
solidly Democratic, whatever the presidential race's outcome. And
they agree that if Bush wins and if he pulls GOP House contenders to
victory at all, it is likely to be in only a handful of races
scattered across the country, mainly in the conservative South.
   ``As George Bush does better, it helps the image of the
Republican Party,'' says North Carolina GOP chairman Jack Hawke, in
whose state there are four tight House races. ``But in the past we
just haven't seen coattails that significantly in North Carolina.''
   For the coattail effect to work, a presidential candidate must be
so appealing that he draws large numbers of people to the polls who
dutifully vote for other candidates of the same party.
   But in recent decades, strict party-line voting has been going
the way of candidates who lack blow-dried coiffures.
   Beginning with President Eisenhower's re-election in 1956, more
than one quarter of the country's 435 House districts have voted for
one party for president and the other party for its representative.
In 1984, such ticket splitting between the presidential and House
candidates occurred in 196 districts, or 45 percent.
   ``Most House races are pretty insulated from the presidential
election,'' says spokeswoman Peggy Connolly of the Democratic
Congressional Campaign Committee.
   The reasons are many. Increasing numbers of voters identify
themselves as independents, and often decide congressional races on
local issues, not national ones. And incumbents of both parties
usually enjoy insurmountable fund-raising advantages and represent
districts drawn to maximize their re-election prospects.
   Not only do most House incumbents seeking re-election win these
days _ the success rate was 98 percent in 1986 _ but they are doing
it so convincingly that they are usually invulnerable to defeat by
their party's presidential candidate.
   Two years ago, nearly nine out of every 10 incumbents were
re-elected with at least 60 percent of the major party vote, putting
them far out of range of the 1 or 2 percent vote swing that a strong
presidential candidate can bring to House contenders on his ticket.
   ``For there to be coattails this year, it would have to be in a
race that's very close and in an area where Bush will do very
well,'' says Martin Wattenberg, a political science professor at the
University of California at Irvine who studies voting behavior.
``We're talking about a pretty minimal impact there.''
   Political pros on both sides say about a dozen such races do
exist. Besides the contest between White and Patterson _ who
mentions Dukakis' name as infrequently as possible _ others where
presidential coattails might help are Republican Lyons Gray's bid to
oust Democratic Rep. Stephen Neal in North Carolina's 5th District;
GOP Rep. John Hiler's fight to hold off Democratic challenger Tom
Ward in the Indiana 3rd; and Democrat Harry Johnston's fight with
Republican Ken Adams to retain an open Democratic seat in the
Florida 14th.
   But even though Republicans might pick up a few seats this year
that may be attributed to Bush's victory, it is possible that for
the first time since 1960, the party that wins the presidential race
might suffer a net loss of seats in the House.
   That is largely because while the 70 contests considered
reasonably close are split evenly between Democratic and Republican
seats, the GOP holds 15 of the 27 open seats that are not being
defended by an incumbent. Open seats are where turnover from one
party to the other is most likely.
   It is even possible that in a losing effort, Dukakis might still
help Democrats in tight House races in New England, including
Democratic Rep. Fernand St Germain's effort to retain his 1st
District Rhode Island seat against Republican Ronald Machtley, and
Democrat James Donchess's fight for the open GOP seat in New
Hampshire's 2nd District against Republican Chuck Douglas.
   Since the Democrats lost 20 House seats when President Kennedy
was elected in 1960, the party of the winning presidential candidate
has picked up seats in the chamber every four years.
   Since then, the presidential year swings have ranged from the 38
seats the Democrats won in President Johnson's 1964 victory to the
two Democratic pickups that accompanied President Carter's 1976
triumph.
</TEXT>
