<1ST_LINE>r i PM-BRF--Gandhi     11-07 0170</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Gandhi,0173</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Indian Independence Leader Reinstated As Lawyer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Forty years after his death, Indian independence
leader Mohandas K. ``Mahatma'' Gandhi has been reinstated as a
lawyer by the legal society in London that disbarred him in 1922, a
member of the society said.
   Gandhi, who protested British colonial rule with a campaign of
passive resistance, was arrested and imprisoned in India several
times in the 1920s. Because of that he was disbarred in 1922 by the
Inner Temple, one of the four Inns of Court with exclusive right to
call lawyers to the English bar.
   Gandhi was reinstated Sunday, the 100th anniversary of the start
of his legal career at the Inner Temple. Patrick Sheehan of the
legal society said the posthumous reinstatement indicated a changed
point of view.
   ``I believe people weren't used to the idea of the revolting
dominions, colonies, seeking their independence in that way,'' he
said.
   Gandhi was assassinated in 1948 by a Hindu nationalist. India
gained its independence the previous year.
</TEXT>
