<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Veterans-Cost     11-07 0562</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Veterans-Cost,560</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>VA Expansion Will Cost More Than $9 Million</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM AHERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Changing the Veterans Administration into the
Department of Veterans Affairs may be relatively cheap as government
programs go, but officials say it will still cost upwards of $9
million over the next decade.
   Much of that money will go for new signs and stationery for the
government's fifth-largest agency, according to officials from the
VA and the Congressional Budget Office.
   But ``given the relative size, the cost impact isn't expected to
be significant, particularly in any one given year,'' said Nina
Shepard, the CBO analyst who helped develop the cost projections.
   When the new department comes into being next March 15, it will
be little different from the current VA, according to Bonner Day, a
spokesman for the agency.
   ``I don't think much has to be done before March 15. The
essential duties have not been changed. The biggest difference is
that the head of the agency will now be a member of the Cabinet,''
he explained.
   The agency won't move from any of its more than 500 buildings
around the country, nor will its operations be greatly affected.
   ``Really, except for the different name and what that requires,
we'll be the same as we are now,'' he explained. ``I don't think you
will see changes day to day.''
   What is required by the name change are new signs _ thousands of
them _ along with stationery with the new name.
   The VA has a $30 billion annual budget, much of which is
disbursed in payments to the nation's veterans. There are about 27
million veterans and 49 million dependents of veterans or survivors,
although only about 2.5 to 3 million use VA services on a regular
basis.
   The bill creating the Department of Veterans Affairs as the 14th
seat in the Cabinet was signed by President Reagan on Oct. 25,
shortly after it had been given overwhelming approval by both the
House and Senate.
   Veterans organizations had long had the bill at the top of their
legislative agenda and said moving the agency into the Cabinet would
elevate the status of veterans.
   The VA is estimating a cost of $9.8 million for the switch,
including $8.5 million for signs and the rest for changing
stationary and the names on veterans publications.
   The signs will have to be changed at the more than 500 VA
buildings around the country, Day said. The VA is still trying to
figure out just exactly how many new signs it will need.
   The VA doesn't plan to change all its signs or buy new stationery
right away, Ms. Shepard said. ``We tried to find out the number of
signs, but they didn't have an exact figure at hand.''
   ``As the old stationary runs out, they will buy new stuff,'' she
said. Similarly, the signs will be redone over the next five years.
   During the congressional debate over changing the VA's status,
some legislators said the total cost might be $33 million, far
higher than the $9.8 million figure.
   But that estimate was for a different bill, which would have
substantially expanded the staff of the agency's inspector general
department, the office which guards against wrongdoing. The bulk of
the additional money would have gone to hire new staff members, Ms.
Shepard said. Those provisions were dropped.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
