<DOCNO> AP881107-0017 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-07-88 0047EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-PresidentialPolls     11-07 0830</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Presidential Polls,810</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Leads in National Polls; Margin Ranges from Five to 12</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Election Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GARY LANGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A barrage of pre-election polls has given George
Bush a lead for popular votes in the presidential contest and an
even greater advantage in the more critical race for electoral votes.
   With Election Day looming, a 50-state poll by ABC News and The
Washington Post put 25 states firmly in Bush's column and another 16
leaning his way. Only the District of Columbia was firm for Democrat
Michael Dukakis.
   Though the poll did not jibe with all other individual state
assessments, it assigned Bush a daunting lead: His 25 firm states
alone would provide more than the 270 electoral votes needed for
election.
   In national popularity, the ABC-Post poll gave Bush a 10-point
lead among likely voters, 54-44 percent. Gallup found Bush up by 12
points, a CBS News poll said nine points and a USA Today-CNN poll
said 11. NBC News-Wall Street Journal and Harris polls found a
closer race, with a 5-point Bush lead.
   The differing results indicated continuing indecision and
dissatisfaction among some voters, factors that can accentuate the
effect of differences in polling dates and methods, such as
identifying likely voters.
   There was room for movement: One in five respondents in the
Gallup and NBC-Journal polls were undecided or said they could
change their minds, and in Gallup's poll only about half of each
candidate's support was strong.
   Gallup, however, said its undecided respondents appeared likely
to split evenly, on the basis of their background and ideology.
   Voter dissatisfaction was clear. Two-thirds in the NBC-Journal
poll said the campaign was one of the worst in recent history, as
many were unhappy with the nominees' discussion of the issues and
six in 10 said they wished other candidates were running.
   As it was, Bush led in most ratings on presidential ability.
Likely voters by 62-25 percent said he would be better able to
maintain a strong defense, and he outranked Dukakis on crime, the
economy and foreign policy.
   The ABC-Post's state-by-state poll underlined the difficulty of
Dukakis' position: He needed to win all his firm and leaning states,
all the tossup states, all the leaning Bush states and at least one
firm Bush state.
   The poll, conducted by re-interviewing most of the respondents in
a 50-state survey in early October, found 17 states moving toward
Bush and only three moving toward Dukakis. The number of states
firmly or leaning for Dukakis actually declined from eight to four.
   The results did not agree with all recent state polls. New York
was rated as leaning to Bush, for example, although a recent state
poll put Dukakis slightly ahead in New York. Washington state also
was said to be leaning for Bush, although a poll there last week put
Dukakis ahead by 10 points.
   USA Today and CNN conducted five separate state polls, finding
Bush ahead in California, 54-45; in Ohio, 58-42; and in
Pennsylvania, 53-46. It was about even in Illinois, 51-48 for Bush,
and Michigan, 51-49 for Bush.
   Although the other new national surveys were not large enough for
state-by-state results, Gallup found the race tight in the East and
Bush leading strongly in all other regions, particularly the South.
The closer NBC-Journal poll found Bush leading well in the South and
West with tight races in the East and Midwest.
   In popularity nationwide, the ABC-Post poll found a slight
decline from a 13-point Bush lead late last month. The other polls
Sunday also found some tightening, although they disagreed on its
extent.
   The ABC-Post poll was weighted to an effective sample size of
1,500 likely voters for the national popularity figure, with a
margin of error of plus or minus three points. Margins of error
varied state-by-state, and ABC made characterizations of the state
results without releasing numbers.
   In addition to the District of Columbia firmly for Dukakis, it
said Hawaii, Massachusetts and Minnesota were leaning his way.
Tossups were Illinois, Oregon, Pennsylvania, Rhode Island, Vermont
and West Virginia.
   Leaning for Bush were Alabama, Colorado, Iowa, Kansas, Louisiana,
New York, Maine, Maryland, Michigan, Montana, Mississippi, Nebraska,
Nevada, Oklahoma, Tennessee and Washington. The rest were rated as
firm for Bush.
   NBC and the Journal polled 1,721 likely voters Tuesday through
Saturday; Gallup, 1,969 Thursday through Saturday; Harris, 2,114
Wednesday through Saturday; CBS, 1,585 Friday and Saturday; USA
Today-CNN 2,506 nationally and about 500 in each of the five states,
Thursday through Sunday.
   The Gallup and Harris polls had margins of error of plus or minus
two percentage points; the NBC-Journal and CBS polls, three points;
the USA Today-CNN polls, two points for the national sample, four
for the states.
   In addition to the ABC-Post finding of 54-44 percent Bush, the
numerical results were: USA Today-CNN, 55-44; Gallup, 53-41; CBS,
51-42; Harris, 50-45; NBC-Journal, 48-43. All included leaning
voters except the NBC-Journal poll; including them, its result was
50-45.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
