<2ND_LINE>PM-Farm Briefs,240</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jamaica Will Neld Help Restoring Poultry Flock</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jamaica's poultry flock was almost wiped out in
mid-September by Hurricane Gilbert, and the Agriculture Department
says the Caribbean nation will need additional aid to get it
reestablished.
   A report by the department's Economic Research Service says only
about 150,000 of Jamaica's normal flock of 5 million birds were
spared by the storm. Beef and dairy operations apparently were
damaged less severely, but heavy losses were reported for crops,
including sugar cane, bananas and tree products.
   Poultry accounts for nearly 60 percent of the meat consumption of
Jamaica's 2.5 million people. About 60 percent is produced
domestically, the rest from imports, mainly from the United States.
   Loans under various USDA credit programs have been stepped up to
help Jamaica buy food, breeding stock, hatching eggs and other items
needed to recover from the storm, the agency said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   This year is the 30th anniversary of the first
sales of instant noodles in Japan, and a report from Tokyo says the
noodles have become a regular part of the Japanese diet and
lifestyle.
   Originally a snack food for children, the noodles _ known as
ramen _ now are consumed at the annual rate of 4.5 billion packets,
based on 1987 figures by the Japan Instant Food Industry Association.
   The report said that Japanese men, on the average, consume 3.7
packets a month; women, 2.8; and young people, 4.6. Overall, the
instant noodles make up an estimated 5 percent of Japanese food
expenditures.
</TEXT>
