<1ST_LINE>r i PM-NewCaledonia     11-07 0482</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-New Caledonia,0495</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>French Voters Approve Plan For New Caledonia, But White Islanders
Vote No</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFFREY ULBRICH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   French voters have approved a program to grant more
autonomy to New Caledonia and permit an independence referendum in
1998 on the South Pacific territory, but turnout was light and many
white islanders voted no.
   The government of Socialist Premier Michel Rocard is hoping the
statute, which passed Sunday, will buy 10 years of peace in the
islands that have suffered from intercommunal violence since 1984.
   The statute includes a development program for native Melanesians.
   With all votes in except from a few Caribbean territories, 80
percent of the vote was in favor of the new statute and 20 percent
against. Turnout, however, was a mere 37.3 percent, the worst
showing for any national election since the end of World War II.
   The archipelago of New Caledonia, 11,000 miles from Paris, has
been rent by periodic violence between the native Melanesians, known
as Kanaks, and white European settlers.
   Kanaks, most of whom favor independence, make up 43 percent of
New Caledonia's 145,000 inhabitants. The settlers, most of whom want
to remain French, are 37 percent. The rest of the population is made
up of Polynesians and Asians, who generally favor France.
   After another round of violence last spring that left 25 people
dead, Kanak leader Jean-Marie Tjibaou and Jacques Lafleur, leader of
the anti-independence forces, signed an agreement with Rocard on the
island's future.
   Tjibaou and Lafleur demanded a referendum to seal the deal.
   But Tjibaou, Lafleur and Rocard did not get strong national
backing for their plan. Only 14.5 million of France's 38 million
voters cast ballots. And of them, 13 percent cast blank or invalid
ballots.
   In New Caledonia itself, turnout was much higher at 63.7 percent,
but the approval much less. ``Yes'' received 57.03 percent and
``no'' 42.9. The opposition vote was largely in the south, where
most of the European population lives. In Noumea, the capital and
white settler heartland, 63.7 percent voted against the plan.
   ``Democracy has spoken,'' Rocard said after the polls closed.
``It appears that 12 million French have just approved the statute.
This statute is from now on the law of France.''
   The draft law voted on in the referendum proposes a new local
autonomy statute for New Caledonia, the seventh since the end of
World War II. It divides the archipelago into three provinces, each
with its own provincial assembly and local administration.
   The law also provides amnesty for any person charged with actions
of a political nature before Aug. 20, except murder.
   It also provides for a program of economic development in
Melanesian areas and training of local residents to assume
administrative tasks.
   Tjibaou admitted that the 42.9 percent ``no'' vote ``is very
large. It is a significant handicap for the future. We must be very
vigilant.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
