<1ST_LINE>r a PM-People-Kean-Dog     11-07 0353</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-People-Kean-Dog,0365</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New Jersey Governor Steps In To Save Dog</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MILFORD, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 125-pound Great Dane named Cinnamon has
Gov. Thomas H. Kean to thank for a reprieve of sorts that allowed it
to stay with its family.
   An insurance company had told William and Tina Slack they either
had to get rid of the dog or stop operating a day care center in
their home.
   Branchville-based Selective Insurance Co. of America told the
Slacks a large dog like Cinnamon might endanger young children, Mrs.
Slack said Sunday.
   ``Basically, their hands were tied,'' she said of the company.
``They didn't have much choice as far as the law is concerned.''
   She said no other insurance company would talk to them about a
day-care policy except Selective, and the family had to think of a
solution.
   The family needed the money from the day-care operation to help
pay the mortgage on their new house, Mrs. Slack said. Her husband is
a pastor.
   Faced with the thought of life without Cinnamon, their daughter,
11-year-old Kristy, wrote a letter to Kean and started what has
become known as the ``Cinnamon Affair.''
   A week later, the Slacks received a letter from the governor's
office, which said they could expect to hear about the case in a few
days, Mrs. Slack said.
   But Kristy grew impatient, called the office and was told that
her case had been sent to a higher state official.
   A few days later, Mrs. Slack said, the family received a personal
phone call from Kean, who told them a compromise had been worked out
and they could keep the 3-year-old dog.
   The family will have to keep her in a kennel in the backyard when
children are being cared for.
   Kean placed a few calls to state Insurance Commissioner Kenneth
Merin and Selective Insurance Co. executives, said Carl Golden, the
governor's press secretary.
   ``Here was a case that the governor felt was something that he
could involve himself in and hopefully bring it to a successful
conclusion, which he did,'' Golden said, who added that Kean is a
long-time dog lover.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
