<HEAD>Third-Ranking Communist Official Reported Arrested</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: CORRECTS spelling of Capegsan thruout and LEADS with 5 grafs
to UPDATE with conflicting reports on whether he bound for Los
Angeles. Picks up 6th graf pvs, `Aguirre said ...'</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The third-ranking leader of the
outlawed Communist Party of the Philippines was arrested at Manila's
airport on Sunday, authorities announced.
   Brig. Gen. Alexander Aguirre, capital regional commander, said
Ignacio Capegsan, allegedly the party's deputy secretary-general,
was planning to board a flight for Los Angeles.
   ``He was on his way to the USA, particularly Los Angeles,''
Aguirre said. ``It is possible that he is being projected into the
international commission of the Communist Party of the Philippines.''
   But a military official, quoting an intelligence report, said
Capegsan was at Ninoy Aquino International Airport to see off a
woman friend who was on her way to California.
   The official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said the
report did not say whether the woman was arrested. Aguirre said
Capegsan was carrying documents identifying him as a ``Mr. Beltran.''
   Military officials have claimed rebel representatives are raising
funds among Filipino expatriate communities abroad to finance the
19-year-old Communist insurgency. Aguirre said Capegsan was carrying
travel documents identifying him as a ``Mr. Beltran.''
   Aguirre said that following the arrest, troops raided a suspected
rebel ``safe house'' early Monday in suburban Quezon City and seized
bank books, computer diskettes and other records.
   Aguirre said he reported the arrest to President Corazon Aquino,
who has vowed to crush the rebel movement before her term expires in
1992.
   Capegsan was the highest-ranking member of the party to be
arrested since secretary-general Rafael Baylosis was captured in
March.
   He was believed to be a member of the party's ruling Political
Bureau and central committee. He was also chairman of the party's
Northern Luzon Commission, which directs rebel operations in the
northern Philippines.
   Capegsan was the seventh member of the central committee arrested
this year, according to the military. Longtime party leader Rudolfo
Salas was arrested in September 1986.
   Last month, a Philippine court issued an arrest warrant charging
that the founder of the party, Jose Marie Sison, had resumed its
leadership.
   Sison was jailed in the 1970s but released by Mrs. Aquino in
March 1986. He left the country the following September and remains
in Western Europe, where he issued a statement denying having
resumed party leadership.
</TEXT>
