<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Quayle     11-07 0643</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Quayle,630</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Quayle Calls Dukakis Inexperienced</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Election Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: Prenoon lede uncertain; Quayle has late morning plant tour in
Baltimore.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Dan Quayle is calling Democrat Michael
Dukakis ``the frightening candidate'' for president, saying Dukakis
has no foreign policy credentials.
   Answering questions Sunday as he entered the homestretch of the
1988 campaign, Quayle said he was offended by Dukakis' suggestion
that he would be unfit to head a White House crisis management team
in a Bush administration.
   The GOP vice presidential candidate said that Dukakis ``has
absolutely no experience in foreign policy. The only foreign policy
he's had is conversing with the governor of New Hampshire.''
   The Indiana senator struck back at Dukakis a day after the
Democratic standard-bearer said the notion of Quayle involved in
sensitive national security matters was ``a frightening thing.''
   Quayle scheduled a tour of a Westinghouse plant near Baltimore
today before flying to Roanoke, Va., for a rally and then to his
home state of Indiana.
   Quayle was rounding out his campaign with an appearance in South
Bend, Ind. He planned to dine privately with family and friends in
Indianapolis tonight, cast his ballot and return here Tuesday night
to await the election results.
   While carrying out a modest campaign schedule consisting of an
appearance at the historic Berkeley Plantation in southeastern
Virginia Sunday, Quayle was asked at several points if the Bush
campaign organization was intentionally giving him a low-profile
schedule in the campaign's waning days.
   ``I think you probably better unfog your glasses,'' he told a
bespectacled reporter who raised the question. ``I'm right here.
We're very versatile, very flexible. We go to good ones (solid
Republican states), bad ones (Democratic states) and in between.
Wherever they say.''
   The question was raised because Quayle in recent days has made
appearances in mostly small media markets and, with the exception of
Kentucky, Maryland and West Virginia, states considered safely in
the Republican column.
   Bush spokesman Mark Goodin, who accompanied Quayle on the
Virginia trip, said that sending the senator into traditionally
strong Republican states is part of a strategy, not to hide Quayle,
but to have the senator work to keep Republican backers from taking
Bush's election for granted.
   Quayle's ire was raised by statements that Dukakis made in
response to questions in an Associated Press interview. The governor
was asked about what he thought about Bush's suggestion, in an
interview with British television personality David Frost, that he
would put Quayle in charge of a crisis management team, if elected.
   ``Dan Quayle?'' Dukakis asked.``In charge of managing the most
serious crises we face in the country? That's a frightening thing,
isn't it.''
   Quayle, standing next to his plane before commencing his campaign
activities Sunday, snapped back. ``Well, the frightening thought is
President Michael Dukakis. He is truly the frightening candidate.
... He's the one that's truly frightening in the area of foreign
policy in any kind of crisis.''
   Asked what he would do if put in charge of a crisis management
team in a Bush administration, Quayle said only, ``Same thing George
Bush has done.''
   President Reagan gave Bush a similar assignment early in his
administration in a move that contributed to Alexander M. Haig Jr.'s
resignation as secretary of state. There has been little definitive
record of what Bush did in that capacity, although he has been
credited by some in the administration as having played a principal
role in overseeing the U.S. invasion of Grenada.
   Quayle said last week he thought he could be a valuable foreign
policy adviser to Bush because of his service on congressional
foreign affairs committees. Sen. Phil Gramm, R-Texas, appearing with
Quayle at a campaign rally in Louisiana, credited the Indiana
senator with helping to get the Intermediate-range Nuclear Forces
(INF) treaty ratified by the Senate.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
