<1ST_LINE>r a PM-DivorceLawyers     11-07 0446</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Divorce Lawyers,0458</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Divorce Lawyers Give Thumbs Down To Arnie Becker of ``L.A. Law''</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Divorce lawyer Arnie Becker may be a hotshot
attorney in the fictional legal world of television's ``L.A. Law,''
but his real-life peers say they wouldn't want to invite him to join
their group.
   After a panel discussion titled ``Arnie Becker _ How Real is
He?'' members of the American Academy of Matrimonial Lawyers voted
50-14 against the notion of extending an invitation to Becker to
join their association.
   The hypothetical matter came up Saturday at the start of a
four-day meeting devoted mostly to weightier issues, such as custody
and surrogacy, and the economic hardships that no-fault divorce have
caused some women.
   But Leonard Loeb, president of the academy, credits Becker's
character with raising awareness of the legal specialty. However, he
said it's impossible to know whether the character actually has
influenced members of the profession.
   ``The character is bigger than life, but not unreal,'' said Loeb.
   ``And we're up closer than most people. We see the warts and
freckles, we understand many of the things he goes through. I
suppose the jury is still out, to what extent the portrayal has
helped.''
   Among those sitting in on the Becker panel was Bill Finkelstein,
an ``L.A. Law'' story editor and producer who writes Becker's
character, played by actor Corbin Bernsen, for the NBC-TV show.
   ``I'm not comfortable thinking about Arnie or any other character
strictly as a role model, because dramatically, that's too limiting
a standard to hold him to,'' said Finkelstein, an attorney who put
aside his practice while working on ``L.A. Law.''
   ``Like everybody else, Arnie has different sides, some heroic and
some anything but heroic. Arnie has done things that if someone I
knew in real life had, I'd say, `What a jerk!'
   ``By the same token,'' Finkelstein said, ``he's done some things
I greatly admire. And in this company, in dress, behavior and other
measures, I'd say he's basically middle of the pack. There are a
fair share of matrimonial lawyers more flamboyant than Arnie.''
   Needless to say, the vote probably won't affect Becker's
television following.
   Besides, fictional characters cannot join the elite academy,
which is comprised of only about 1,000 of the nation's 40,000
divorce lawyers. The American Bar Association's Family Law Section,
by contrast, has about 16,000 members.
   Despite the turndown, one thing Becker still has going for him is
the perception that ``L.A. Law'' has not only glamorized the
business, but has encouraged more young people to enroll in law
school.
   ``Enrollment is definitely up,'' said Finkelstein, ``but I don't
know whether that means I get the credit or the blame.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
