<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Lites     11-07 0435</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lites,0452</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>On The Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   If kids could vote, George Bush and Michael
Dukakis would have a hard time matching 9-year-old Joseph Norfleet's
presidential platform: turn the White House into a toy factory.
   ``Instead of congressmen going to meetings, they would be busy
making my tops,'' Joseph wrote.
   Child's Play, a theater troupe, turned Joseph's and other
children's musings on what they would do as president into a stage
production at the Goodman Studio Theater on Saturday.
   And what would they do?
   Rig lotteries so their friends would get rich; hold school only
three times a week; hire an expert chef to prepare school lunches;
elect Chicago Bulls basketball star Michael Jordan mayor of Chicago;
and end federal ``spending on dumb things.''
   Shalita Boyle, a seventh-grader from suburban Crestwood, said if
she were chief executive for a day, said she'd go shopping and have
the taxpayers pick up the tab.
   Since none of them will be president in 1988, what would the
youngsters tell Bush and Dukakis if they met them?
   ``That's easy,'' said Joseph. ``I think they shouldn't make
promises they can't keep.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CAVE IN ROCK, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Not much traffic flows through this
sleepy town on the Ohio River, but a rock store on its main drag
boasts worldwide, mail-order sales that owners claim make it a gold
mine.
   ``We've got the best business in town, and people from around
here don't even know it,'' Larry Palmer, 23, said of Palmer's
Trading Post, which he and his father, John, operate in this
community of 468 people.
   ``Rocks are a good business. You'd be surprised.''
   John Palmer established the store about 18 years ago to get away
from the dangers of fluorite mining. Rocks always had fascinated
him, and he collected enough in his 16 years as a miner to go into
business.
   Finding a beautiful rock is like ``looking at a beautiful
woman,'' he said recently. ``You go, `Wow!' That's why people
collect rocks.''
   Most of the Trading Post's rocks come from the area. They carry
prices ranging from 50 cents to $4,000 and weigh up to 200 pounds.
The Palmers rely mostly on local miners to help the store maintain a
rock inventory in the thousands.
   ``What's so amazing about our little store here,'' Larry Palmer
said, ``is we can sit here all winter long and the only one who
comes here is the (mail carrier), and we're still making a living.
   ``I just bought me a new car,'' he said. ``I've got one of the
best jobs a guy in this country could have.''
</TEXT>
