<2ND_LINE>PM-Cutting Back, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0448,0595</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Strapped School System Endures Fall Without Football</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS last graf to CORRECT attribution to Winters sted Stiller.
A version moving on sports wires</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto CD1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOE McDONALD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLUMBIANA, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The football practice field at Columbiana
High School is choked with foot-high grass this fall because
financial problems have sidelined the football squad and other
extracurricular activities.
   ``We don't have a student newspaper, we don't have plans for a
yearbook, we don't have any sports. Right now we are not planning on
a prom,'' said Charles A. Winters, principal at the town's
350-student high school.
   The 1,200 students in Columbiana schools in northeastern Ohio
have lost extracurricular activities this school year because voters
have rejected six tax levies since 1986.
   A school tax increase is on Tuesday's ballot.
   Other school systems in Ohio have cut back sports because of
money woes, but the Ohio High School Athletic Association said
Columbiana is the state's only district without athletics this year.
   As a result, about eight athletes transferred to other school
systems, said Superintendent Roger Stiller. The latest departure was
by a basketball player last week, he said.
   Winters, who went to the University of Pittsburgh on a football
scholarship, said cutbacks in sports and other school programs could
hurt some students' chances to win scholarships and admission to
college.
   Senior Sheli Farran, who has played on the basketball, volleyball
and softball teams, said the loss of high school activities has left
Columbiana teen-agers without much to do in their spare time in this
rural village of 4,900 residents near Youngstown.
   ``It seems like you just come here, you go to school, and then
you go home and you have to find your own thing to do,'' she said.
``There's a movie theater, but you can only see the same movie so
many times ... really there's nothing for the kids in this town.''
   School districts on the East and West coasts generally have
avoided such cuts because of strong local economies, but in the
Midwest, where regions are suffering from stagnant economies, cuts
in sports, music and drama are more common, said John Myers, a
spokesman for the Denver-based National Conference of State
Legislatures.
   ``We have had the southern oil-producing and (midwestern)
agricultural areas show sharply declining property tax revenues,
which presents the schools with less money to spend on activities,''
he said.
   Myers said there are also efforts in some states to mandate a
limit on property taxes, thus reducing the amount of money available
to schools.
   Columbiana school officials first made the cuts in 1986.
   But a group of parents raised $92,000 to cover the cost of the
threatened activities through last school year, paying for coaches,
sports equipment and a choir director with the donations, Winters
said.
   ``The whole time they were saying, `This is a one time shot for
us, we can't do this again, so we need your support and we need this
levy passed,''' he said.
   Stiller said the average homeowner in the district pays $600 to
$650 in property taxes to the schools, which he said is about
average in the state.
   ``I guess what we have here is a real division in the community
between people who want those activities and people who either don't
care or don't want them,'' Winters said. ``Folks who don't have kids
or whose kids aren't involved don't really see that as a part of
education, I guess.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
