<HEAD>Imelda Marcos Arrives In California</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 4 grafs to UPDATE with more details on arrival in
California; officials not confirming destination of Hawaii; CORRECT
time of landing; picks up 4th graf pvs, `Miss Duke ...'</NOTE>
<DATELINE>SAN JOSE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A private jet owned by tobacco heiress
Doris Duke brought former Philippine first lady Imelda Marcos here
Sunday night.
   The Boeing 737 landed at San Jose International Airport about 8
p.m., said Griz Gotschall, the airport's operations supervisor.
   After the plane landed, Mrs. Marcos got into a private car and
drove away, Gotschall said. He said he didn't know when she would
leave or if she planned to head back to Hawaii.
   The plane left Morristown Airport in New Jersey on Sunday
afternoon. Mrs. Marcos had been staying with Miss Duke, who has a
1,200-acre estate at Hillsborough, N.J., after pleading innocent in
U.S. District Court in New York City to racketeering charges last
week.
   Miss Duke has an unlisted telephone number and could not be
reached for comment at her Hillsborough home.
   Mrs. Marcos and her husband, former Philippine President
Ferdinand Marcos, are accused of looting more than $100 million from
their homeland, funneling it to foreign bank accounts and using it
to buy prime New York City real estate and art.
   Marcos, 71, remained in Hawaii, where the couple has lived since
their ouster from the Philippines in 1986. His lawyers said he was
too ill to travel.
   Miss Duke and Mrs. Marcos are said to be old friends, and the New
Jersey millionaire posted more than $5 million bail for the former
first lady.
</TEXT>
