<1ST_LINE>r p PM-GovernorsRdp     11-07 0563</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Governors Rdp,0577</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Democratic Challenger Draws Even In R.I. Race For Governor</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FLIPPEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrat Bruce Sundlun, hurling
allegations of unethical conduct, has battled to a dead heat against
Republican Gov. Edward DiPrete, and kept up the attack in an
eleventh-hour gubernatorial debate.
   Turning around a question on education Sunday, the millionaire
communications executive said: ``I think you ought to start
educating our children on the need for honesty and integrity in
state government. Ethics _ it's taught in the sixth grade.''
   Rhode Island is one of 12 states selecting governors Tuesday.
Democrats are given a good chance of retaking the office in Utah,
West Virginia and Indiana. Nine incumbents _ six Republicans and
three Democrats _ are on ballots.
   The gubernatorial race here is the most expensive in Rhode Island
history, with each candidate spending about $2 million. Sundlun, 68,
has contributed $1.9 million out of his own pocket.
   Sundlun, who lost to DiPrete by a landslide in 1986, robbed the
two-term governor of an early, commanding lead by raising questions
about DiPrete's private business deals, alleged favoritism in the
awarding of state contracts and the hiring last month of the ex-wife
of a reputed mobster for a state job.
   DiPrete, 54, has stressed the state's economic recovery in his
four years in office, citing increased spending on education and day
care and challenging Sundlun on Sunday to say what he would do
differently. He has also accused his opponent of business misconduct
and mismanagement.
   A WLNE-TV poll Friday and Saturday gave Sundlun 44 percent to 43
percent for DiPrete. A WPRI-TV poll Wednesday and Thursday gave
DiPrete 47 percent to Sundlun's 46 percent. Both surveys had margins
of error of roughly 5 points.
   ``We've seen all this negativeness and I think that adds a new
dimension to the undecided vote,'' said Brown University political
science professor Darrell West. ``They're not going to be able to
resolve their indecision because neither of the candidates has given
them a reason to vote for them.''
   Pollsters said undecided voters were relying on Sunday's hastily
arranged, televised debate to help them make up their minds, but
neither candidate took the experts' advice that Sundlun talk issues
and DiPrete confront the ethics questions.
   ``We're here today to talk about issues,'' said the governor,
accused by Sundlun of using his political influence in a family land
deal that netted him $400,000. ``I think the public is fed up with
your mudslinging, quite frankly.''
   Sundlun, who has attacked DiPrete for increasing spending 45
percent, appeared nonplussed and had to grope for an answer when
DiPrete asked him, ``What would you cut?'' The Democrat said he
would stop hiring outside lawyers for state business and reduce
spending by the governor's office.
   Elsewhere, West Virginia Gov. Arch Moore, a Republican, trailed
far behind Democrat Gaston Caperton; Democrat Evan Bayh, the son of
former U.S. Sen. Birch E. Bayh, led GOP Lt. Gov. John M. Mutz in
Indiana; and in Utah, Gov. Norm Bangerter erased a 30-point deficit
to draw even with Democrat Ted Wilson.
   Democrats hold 27 of the 50 governorships. Republican Robert Orr
of Indiana is barred by law from a third term; Montana Democrat Ted
Schwinden and New Hampshire Republican John Sununu are retiring.
Other states holding gubernatorial elections are Delaware, North
Carolina, Missouri, North Dakota, Vermont and Washington.
</TEXT>
