<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BoringJail     11-07 0286</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Boring Jail,0294</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man Asks For Prison Term, Says County Jail Too Dull</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PORT TOWNSEND, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 20-year-old man told a judge he
wants to serve time for car theft and forgery in prison because the
county jail is too boring.
   ``I can't sit that long in the county jail because it will drive
me crazy,'' Robert R. Couture said. ``There's nothing to do. If I go
to prison, I can go to school, I can get a job, go to work camp.''
   Couture asked Jefferson County Superior Court Judge William
Howard on Friday to delay his plea on three counts of forgery until
after Couture is sentenced in Snohomish County on a car theft charge.
   Jefferson County Deputy Prosecuting Attorney Steve Olsen said
Couture wanted to plead guilty to the car theft charge first so that
sentence will be added to his forgery sentence.
   Sentences over one year are served in state prisons, less than a
year in a county jail.
   Public defender Crad Verser told the court that the Snohomish
County prosecutor will recommend that Couture be sentenced to two
months in jail for the car theft. The standard range the court could
impose is two-to-five months.
   On the forgery charges, the most Couture could get is under 12
months, which would mean jail time.
   But with the sentences from both counties added together, Couture
could be sent to prison, for 12 to 14 months.
   Couture said he fears that if he had to languish in jail, he'd be
so restless he'd end up back in court on other charges before
completing his sentence.
   Howard accepted the two attorneys' recommendations and delayed
Couture's arraignment on the three forgery counts until January.
</TEXT>
