<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Hirohito Bjt   11-07 0429</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hirohito, Bjt,0442</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Emperor Stabilizes After His Most Serious Blood Loss; Grandson
Returns</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRIL JONES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Emperor Hirohito's vital signs stabilized today, one
day after his most serious loss of blood since falling ill seven
weeks ago with internal hemorrhaging, an imperial palace spokesman
said.
   The 87-year-old Hirohito, who has received almost daily blood
transfusions since he first coughed up blood Sept. 19, received 4.66
pints in emergency blood transfusions Sunday, spokesman Kenji Maeda
said.
   Also today Hirohito's second grandson, Prince Aya, arrived in
Tokyo after he was called back from Britain for the second time
since the emperor took ill. Aya, 22, is studying at Oxford
University.
   He returned to Japan at the end of September for nine days when
Hirohito's condition took a turn for the worse, and his latest
return was expected to fuel concern over the fate of the bedridden
emperor.
   The world's longest-reigning living monarch was ``in stable
condition for the time being,'' Maeda told reporters. But ``doctors
fear he may bleed again,'' he said.
   ``His temperature and other signs are stable,'' Maeda said, but
did not give the figures.
   Hirohito received the transfusions Sunday because of
``considerable'' amounts of blood lost during intensified
hemorrhaging, palace officials said.
   Kyodo News Service quoted palace sources as saying the emperor
discharged 56 ounces of blood Sunday.
   With the latest transfusions, the emperor has received a total of
40.16 pints of blood since September, more than three times the
blood circulating in his body.
   Doctors believe the emperor is bleeding in the upper intestinal
area, where he underwent a bypass operation in September last year.
   Hirohito's systolic blood pressure, which fell below the critical
level of 100 at one time Sunday, later recovered slightly but was
still well below the 150-point level of the past few days.
   The emperor's blood pressure was 116 over 56 this morning,
compared with 122 over 62 Sunday evening, Maeda said.
   Hirohito was ``awake and fully conscious'' in his room at the
Fukiage Palace, and had not discharged any blood today, the
spokesman said.
   Palace officials have refused to confirm or deny reports that
Hirohito has pancreatic cancer. ``We still don't know the exact
nature of the illness,'' said a senior palace spokesman, but ``the
illness is clearly progressing'' for the worse.
   Hirohito's son, Crown Prince Akihito, 54, has assumed imperial
duties that include placing an official seal on government documents
and meeting visiting dignitaries. Under Japan's constitution, the
emperor _ who was once worshiped as a god _ is a symbolic head of
state.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881107-0042 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-07-88 0550EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>d a PM-BRF--GasPrices     11-07 0138</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Gas Prices,0141</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Prices Rise for First Time Since August</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Motorists paid slightly more for gasoline
during the past two weeks because dealers passed on short-term cost
increases, an analyst says.
   The average price of gasoline for all grades and types of
services, including taxes, rose .2 cent a gallon to $1.0023 a gallon
between Oct. 21 and Nov. 4, Trilby Lundberg said Sunday.
   It was the first increase since the end of the summer driving
season, she said.
   The Lundberg Survey of 12,000 gasoline stations nationwide found
the following average prices for self-service, which accounts for
most gasoline sales: Regular unleaded, 90.77 cents a gallon; premium
unleaded, $1.0606 and regular leaded, 87.28 cents.
   Full service prices were $1.1958 a gallon for regular unleaded,
$1.3013 for premium unleaded and $1.1666 for regular leaded.
</TEXT>
