<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Bush-Arrest     11-07 0233</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bush-Arrest,230</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man With Starter Pistol Arrested At Bush Rally</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man was arrested at a rally for presidential
candidate George Bush when he dropped a starter pistol, frightening
observers who shouted ``There's a gun! There's a gun!''
   John Arthur Junot, 40, of Los Angeles, was taken into custody
Sunday for violation of a federal law against impeding or disrupting
government business, said Secret Service spokesman Richard Adams.
   Junot was about 50 yards away from the vice president, who was
addressing a suburban Los Angeles crowd of about 10,000 on gun
control, said witness Hank Rodriguez, an ex-police officer.
   ``I will not take away your guns,'' Bush said in his speech.
There was no indication Republican presidential nominee even noticed
the incident.
   Junot fled as frightened bystanders yelled that he had a weapon.
Police arrested him moments later, authorities said.
   Junot could be fined $500 and sentenced to a six months in prison
if convicted, Adams said.
   Sgt. Jim Thompson of the Los Angeles Police Department said the
starter pistol was the type normally used at track and field events
and resembles a handgun, although it fires only blanks.
   Junot, who had been trying to get closer to the stage, reached
for his waistband when the pistol fell to the ground, said Rodriguez.
   Rodriguez said Junot ran when some spectators began yelling,
``There's a gun. There's a gun.''
</TEXT>
