<DOCNO> AP881107-0046 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-07-88 0522EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Heroes     11-07 0653</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Heroes,0675</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Carnegie Fund Honors 16 Heroes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER MATTIACE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Truck driver Cecil Roy Taylor Sr. twice entered
a burning and overturned car to save an 8-month-old girl trapped
inside. Now, Taylor says modestly, ``It was the natural thing to
do.''
   Taylor and 15 other Americans and Canadians were honored as
heroes Sunday by the Carnegie Hero Fund Commission. Two died in the
performance of their heroic deeds.
   The heroes or their survivors received $2,500 and a medal from
the commission, which was founded by industrialist Andrew Carnegie
in 1904 to honor heroic American and Canadian civilians. The
commission has honored 7,274 people.
   Taylor, 37, of Hamilton, N.C., was driving his car along North
Carolina 903 on March 24 when he saw a car ahead ``sliding down the
highway.''
   Trapped in the rear seat was little Gerrikka Taylor, who is not
related.
   ``The car was burning when it stopped,'' Taylor recalled. ``A
woman kept hollering that her baby was in the car. I climbed through
the car window and I saw the youngster. Something blew up and I had
to get out.
   ``I got my hunting knife and went back in the car. I cut the
girl's seat loose and I handed her out. I had to break the front
seat to get out myself.''
   Taylor said he is not a hero.
   ``Everybody tries to tell me I'm a hero, but it just seemed like
something a human being should do,'' he said. ``It was the natural
thing to do.''
   Others honored by the commission are:
   _ Michael N. Knieriem, 46, of Thousand Oaks, Calif., who rescued
a 6-year-old girl and a 4-year-old boy from their burning
condominium in Newbury Park, Calif., on Oct. 2, 1987. Knieriem
suffered severe smoke inhalation.
   _ Bobby D. Ratliff, 44, and Kenneth G. Harlow, 45, both of Llano,
Texas, who rescued a woman, her 12-year-old boy and her 4-year-old
boy from their burning car after a June 12, 1987, traffic accident.
Harlow suffered minor burns.
   _ Christopher Bordeaux, 24, of Chicago, who died trying to save a
28-year-old woman who had fallen in the path of a speeding train at
Lake Forest, Ill., on Jan. 11. The woman also died.
   _ Philip Contreras, 26, of Huntington Beach, Calif., who saved a
59-year-old man from his burning car after a traffic accident in
Compton, Calif., on Aug. 27, 1987.
   _ Martin Lopez, 21, of Cuero, Texas, who saved a 10-year-old boy
from a burning apartment on Aug. 5, 1987.
   _ Grant P. Clemens, 32, of Oxnard, Calif., and Kenneth R.
Vandergrift, 40, of Santa Paula, Calif., who saved a 59-year-old man
from his burning car after a traffic accident in Saticoy, Calif., on
Dec. 9, 1987. Both men suffered burns.
   _ Steven Allen Grimm, 17, of Mishawaka, Ind., who saved a
10-year-old girl from her burning mobile home on Dec. 26, 1987.
Grimm suffered burns.
   _ Tommy James Russell, 18, of San Diego, who saved a 36-year-old
man from his burning car after a traffic accident in National City,
Calif., on July 24, 1987.
   _ Timothy J. Costello, 16, of Chula Vista, Calif., who saved a
12-year-old boy from drowning in the Pacific Ocean at Coronado,
Calif., on June 19, 1987.
   _ Adam Michael Calderon, 17, of Lake Elsinore, Calif., who saved
a 59-year-old woman from an attacking Doberman pinscher on Feb. 2.
Calderon suffered bites.
   _ Orville L. Parde, 46, of Adams, Neb., who saved a 32-year-old
man from a burning car after a traffic accident at Panama, Neb., on
Feb. 12.
   _ Troy D. Leach, 16, of Pilton, Ill., who drowned trying to save
a 14-year-old boy from drowning in the North Fork of the Vermilion
River at Danville, Ill., on June 2, 1987. The other boy survived.
   _ Walter Moyseuik, 67, of Etobicoke, Ontario, who rescued a
47-year-old woman from a man with a gun on March 12.
</TEXT>
