<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Philippines-Communist     11-07 0544</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Philippines-Communist,0561</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Military Says It Captures Third-Ranking Communist Rebel</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN GUERRERO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The third-ranking Communist rebel
leader was captured at Manila airport, where he may have been
planning to board a flight for Los Angeles under an assumed name,
officials announced today.
   President Corazon Aquino said Sunday's capture of Ignacio
Capegsan, whom the military described as deputy secretary-general of
the Communist Party of the Philippines, shows that her government is
winning its struggle against the 19-year Marxist insurgency.
   Brig. Gen. Alexander Aguirre, capital regional commander, said
Capegsan was captured Sunday in the parking lot of Ninoy Aquino
International Airport.
   Capegsan's wife, Cresteta, was arrested today during a raid on
the couple's suburban Quezon City home in which police seized
weapons, a personal computer and bank books for accounts totalling
$75,000, officials said.
   ``He was on his way to the USA, particularly Los Angeles,''
Aguirre told reporters. ``It is possible that he is being projected
into the international commission of the Communist Party of the
Philippines.''
   Later, Capegsan, 42, told reporters at a police station that he
had gone to the airport to see off his father-in-law, Lorenzo
Mercado, who was on his way to California. Capegsan denied he
planned to leave the country.
   Capt. Florenio Angeles, who made the arrest, said Capegsan
dropped off his wife and father-in-law at the departure terminal and
then drove his car to a nearby parking lot, where he was taken into
custody.
   Angeles said police were simply speculating that Capegsan
intended to fly to California too because there was no other
explanation for parking the car. Access to the terminal is limited
to ticketed passengers.
   He said informants had told police Capegsan planned to travel to
the United States last month, but canceled the trip.
   Military officials have claimed rebel representatives are raising
funds among Filipino expatriate communities abroad to finance the
insurgency.
   Angeles said, however, that police found no ticket on Capegsan
and that Philippine Airlines had confirmed reservations only for the
wife and father-in-law. He said Capegsan may have planned to fly
stand-by.
   Angeles said police made no attempt to track down the wife and
father-in-law inside the terminal. But Mrs. Capegsan returned home
without boarding the flight and was arrested the following day.
   During a brief appearance before reporters, Capegsan claimed he
left the rebel movement in late 1986, after nearly 16 years in the
underground, because of fatigue and philosophical differences with
other rebel leaders.
   Foreign reporters, however, saw him with rebels in December 1986
during a nationwide 60-day cease-fire.
   According to the military, Capegsan is the highest-ranking member
of the party to be arrested since secretary-general Rafael Baylosis
was captured in March. Authorities say Capegsan served as chairman
of the party's Northern Luzon Commission, which directs rebel
operations in the northern Philippines.
   Capegsan told reporters he had been deputy chairman before
leaving the underground.
   Mrs. Aquino, who has vowed to crush the rebel movement before her
term expires in 1992, hailed the arrest. She told a meeting of
Southeast Asian businessmen today that the capture was ``a very
important development.''
   Capegsan was the seventh suspected central committee member
arrested this year. Longtime party leader Rudolfo Salas was captured
outside a Manila hospital in September 1986.
</TEXT>
