<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Kristallnacht-NY 1stLd-Writethru a0499 11-07 0416</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Kristallnacht-NY, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0499,0422</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Catholic Mass Marks 50th Anniversary of Kristallnacht</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 6th graf, ``Let us ...,'' to CORRECT that Torah is first
five books of Hebrew Bible, sted entire Bible.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RONALD POWERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cardinal John O'Connor honored Jews and the holy
laws of the Torah in a Mass marking the 50th anniversary of
Kristallnacht, the night of shatttered glass that ushered in the
Nazi Holocaust.
   The Roman Catholic cardinal said more than human decency demands
the world remember the Nazi atrocities.
   ``Otherwise we will be destroyed by the indifference that permits
betrayers and killers to stalk the face of the Earth,'' O'Connor
said during a Mass on Sunday at St. Patrick's Cathedral.
   O'Connor has asked all 410 churches in the Archdiocese of New
York to ring their bells Wednesday and parishioners to light candles
on the anniversary. He said he would light a memorial candle in the
window of his residence that night.
   On Nov. 9-10, 1938, Nazis rampaged against Jews in major cities
as well as those in small towns in Germany and Austria.
   ``Let us remind ourselves of the depth of gratitude that we owe
to our Jewish brothers and sisters who died, who lived, but
ultimately survived, survived because they preserved the law,''
O'Connor said, holding the Torah, or first five books of the Hebrew
Bible, given him by Jewish leaders soon after his arrival in New
York City in 1984.
   The attack became known as Kristallnacht, or Crystal Night,
because of the shards of broken glass that littered the streets. It
is considered the beginning of the German drive to exterminate Jews.
An estimated 6 million Jews and hundreds of thousands of others died
at the hands of the Nazis.
   O'Connor made the remarks during his annual Mass for Catholic
lawyers and judges. He reminded the legal community of its duty to
preserve the law.
   ``Is it any wonder that the first lawyers ... were awed by their
tasks, that they were mandated to preserve the law, to copy the law,
to teach the law, to interpret the law, above all to love the law,''
he said. ``Without the law the heart is ripped out of Judaism, the
heart is ripped out of the world.''
   Among those at Sunday's Mass were former Gov. Hugh Carey, Vincent
McConnell of the Guild of Catholic Lawyers, Rabbi Marc Tanenbaum of
the American Jewish Committee and Dr. Yaffa Eliach of the Center for
Holocaust Studies.
</TEXT>
