<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Fan'sAshes     11-07 0346</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Fan's Ashes,0355</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Baseball Fan Wants Ashes Scattered at Third Base</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Elane Sollins' last wish was to have her ashes
scattered where her favorite baseball player could be found _ on
third base at Baltimore's Memorial Stadium.
   Sollins was an avid fan of the Baltimore Orioles, especially
former third baseman Brooks Robinson. She went to about 20 games a
year, where her favorite seat was along the third-base line, and she
listened to the rest of the games on the radio or television.
   Since Sollins died Oct. 25 at 63, her son has been pursuing her
wish.
   ``She's been saying that for 20-30 years ... whenever Brooks
Robinson started playing,'' said her son Charles Kalus. ``She was a
big Orioles fan for years, and third base is where her darling
Brooksie played. I know it's an odd request, I know it's nutty, but
odder requests have been made.''
   Robinson said he didn't know Sollins.
   ``I've heard a lot of them, but this is a new one,'' he said.
``I'm flattered. I didn't realize how involved fans got with players
until I got out of the game.''
   John Aymold, who works for the Loring-Byers funeral home, wrote
to the city's director of parks and recreation for approval. If he
goes along, the decision rests with the team.
   ``If there's any way to honor it, we're going to try,'' Kalus
said. ``Before she died, she went straight to the Orioles with her
request and was turned down. I understand that. But I just told her
I would take it from there.''
   Larry Lucchino, acting president of the Orioles, said he was
staggered by the request, but said the team would be willing to talk
to the city and family about it.
   If the request is denied, Kalus said he might take matters into
his own hands.
   ``I'll show up at the stadium and talk to them myself,'' he said.
``I might even call Brooks to see if he has any pull ... and there's
always Camera Day, when fans are allowed on the field.''
</TEXT>
