<1ST_LINE>r i PM-CocaineCourier     11-07 0487</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Cocaine Courier,0501</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>American Photographer Convicted of Drug Trafficking Leaves For U.S.</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEAD prospects uncertain. New York arrival expected about 3
p.m. EST.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BARCELONA, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 24-year-old American, convicted on
cocaine trafficking charges by a Spanish court despite attempts by
former U.S. Attorney General Edwin Meese to have him freed, left
today for the United States.
   Conan Owen, 24, of Annandale, Va., was sentenced to six years in
prison in April after being convicted of bringing four pounds of
cocaine into Spain from Chile in a false-bottomed suitcase.
   But once in the United States, Justice Department officials could
decide to grant Owen immediate parole because they believe he is
innocent.
   Owen has consistently denied any knowledge of the cocaine in the
suitcase, a claim corroborated in a court deposition by a Washington
D.C. man for whom Owen was working as a freelance photographer at
the time of his arrest.
   To obtain the transfer to the United States, Owen had to agree
not to appeal his conviction. He returns home under a 1983 treaty
signed by Madrid and Washington that permits convicts to serve out
their sentences in prisons in their home country.
   The Spanish government agreed to his request for a transfer
during a weekly Cabinet meeting Oct. 28.
   Accompanied by two U.S. marshals, Owen boarded TWA flight 903,
which left Barcelona for New York with a stopover in Madrid. He left
prison Sunday in a police van and spent the night at Barcelona
police headquarters.
   Owen, who worked as a 1984 summer intern in Vice President Bush's
office and had been admitted to the U.S. Army Intelligence School at
Fort Huachuca, Ariz., was arrested March 13, 1987, on his arrival in
Barcelona from Santiago, Chile.
   In Chile, Owen said he had been shooting travel brochure photos
on an assignment arranged by Washington D.C. resident Jorge Barahona.
   In return for a suspended sentence on a felony cocaine charge and
a promise from U.S. officials that he would not be extradited to
Spain, Barahona told a U.S. federal judge that Owen knew nothing
about the drugs and had been set up to carry the suitcase.
   His declarations also led to the indictment in Virginia of three
others in the plot. All three are at large.
   But the Barcelona court that tried Owen refused to admit
Barahona's deposition as evidence because plea-bargaining is illegal
in Spain.
   When Meese traveled to Madrid in February to sign a protocol for
an extradition treaty with then-Justice Minister Fernando Ledesma,
he told reporters he was handing over Barahona's deposition to
Ledesma in hopes the charges against Owen would be dropped.
   After Owen's conviction, Meese said through a Justice Department
spokesman that he ``regrets very much this action by the Spanish
court. ... I think it's important to stress that we continue to
believe ... in Mr. Owen's innocence, and we continue to hope that he
will ultimately be exonerated.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881107-0058 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-07-88 0756EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-SriLanka 1stLd-Writethru a0471 11-07 0553</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Sri Lanka, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0471,0565</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Army Crushes Prison Uprising; 12 Inmates Killed</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with troops storming prison, 12
killed.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Troops backed by helicopters and
armored cars stormed a prison and killed 12 inmates today in
crushing a rebellion by 1,500 convicts, authorities said.
   About 25 prisoners were injured in the assault by troops who
threw tear gas and opened fire as two helicopters hovered over the
medium-security Welikade Prison in suburban Colombo, police said.
   Soldiers stood guard and smoke could still be seen more than two
hours after the uprising was quashed at the prison, which generally
houses inmates awaiting trial on criminal, rather than political or
civil charges.
   Among the injured was a former navy sailor convicted of attempted
murder for clubbing Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi of India with a
rifle butt two years ago, police said.
   Half the prison population of 3,000 broke out of their cells
Sunday and staged a sit-in to demand better food, the resignation of
President Junius R. Jayewardene and the dissolution of Parliament,
officials said.
   The inmates took one guard hostage but released him early today,
police said, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   They then set fire to furniture in four buildings behind the
20-foot walls around the prison complex and cut telephone lines, the
police said.
   Officials who spoke on condition of anonymity said the prison
rebellion apparently was inspired by strikes and demonstrations
being organized around the country by a radical Sinhalese group, the
People's Liberation Front.
   The front has accused Jayewardene, a Sinhalese, of making too
many concessions to minority Tamils seeking autonomy.
   In southern Sri Lanka, at least 153 prisoners tunneled out of a
military detention camp Sunday, but 78 of them were recaptured, the
government.
   Almost all the escapees from the Pelawatte camp had been detained
on suspicion of belonging to the People's Liberation Front, blamed
by authorities for more than 500 killings in the past 15 months. The
camp is 30 miles southeast of Colombo.
   The front opposes the government's peace overtures for ending a
five-year-old Tamil guerrilla war. Tamils, who make up about 18
percent of Sri Lanka's 16 million people, want an independent
homeland in the northeastern Sri Lanka. They claim they are
discriminated against by Sinhalese, who comprise 75 percent of the
people.
   In another prison protest Sunday, about 800 inmates in Kandy, 60
miles east of Colombo, staged a clamorous demonstration from their
cells. About 35 of them sat on the roof of Bogambara Prison, waving
red flags and demanding Jayewardene's resignation.
   The president has already said he plans to retire after new
presidential elections scheduled for Dec. 19.
   The injured inmates at Welikade Prison included Wijemuni Vijitha
Rohana, who attacked Gandhi on July 30, 1987, one day after Gandhi
and Jayewardene signed a peace accord designed to end a guerrilla
war by Sri Lanka's Tamil minority.
   Rohana, a 23-year-old Sinhalese, was listed in serious condition,
police said.
   Rohana was a member of a military honor guard that Gandhi was
inspecting when the sailor swung his rifle and landed a glancing
blow on the prime minister's shoulder. In November 1987, a military
court convicted Rohana of attempted murder and sentenced him to six
years in prison. Rohana has appealed.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
