<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Israel-Religion     11-07 0602</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel-Religion,0620</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Israeli Coalition Agreement May Divide Jews In Israel, Abroad</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RONI RABIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Right-wing Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir may pay
a high price for forming Israel's next government if he drives a
wedge between the Jewish state and the international Jewish
community in the process.
   Shamir's Likud bloc is using a package of religious laws, opposed
by many Jews outside Israel, as a bargaining chip to coax the
religious parties into a Likud-led coalition.
   Jewish organizations overseas particularly fear passage of laws
that enhance the power of Israel's Orthodox Jews, thus devaluing the
Conservative and Reform streams of Judaism to which many Jews abroad
belong.
   ``This is a red line,'' said Harry Wall, head of the Israeli
office of the U.S.-based Anti-Defamation League of B'nai B'rith.
``This could do serious damage to the concept of Jewish unity and
common destiny, and weaken the ability of American Jews to identify
with Israel.''
   Likud won 40 parliament seats in Tuesday's elections, more than
the 39 seats won by the left-leaning Labor Party but not enough to
form a government without the support of four small religious
parties, which together hold 18 seats.
   Passing religious legislation could undermine the American Jewish
community's political and moral support for Israel and threaten the
half-billion dollars Israel gets in annual contributions from
American Jewry.
   One of the ripple effects could be to diminish the power of the
pro-Israeli lobby in the United States, which has a tremendous
influence over U.S. foreign policy. The United States gives Israel
$3 billion in aid each year.
   At the heart of the controversy is the so-called ``Who is a Jew''
law _ the law that defines who is Jewish and thus eligible for
automatic Israeli citizenship.
   At present, the law says a Jew is anyone whose mother is Jewish
or who converted to the faith.
   But Orthodox Jews say this is not enough. They want to amend the
law so that only conversions performed by an Orthodox rabbi will
count.
   Only 10 to 15 percent of the United States' 5.5 million Jews are
Orthodox. For the others _ although the number of converts among
them may be small and the number who plan to live in Israel marginal
_ a change in the law would cast doubt on their Jewishness.
   ``The American Jewish community is going to support Israel
regardless of Israeli policy on almost any issue,'' said Shlomo
Avineri, a political scientist at the Hebrew University in
Jerusalem. ``There is only one reservation, and that is the
Who-is-a-Jew legislation.''
   Jewish groups in the United States and worldwide are mobilizing
their forces to fight the amendment.
   Representatives of organizations and private individuals have
flooded Israeli consulates and embassies with telegrams and phone
calls opposing the change, said Rabbi Richard Hirsch, executive
director of the World Union for Progressive (Reform) Judaism.
   ``It's been a spontaneous reaction,'' he said. ``Who-is-a-Jew has
become a symbol of what the relationship is between the state of
Israel and the Jewish nation.''
   The North American Coalition on the Who's A Jew Question, an
umbrella group formed last year before a previous attempt to change
the law failed, voted unanimously Friday to fight the amendment,
said Stephen Donshik, director of the Israeli office of the Council
of Jewish Federations.
   He said the coalition communicated its concern to Israeli
political parties even before last week's elections, and will repeat
its message through telegrams, letters and possibly newspaper
advertisements.
   ``The state of Israel is a mutual identification point for Jews
all around the world,'' Donshik said. ``This should not be a
political issue.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881107-0060 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-07-88 0824EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-TitanLaunch     11-07 0349</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Titan Launch,0360</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Titan Missile Launched, Probably Carries Military Satellites</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VANDENBERG AIR FORCE BASE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Titan 34D rocket
thundered into space with a secret cargo during the weekend, and one
expert said it probably carried a pair of military communication
satellites into orbit.
   The 16-story-tall booster blasted off Sunday morning, said Air
Force Capt. John Sullivan, a spokesman for the sprawling Vandenberg
military base on the coast 140 miles northwest of Los Angeles.
   As usual for military space flights, the Air Force didn't
announce the launch in advance and declined to identify its payload.
   However, it most likely carried two Satellite Data System
satellites, although it also might have carried either a KH-9 or
KH-11 photo reconnaissance satellite, said John Pike, a space policy
expert for the Washington-based Federation of American Scientists.
   Pike, who knew about the launch in advance, said Friday the data
system satellites are used for military communications.
   The satellites provide ``a way for the president to stay in touch
with our nuclear forces ... to give bombers and (silo-based crews
operating) missiles the `go code''' to launch nuclear warheads, he
said.
   Pike said two SDS satellites were ``launched five years ago.
They're due for replacement.''
   SDS and KH-series satellites are the only types launched from
Vandenberg on Titan 34Ds, he said.
   ``The reason I think it's SDS is I don't think the Air Force has
any more KH-9s or KH-11s,'' Pike said.
   The Titan 34D, America's most powerful space booster, will be
supplanted by the Titan 4, due for its maiden launch next year from
Cape Canaveral, Fla.
   The last launch of a Titan 34D was from Cape Canaveral on Sept.
2, but sources told The Associated Press it failed to place its
payload in orbit.
   Pike described that payload as a satellite designed to monitor
Soviet missile tests and radio, telephone, radar and other
electronic communications.
   Two Titan 34Ds were launched successfully in late 1987. Before
then, they were grounded following two straight explosions during
launches on Aug. 28, 1985, and April 18, 1986, destroying a KH-11
and a KH-9.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881107-0061 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-07-88 0829EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Israel     11-07 0611</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel,0632</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Palestinian Kills Soldier Guarding Jewish Settlement</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KARIN LAUB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Palestinian day laborer today stabbed to death
a soldier guarding a Jewish settlement in the West Bank, and then
the assailant was killed by an Israeli farmer, witnesses said.
   The soldier was killed at about 9 a.m. while guarding the gate to
the Massua cooperative farm, 26 miles northeast of Jerusalem, said
Yuval Yedidia, head of the cooperative.
   The Arab worker approached the gate on foot, Yedidia said. When
the guard demanded an entry permit, the assailant ``attacked the
guard with a knife and stabbed him about 30 times,'' Yedidia said.
   One of the farm's residents ``heard shouts, he grabbed a gun, and
they (the soldier and the assailant) were still entangled when he
arrived. He opened fire,'' Yedidia said.
   The Palestinian was among about 100 seasonal laborers working in
grapevines, pepperfields and flowerbeds, residents said.
   The cooperative was closed off by soldiers after the attack, and
Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin and Lt. Gen. Dan Shomron, army chief
of staff, came to the farm.
   Yedidia described relations between Arabs and Jews in the
cooperative as ``generally good,'' but said members had expressed
concern about Palestinians working in their midst. He said farmers
or soldiers routinely guard the cooperative.
   Today's deaths brought the Palestinian death toll to 308 since
the Dec. 8 start of the uprising against Israeli occupation of the
West Bank and Gaza Strip. The guard became the 11th Israeli and
second soldier to be killed.
   In the West Bank city of Nablus, four Palestinians were wounded
today when troops opened fire to disperse a demonstration protesting
the army's closure of West Bank schools, Arab hospital officials
said.
   Some demonstrators carried outlawed Palestinian flags and others
chanted ``Open our schools immediately!'' and ``Freedom for our
students!''
   West Bank schools have been closed for most of the uprising. Army
officials argue that schools are hotbets of anti-Israeli violence.
   A fifth Palestinian, a 14-year-old boy, was wounded in a clash
with troops in Gaza City, hospital officials said.
   Also today, the right-wing Likud bloc and the left-of-center
Labor Party held talks with smaller parties for a chance to form the
next coalition govermment after Tuesday's inconclusive elections.
   Attacks on Israelis generally boost hard-line sentiments, and an
West Bank firebomb attack Oct. 30 is believed to have cost Labor a
crucial three seats in the 120-member Parliament.
   A mother and her four young sons were burned to death in the
assault on a bus north of Jericho.
   Likud, the largest party, seemed to have the best chance of
putting together a rightist coalition with the support of four
Orthodox parties.
   Likud won 40 seats in the 120-member Parliament and Labor won 39,
but the left wing parties together have 49 seats to the right's 47.
   Labor's chances improved Sunday after two ultra-Orthodox groups _
Shas and the Torah Flag Party _ announced they were considering
joining a Labor-led government.
   Another prospect of Labor participation was a joint government
with Likud like the one formed after 1984 elections ended in
stalemate. Labor Party leader Shimon Peres is under some pressure to
join with Likud and avoid concessions that would curtail the freedom
of Israel's secular majority.
   The Hadashot newspaper said over the weekend that Likud leader
and Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir would be willing to discuss such a
coalition on condition he remain prime minister, with Rabin, a
Laborite, staying on as defense minister.
   Rabin, who has had a long-running feud with Peres and is a rival
for the Labor leadership post, told Israel television Saturday he
didn't rule out a joint government with Likud.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
