<2ND_LINE>PM-Lotto Winner,0226</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Single Winner to Receive $38 Million Lotto Jackpot</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One player matched all six numbers to win a $38
million Lotto jackpot, but the identity of the lucky ticket-holder
remains a mystery, lottery officials say.
   The player, who won the grand prize after a week of
record-breaking ticket sales, will receive the state's second
largest jackpot in annual payments over the next 20 years, said
Sharon Sharp, director of the Illinois lottery.
   In the hour before the 7 p.m. drawing Saturday, the state's 4,100
machines processed a record 26,000 tickets per minute and sales
topped $1.1 million an hour, said lottery spokeswoman Kathy Rem.
   Ticket sales totaled $26.7 million for the week, including $11.5
million on Saturday alone, Ms. Sharp said Sunday.
   Lottery officials were expected to announce the total prize _ at
least $38 million _ today, Ms. Rem said. But she said it was
unlikely the winnings would top the $40 million prize won in 1984 by
Chicago printer Mike Wittkowski.
   The prize grew as no one matched all the Lotto numbers for three
consecutive weeks.
   To win, players must match the six numbers between one and 54.
Lesser prizes go to players who match four and five of the six
winning numbers. The winning numbers were 33, 35, 43, 44, 45, and 52.
</TEXT>
