<1ST_LINE>r a PM-YellowstoneFires     11-07 0264</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Yellowstone Fires,0272</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>All But One Of Yellowstone Fires Now Controlled</HEAD>
<DATELINE>YELLOWSTONE NATIONAL PARK, Wyo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   All but one of the forest
fires that plagued Yellowstone National Park this summer have been
declared under control, thanks to early snowfall.
   Fire managers will watch the smoldering leftovers of the fires
until the last puff of smoke dies away, said park spokeswoman Amy
Vanderbilt.
   Only the Clover-Mist blaze, whic burned in Yellowstone and the
adjacent Shoshone National Forest, has yet to be declared
controlled, Vanderbilt said Sunday.
   Wintry weather late last week helped get the North Fork, Wolf
Lake and Snake complex of fires under control, she added.
   The snow also forced park officials Sunday to close Yellowstone's
south and east entrances, probably until spring. The west and north
entrances remain open.
   Officials have estimated that about 20 percent of the 1.1 million
acres the fires surrounded were charred in the 2.2 million-acre park.
   Snow depths in the park Sunday ranged from an inch or less to as
much as a foot.
   Active firefighting ended some weeks ago, but officials have
continued to keep a close eye on the fires.
   As of Saturday there were still 41 people and one helicopter
monitoring and doing rehabilitation work on the North Fork fire in
the area of the Old Faithful geyser, while 173 people and three
helicopters monitor the adjacent Wolf Lake fire, according to
Vanderbilt. Four people were monitoring the Snake complex in the
park's southern section.
   ``That's primarily rehabilitation crews, and some of that work is
ongoing as long as weather permits,'' she said.
</TEXT>
