<HEAD>PRECEDE Washington</HEAD>
<HEAD>Strong Earthquakes Hit Pacific Islands</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates throughout with quake near Fiji. No pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>CANBERRA, Australia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Strong earthquakes jolted the Vanuatu
and Fiji islands in the South Pacific today, seismologists reported.
   There were no reports of casualties or damage from the quakes,
each of which measured 6.9 on the Richter scale, according to the
Seismological Observatory in Canberra and the U.S. Geological Survey
in Golden, Colo.
   The epicenter of the Fiji quake was in the sea about 250 miles
south of the islands, said an official at the Canberra observatory.
He gave no time for the quake.
   An earthquake struck Vanuatu, about 700 miles west of Fiji, at
3:50 p.m. local time today, according to seismologists in Golden who
registered the movement. Vanuatu is 1,100 miles north of Auckland,
New Zealand.
   The Richter scale is a gauge of energy released by an earthquake
as measured by ground motion recorded on a seismograph. Every
increase of one point represents a tenfold increase in intensity. A
reading of 6 on the Richter scale can cause severe damage in a
populated area.
</TEXT>
