<1ST_LINE>r a PM-People-HurricaneRelief     11-07 0301</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-People-Hurricane Relief,0312</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Operation California Sends 30 Tons Of Supplies To Nicaragua</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thirty tons of medical and other emergency
supplies have been flown to hurricane-ravaged Nicaragua after an
airport send-off by actors Robert Blake, Kris Kristofferson and
others.
   The $750,000 worth of medicine, medical equipment, water
purification and storage equipment and shelter material were donated
by pharmaceutical companies and other corporations, said organizer
Richard Walden.
   Nicaragua and other Latin American nations were battered last
month by Hurricane Joan, which devastated the Nicaraguan city of
Bluefields.
   Debrah Farentino of the ``Hooperman'' TV series, Valerie Wildman,
who starred in the movie ``Salvador,'' and movie director Haskell
Wexler also turned out Saturday to lend their support.
   Walden, Wexler and Wildman accompanied the cargo to Nicaragua,
which has not received any U.S. government aid. The Reagan
administration supports the Contra effort to overthrow Nicaragua's
leftist Sandinista government.
   The supplies will be distributed by an ecumenical coalition of
Nicaraguan churches, Walden said.
   ``This load will be absorbed in about three days,'' said Blase
Bonpane, director of the private Office of the Americas
organization, which assisted with fund-raising.
   The relief supplies were shipped on a DC-8 chartered by Operation
California, a private international relief group, at a cost of
$40,000.
   An additional 15 tons of supplies are ready to be shipped but
there is no transportation, Bonpane said.
   Borrowing a U.S. military cargo plane would save the relief group
$50,000, he said, but a request to use an Air National Guard C-130
has been pending in Washington since the hurricane hit, he said.
   ``They're sitting on it back there,'' said Bonpane.
   Office of the Americas is dedicated to peace in the hemisphere
and engages in hemispheric education and ``private diplomacy,'' he
said.
   ``This has nothing to do with anything but humanitarian aid.''
</TEXT>
