<DOCNO> AP881107-0067 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-07-88 0922EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Bush 1stLd-Writethru a0469 11-07 0884</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bush, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0469,870</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Says He's Sprinting to Election</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Top 8 grafs new with Bush speech; pickup pvs 2nd graf bgng,
``I am getting; SUBS pvs 6th graf bgng, After a day, to past-tense;
tops planned.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican George Bush, in a frenzied campaign
swing aimed at bolstering his lead over Democratic rival Michael
Dukakis, declared today he was winding up his marathon race for the
presidency ``not in a power walk but in a sprint.''
   The vice president began last-day sweep through four states by
urging his rally audience in the Detroit suburb of Southfield to
vote in Tuesday's election. And when they go to the polls, he said,
they should ask themselves, ``Is the country headed in the right
direction?''
   Added Bush: ``The answer is, yes it is.''
   The GOP nominee took what appeared to be a veiled swipe at
Dukakis' penchant for getting exercise by speed walking with weights
in each hand.
   ``In a sense, Michigan is where we got our real start this
year,'' Bush said. ``And in a sense, it's a very important place to
be as we run right down to the finish line, not in a power walk but
in a sprint.''
   The close contest in Michigan ``could be the key to this whole
election,'' he said, referring to the importance of the big,
vote-heavy industrial states of the Middle West.
   Michigan was the first battleground in the race for the
Republican nomination, and it was there that Bush got his start by
beating Pat Robertson and Rep. Jack Kemp of New York.
   On Tuesday, Bush sought to counter criticism that he had set the
negative tone of the 1988 presidential campaign.
   ``I am getting sick and tired of my opponent's complaining about
the rough and tumble of this campaign, something he does every time
just before an election,'' Bush told a rally Sunday in the San
Fernando Valley of Los Angeles.
   ``He seems to forget the past. He seems to forget those personal
attacks night after night on me, on my character, at that idiotic
Democratic convention.''
   The vice president said voters can see through the ``smoke
screen,'' and that ``all that's left is this daily whining about a
negative campaign.''
   ``My advice to the liberal governor of Massachusetts ... is `look
my friend, if you can't stand the heat, get the hell out of the
kitchen,''' Bush later told an outdoor rally in Covina, Calif.
   After a day of courting voters in Colorado and California, Bush
tried to put Michigan firmly into his pocket and then headed for
Missouri and Ohio, two other states where the race is close, before
spending tonight and Election Day in Houston.
   Tonight, Bush was making his final appeal to voters nationwide in
a paid half-hour broadcast on the CBS, NBC and ABC networks.
   Campaign officials said Sunday that their tracking polls showed
slippage in Bush's support last week had subsided.
   But other polls for news organizations over the weekend showed
some volatility, with Democratic rival Michael Dukakis gaining a
little ground.
   National polls released Sunday showed Bush ahead by margins
ranging from five to 12 points. Surveys of the 50 states indicated,
however, with indications that the GOP nominee has more than enough
states firmly in his column to garner the 270 Electoral College
votes needed for victory.
   Campaign manager Lee Atwater told reporters Bush forces believe a
Republican victory in either Ohio, Michigan or Missouri would
foreclose any chance Dukakis might have of putting together a
combination that adds up to 270 electoral votes.
   California, where Bush spent Sunday seeking the nation's biggest
electoral prize of 47 votes, was considered a tossup in the final
weekend before Election Day in the GOP campaign's own polls, Bush
aides said.
   ``We feel good with our electoral strength we have in both our
strong states and those that are leaning to us,'' campaign Chief of
Staff Craig Fuller said of the Republican nominee's own polling
figures.
   Sunday's theme from Bush and his surrogates was Dukakis'
complaints about the Bush campaign attacks.
   Atwater called the Dukakis criticism ``hypocritical'' because, he
claimed, the Democrats started the campaign attacks when they
derided Bush at their Atlanta convention this summer. He called the
convention a `three-day mudslinging festival.`
   Those comments, and similar themes voiced by other campaign
spokesmen came on a day when The New York Times published a poll
showing most respondents blamed Bush principally for the negative
tone of race.
   While blasting Dukakis for attacking his attacks, Bush kept up
the offensive. ``He is naive. He is totally inexperienced in foreign
policy,'' Bush said of his opponent.
   Atwater said one of the campaign's biggest concerns was getting
out the vote, a theme Bush has raised continually in the past week
in urging Republican voters against complacency.
   ``I never felt better, or stronger or more ready to fight for
every vote out there,'' the vice president said at the San Fernando
Valley rally.
   Bush aides, meantime, looked beyond Election Day to what an
electoral landslide could mean to the Republican as president.
   ``Anything we can do to enhance George Bush's electoral strength
by harnessing our resources ... should increase George Bush's
electoral lead and strengthen his hand as president,'' said Fuller.
</TEXT>
