<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Britain-Intelligence 1stLd-Writethru a04ctorsblamedin
11-07 0735</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Britain-Intelligence, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0422,0754</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Civil Servants Strike Over Firings at Intelligence HQ</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 13 grafs with one-day strike, lunchtime rallies,
details; PICKS up 10th pvs, `None of ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MAGGIE JACKSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tens of thousands of civil servants in government
offices, ports and prisons went on strike today to protest the
firing of union workers at Britain's intelligence-gathering
headquarters.
   A spokesman for the Council of Civil Service Unions, an umbrella
body for Britain's eight civil service unions, estimated 200,000
workers took part in the one-day walkout.
   Dozens of lunchtime rallies were held to protest the recent
firings of five men at the Government Communications Headquarters in
Cheltenham. The huge southwest England facility eavesdrops on the
Soviet Union, and the government maintains its work is too sensitive
to risk disruption by strikes.
   The firings provoked new charges that Prime Minister Margaret
Thatcher's government is undermining civil liberties.
   The union coalition reported ``80 percent-plus walkouts'' had
shut down many employment and welfare offices, state-run job and
driving-test centers across Britain.
   Civil servants also walked off jobs in customs offices, prisons,
airports, and magistrates courts, it said.
   ``We're thinking 200,000 is not a bad estimate,'' said
spokeswoman Anne Kenefeck.
   The five men have been fired for defying a 1984 ban on unions at
the facility, and another 12 men are facing retirement, compulsory
transfer or dismissal. They are the holdouts from among one-third of
the 7,000 employees at the facility who were union members in 1984.
   At the time, most accepted about $1,400 in compensation to quit
their union.
   Critics see the firings as the latest occasion on which the
Thatcher government has chosen to sacrifice an element of individual
freedom for what it calls the national interest.
   ``The present dispute is one aspect of a much larger debate,''
says Donald Cameron Watt, a professor of international history at
the London School of Economics. ``It's become a party policy issue
over the issue of openness of information, the reform of secrecy
(laws).''
   The firings follow two highly controversial clampdowns. In
October, the government banned broadcast interviews with members of
the Irish Republican Army and 10 other militant Northern Ireland
groups and announced plans to remove any suspects' right to remain
silent under police questioning.
   At Cheltenham, the unions have lost a string of legal battles and
have no chance of overturning the ban, but refuse to back down.
   None of the holdouts had been fired until this year, although
union officials say the government tried to freeze them out with
tactics such as refusing them pay raises.
   Mike Grindley, a Chinese-language expert, estimates he lost 5,000
to 6,000 pounds ($8,850 to $10,000) in raises before being fired in
October. He now works full time on the campaign.
   ``We don't think about the money too much,'' Grindley, 51, said
in a telephone interview. ``It hasn't been easy, but there's been
compensation. ... You can hold your head up high.''
   In imposing the ban, Mrs. Thatcher cited pay strikes in 1979-81
that disrupted work at Cheltenham, the European center of Soviet
eavesdropping for NATO.
   The headquarters intercepts radio signals and other
communications from the Soviet Union and its East bloc allies.
   The facility attracted international attention in 1982 when
Geoffrey Prime, a translator in Russian at the facility, was
uncovered as a Soviet agent. Prime, described as one of the West's
most damaging post-World War II traitors, was sentenced to 35 years
in prison.
   ``You can make quite a strong case on the government point,''
said Professor Watt, who also is a member of the editorial board of
the Journal of Intelligence and National Security.
   ``The government believed they had a case, it wasn't just
union-bashing,'' he added in an interview. ``They operate on a
worst-case analysis, and (strikes) were something they had very good
reason to think would happen.''
   The unions reply that strikes never affected security and that
the government rejected a 1984 offer of a no-strike deal.
   Some Thatcher supporters have expressed unease at the
government's refusal to compromise in the Cheltenham dispute.
   Commentator Nicholas Comfort, writing in the pro-Conservative
Party Daily Telegraph newspaper on the growing power of the state
over the individual, said the government ``could have reached a
no-strike agreement if it had tried.''
   ``It is not just the threat of terrorism which has brought fresh
intervention into our daily lives,'' Comfort added.
</TEXT>
