<1ST_LINE>u p PM-TVCampaign 1stLd-Writethru a0414 11-07 0903</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-TV Campaign, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0414,880</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Made-For-TV Campaign Ends on Video Note</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Top 12 grafs new with latest Bush negative ad; picks up 10th
graf pvs bgng ``Rogich and...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George Bush is mounting a last-minute
television attack on Michael Dukakis with a fierce five-minute ad
criticizing the Massachusetts governor on his handling of everything
from crime to the environment.
   The Bush ad, coming amid a flurry of upbeat musical commercials
and tonight's relatively tame 30-minute network appeals, summarizes
the attacks Republican Bush has been making against his Democratic
opponent in ads and on the stump throughout the election season.
   ``It's running in selected markets. It's a broad overview of
everything that Michael Dukakis stands for, according to his
record,'' Bush ad director Sig Rogich said today. Rogich denied the
ad was introduced in response to narrowing poll margins; he said it
had been ``planned long ago'' and was ``in the works for weeks,
literally.''
   The five-minute ad features Massachusetts residents and officials
complaining about Dukakis' handling of pollution in Boston Harbor,
the state's prisoner furlough program and the state's economy,
including taxes, jobs and budget shortfalls. Bush does not appear.
   In addition to eleventh-hour attack ads, TV viewers also are
being treated to sentimental media closings featuring flags,
children and old people.
   The double-barrelled, multi-million dollar windup concludes a
campaign season shaped to an unprecedented degree by television _
from 10-second sound bites and 30-second ads to extended interviews.
The finale comes tonight, when each candidate airs 30-minute appeals
on the three networks at a cost of $1 million for each campaign.
   Even the ads acknowledge TV's pervasive presence. Bush's musical
spot features several scenes of people watching him on their TV
sets. Dukakis is shown in one of his spots watching a Bush attack ad
and switching off the set in disgust.
   The fall campaigns began with made-for-TV conventions awash in
flags, balloons, children and TelePrompTers, the halls carefully
refashioned with seating, podiums and colors suitable for the small
screen.
   The Dukakis program at 8 p.m. EST showcases the Massachusetts
governor answering questions in a town meeting setting and contains
footage of his family and his running mate, Texas Sen. Lloyd
Bentsen. During the program, Dukakis urges Americans to ``look in
the mirror and ask yourself _ Is George Bush on your side? I want to
give every American a chance to build a better life.''
   The Bush effort at 8:30 p.m. EST summarizes the vice president's
resume, beliefs and plans for the nation.
   The two candidates set records this year for money spent on
commercials (expected to top $30 million apiece) and for free air
time on news, talk and interview shows (at all hours of day and
night).
   Some say the campaigns also set a record for negative
advertising. But while a mixture of ads remained on the air to the
end, the mood of some of the newer spots was uplifting.
   Rogich and Jim Weller, part of the team that brought viewers the
``Morning in America'' ads of President Reagan's 1984 campaign,
evoke the same mood for the vice president with the same song _
``God Bless the USA,'' a patriotic country ballad sung by Lee
Greenwood.
   There are the TV-watching scenes, a grandmother and grandchild,
several Pledges of Allegiance, Bush with world leaders and Bush with
children dressed up as pilgrims for a play. Sings Greenwood: ``If
tomorrow all the things were gone I worked for all my life ... I'd
thank my lucky stars to be living here today cause the flag still
stands for freedom and they can't take that away.''
   The lyrics in Dukakis' ``Anthem'' commercial reflect the
Democrat's more complicated task of promising a better future
without badmouthing the present. ``The time is soon,'' the singers
say as a young mother caresses a baby's face. ``A bright future is
what we're going to see. We keep reaching out for better and we will
never say never because we know where we come from. The best America
... is yet to come.''
   The most memorable commercials of the campaign were less upbeat.
   ``Revolving Door,'' a Bush spot, showed a procession of inmates
filing in and out of a revolving iron gate, then an ominous aerial
view of prison grounds and a guard tower. The narrator says Dukakis
vetoed the death penalty and ``gave weekend furloughs to
first-degree murderers not eligible for parole. While out, many
committed other crimes like kidnapping and rape and many are still
at large.''
   Dukakis struck back, belatedly, first with a ``Packaging of
George Bush'' series that struck a raw nerve among consultants and
columnists. Too confusing, too elitist, they said of the spots,
which showed actors playing cynical Bush handlers trying to disguise
their candidate's alleged shortcomings.
   Bush mocked Dukakis' tank ride and derided his defense positions;
Dukakis castigated Bush's choice of running mate Dan Quayle and
denounced Bush's performance as head of anti-terrorism and drug task
forces. Dukakis is ``on your side,'' his campaign ads pledged.
``America can't afford that risk,'' Bush's ads retorted.
   Did any of it matter? Yes, according to early indications.
   In a 1984 post-election poll of registered voters, 12 percent
said commercials had helped them decide how to vote. Asked the same
question in a CBS-New York Times poll late last month, 25 percent of
probable voters admitted their decision was influenced by
commercials.
</TEXT>
