<1ST_LINE>r a PM-JailShooting     11-07 0411</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Jail Shooting,0423</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Escapee Hit By Three Of 12 Bullets</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two officers have been suspended after the killing
of an unarmed prisoner who was shot when he freed himself from
handcuffs and tried to escape, authorities said.
   The officers fired at least 12 shots, said Harris County
sheriff's Lt. Ruben Diaz.
   Roland Brothers Jr., 28, of Lafayette, La., was struck by at
least three bullets, two in the chest, the county medical examiner's
office said Sunday.
   Some witnesses told reporters that the officers continued
shooting after Brothers fell, but Chief Deputy Sheriff Tommy Thomas
said Sunday that they refused to talk to investigators and that
other witnesses had disputed their reports.
   ``They didn't have to keep shooting that man,'' said witness
Elaine White. She told reporters that after the man was shot in the
leg and in the torso, he said: ```Hey man, I'm not going anywhere.'''
   Brothers, wanted on a felony escape and several other warrants,
was booked by police Saturday in suburban Jersey Village for
unauthorized use of a vehicle and then turned over to sheriff's
Detectives Barry Rizk and Robert Nichols, Diaz said.
   Brothers, whose record included four Harris County escape charges
and one Louisiana escape, was handcuffed and immobilized by a leg
brace during the drive to the county jail, Diaz said.
   But Brothers managed to remove the leg brace and free his right
hand from the cuffs, and when the two detectives stopped the car in
the Harris County jail garage, he left their car and started
running, authorities said. The detectives shouted for him to stop,
Diaz said.
   Brothers, initially identified as Michael Reed, an alias, ran
toward the jail's garage door, which was closing.
   ``Both (detectives) knew they could not reach Reed (Brothers)
before the door closed _ he would have been outside; they were
inside,'' Diaz said.
   The officers then fired about 12 shots, and Brothers fell outside
the door.
   ``The number of times he was shot is immaterial,'' said District
Attorney John B. Holmes Jr. ``The investigation is whether he was
escaping. I don't see there appears to be much doubt to that.''
   Holmes said state law allows use of deadly force to prevent an
escape.
   A handcuff key was found in Brothers' underwear at the medical
examiner's office, Diaz said.
   Rizk, 29, and Nichols, 34, were relieved of duty with pay pending
an investigation by the sheriff's homicide and internal affairs
divisions and the district attorney's office.
</TEXT>
