<1ST_LINE>r a PM-FamilyFight     11-07 0375</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Family Fight,0384</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Elderly Couple Sues Son Over Ownership Of Their Home</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MILTON, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The case of an elderly couple suing their
son in an effort to regain ownership of their own home is not as
unusual as it might sound, say advocates for the elderly.
   Hyman Freeman, a retired fruit seller, and his wife, Frances,
were persuaded two years ago by their 52-year-old son, Leonard, to
put their house in his name to save money on inheritance taxes.
   According to the elder Freemans, who are in their late 70s, the
agreement was that their son would be responsible for upkeep of the
house while his parents lived there on a 25-year lease. Under the
arrangement, if the parents wanted to they could cancel it and take
the house back in their name, they said.
   But the Freemans say their son didn't keep his word. So this
summer they filed suit, accusing him of defrauding them of their
home. They want the property back and without the $100,000 mortgage
they say their son took out on the house to get a line of credit,
The Boston Sunday Globe reported.
   Said Mrs. Freeman: ``We haven't slept nights. ... It's pretty
tough when your son does that to you _ and after you've been so good
to him.''
   The son, a musician and court officer in Boston Land Court, has
declined comment. And his lawyer, Paul Driscoll, said, ``I want to
try my cases in court and not in the arena of public opinion.
   ``If you were in litigation with your father, would you want it
in the newspaper?'' he told the Globe.
   Such cases are not unusual, say advocates for senior citizens.
   Ellen Bruce, managing attorney for Greater Boston Elderly Legal
Services, said her office handles five or six cases per year of
people who say they were induced to give their homes to younger
family members.
   ``It's done much too often without seniors getting proper legal
advice,'' Ms. Bruce said. ``They trust their children.''
   The elder Freeman said he agreed to the arrangement but made it
clear to his son that the house was only to be in the son's name.
   The two sides are scheduled to meet in court in January.
</TEXT>
