<FILEID>AP-NR-11-07-88 1017EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Scotus-Sculpture     11-07 0584</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus-Sculpture,580</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court to Review Dispute Over Sculpture Depicting Plight of Homeless</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today agreed to decide a
recurring copyright question by reviewing a dispute over a sculpture
depicting the plight of the homeless.
   The court said it will hear an appeal by the Community for
Creative Non-Violence (CCNV) and its founder, Mitch Snyder, who seek
exclusive copyright ownership of the work.
   CCNV, which is based in the nation's capital, decided in 1985 to
participate in the annual Christmas Pageant of Peace here by
sponsoring a display dramatizing the plight of the homeless.
   Snyder and other CCNV members commissioned James Earl Reid, a
Baltimore, Md., sculptor, to create a work entitled ``Third World
America.''
   Using a synthetic substance called Design Cast 62 that would be
tinted to resemble bronze, Reid agreed to sculpt two adult figures
and a child huddled on a streetside steam grate.
   The life-sized figures were intended to be part of an updated
Nativity scene.
   CCNV provided a steam grate and pedestal for the work.
   Reid was paid $15,000 for expenses and for his assistants. He
donated his own services without charge.
   CCNV sent the entire sculpture back to Reid in January 1986 for
some repairs.
   The group planned to take the sculpture on a tour of several
cities to raise money for the homeless.
   But Reid objected to the tour because, he said, the sculpture was
too fragile. He urged CCNV to cast the work in bronze or make a
master mold that would withstand the tour.
   CCNV declined, but said Reid could do so if he wished.
   Two months later, Reid refused to return the sculpture and
registered it in his own name. He also said he planned to take the
work on a less ambitious exhibition tour.
   CCNV then filed a lawsuit claiming exclusive copyright ownership
of the sculpture.
   A federal judge ruled in favor of the organization on grounds the
sculpture was ``a work made for hire'' whose copyright is owned by
CCNV.
   But the U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals overturned the judge's
decision and ordered further hearings in the case.
   The appeals court said the physical work itself is owned by CCNV.
But it said the organization may have to share with Reid the
copyright and any profits derived from the work and credit for its
creation.
   ``Intense as CCNV's participation in the project may have been,
Reid, as sculptor, contributed more than a minimal amount of
creativity to `Third World America','' the appeals court said.
   ``That is enough ... to render (Reid) an author of a protected
work'' under a 1976 revision of federal copyright law, the appeals
court said.
   The only question left to be decided is whether CCNV and Reid
should share the copyright ownership, the appeals court said as it
sent the case back to a federal judge.
   The Copyright Justice Coalition, representing more than 100,000
artists, urged the Supreme Court to adopt the appeals court's
interpretation of the 1976 copyright law.
   ``It is critically important for free-lance creators to be able
to claim authorship of their own works in order to build a
reputation that attracts new clients,'' the coalition said.
``Equally as important, free-lance creators rely heavily on the
income-producing potential associated with ownership of the
copyrights in their works.''
   Denying artists such protection ``will dry up our national
resources of free-lance creative talent,'' the coalition added.
   The case is Community for Creative Non-Violence vs. Reid, 88-293.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
