<1ST_LINE>r a PM-HouseFire     11-07 0198</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-House Fire,0203</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House Fire Kills Five</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A late-night fire spread smoke throughout a house
with tightly locked doors and no smoke alarm, killing four
youngsters and their grandmother, officials said.
   ``The call came in from a neighbor who said there was some smoke
coming out from the house next door and they tried to raise some
people, but got no response,'' said a Fire Department dispatcher who
wouldn't give his name.
   Fire Investigator Mike Southerland said the house was secured
with ``double-key'' deadbolts, a type of lock which requires
separate keys to lock the house from the inside and outside.
   ``It is not the type we like people to have,'' said Southerland,
adding that fire officials had not determined if the locks prevented
escape.
   The fire broke out shortly after 11 p.m. Sunday in the one-story
home not equipped with smoke alarms, officials said. Fire officials
said it was extinguished quickly.
   Fire investigator Randy Sanders said a cause had not been
determined.
   Hospital officials believe all the victims suffered smoke
inhalation.
   The victims were identified as Sierra Faggett, 17 months; Marcus
Faggett, 2; Latrece Faggett, 13; Terrance Faggett, 17, and Mary
Graham, 71.
</TEXT>
