<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Dukakis 2ndLd-Writethru a0516 11-07 0986</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dukakis, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0516,980</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Precede BROOK PARK, Ohio</HEAD>
<HEAD>Dukakis Pins Hopes Of Catching Bush on Non-Stop Campaigning</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates with Dukakis in St. Louis in top 5 grafs, picking up
in 4th graf pvs, In all</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis raced from state to state
the day before the presidential voting, declaring the race was
getting tighter and promising a comeback victory in ``a November
surprise.''
   Democrat Dukakis, pinning his hopes of overtaking George Bush on
more than two days of non-stop stumping, spoke at sunrise to a
boisterous crowd of several hundred supporters at a union hall in a
Cleveland suburb, then flew to St. Louis.
   He was greeted at the St. Louis airport by a band playing, ``Rock
Around the Clock,'' a fitting choice for his no-rest final effort.
   ``They talk a lot about October surprises in an election
campaign,'' he told supporters. ``Tomorrow we're going to have a
November surprise.''
   ``The race is very, very tight. It's getting tighter by the
hour,'' Dukakis said.
   He flew to Brook Park, Ohio, on a ``red-eye'' flight from
Spokane, Wash., before heading to St. Louis and was flying west
again for a full day of campaigning in California.
   In all, the trip to the Midwest, added to the schedule Sunday,
had Dukakis traveling more than 4,000 miles in eight hours.
   Dukakis, who caught a two-hour nap on the flight east, had more
stops planned on another cross-country flight early Tuesday,
including a pre-dawn rally in Iowa, on the last leg of a journey
that would ultimately bring him home to Boston to vote.
   ``I don't need sleep; I'm charging,'' he said.
   At the rally this morning, held in a United Auto Workers union
hall, Dukakis continued his attacks on Bush and Republican Vice
Presidential nominee Dan Quayle and promised to be a president who
stands up for American workers.
   ``I'm not running for president to help the sharp operators on
Wall Street,'' Dukakis said, ``I'm running to help the lathe
operators and the machine operators.''
   Despite little sleep, Dukakis was in high spirits. ``Good
Morning, Ohio,'' he declared at the opening of his speech. ``We took
the red-eye to be with the Buckeyes.''
   Then, acknowledging that he trails Bush, Dukakis asked, ``Is Ohio
going to let the pollsters and the pundits decide this election or
are you going to send a message to them?''
   Later in the speech, he said ``We're going to win in Ohio, and
all across this country.''
   As Dukakis stumped Sunday his focus was on his populist appeal
and Quayle, the Indiana senator and GOP vice presidential nominee.
   He scoffed at Bush for borrowing the Democrat's ``I'm on your
side'' line and said the vice president was so worried that his lead
was eroding that he now was following Dukakis around the country.
   ``I'll tell you one place he's not following Mike Dukakis and
Lloyd Bentsen,'' Dukakis told crowds in Westminster, Colo.;
Portland, Ore., and the Washington cities of Tacoma and Spokane.
``He's not following us to 1600 Pennsylvania Avenue.''
   Dukakis also pressed his contention that a man who would pick
Quayle to be a heartbeat away from the presidency lacks the judgment
to be president, honing the attack on a Bush comment that he would
consider putting Quayle in charge of the White House's crisis
management team.
   ``Dan Quayle managing the Cuban missile crisis, think about it,''
Dukakis told about 20,000 people at an outdoor rally at Portland
State University. ``We can't afford to take that risk. Dan Quayle
isn't a crisis manager _ he's a crisis that has to be managed.''
   Dukakis said Bush's only new idea during the campaign has been a
tax cut for the rich while the Democrat listed his proposals on
college financing, health care, a ban on offshore oil drilling in
certain areas and his support for the Equal Rights Amendment and
comparable pay for women.
   ``He's slipping and sliding; we're rocking and rolling,'' an
upbeat Dukakis told his rallies. ``Americans all over the country
are looking hard at this campaign and asking themselves the
fundamental question: Which candidate will stand up for working
families in this country.''
   Dukakis took questions from students at the University of Puget
Sound in Tacoma, Wash., Sunday night and was asked whether he
thought liberal had become a dirty word.
   ``No, I think Mr. Bush is trying to make it a dirty word, and I
object to that,'' the Massachusetts governor said.
   Dukakis, according to most national polls, has cut into Bush's
lead but still faces a formidable task if he is to break the
Republican's apparent lock on the Electoral College.
   National polls released Sunday showed Bush ahead by margins
ranging from five to 12 points, but 50-state surveys indicated that
the GOP nominee has more than enough states firmly in his column to
garner the 270 electoral votes needed to elect.
   According to aides, Dukakis is counting on winning California,
Illinois, Michigan and Pennsylvania, all major states in which polls
show a tight race. His chances appear to hinge on beating Bush in at
least one of three other big states where he trails Bush _ Ohio, New
Jersey and Texas _ although Dukakis aides insist there are other
scenarios that could produce a Dukakis win.
   Dukakis campaign vice chairman John Sasso, who has been directing
the campaign from the road as he travels with Dukakis, told
reporters Sunday that polling in the past 24 hours showed movement
toward Dukakis among undecided voters and soft Bush supporters.
   He said Bush's recent schedule changes to visit states shortly
after Dukakis showed the Bush campaign was worried that Dukakis was
closing the gap.
   ``I want to see if he's going to follow us now _ in the next 48
hours,'' Sasso said after informing reporters of Dukakis' plans to
campaign virtually without sleep from Sunday through Tuesday
afternoon.
</TEXT>
