<1ST_LINE>r a PM-People-ReddFoxx     11-07 0253</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-People-Redd Foxx,0258</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Anonymous Caller Tips Entertainer to Return of Stolen Jewelry</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAS VEGAS, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An anonymous phone call led entertainer
Redd Foxx to most of the jewelry stolen from his home in a $3
million burglary, including a half-pound gold watch given to him by
Elvis Presley.
   Foxx said he received the call Sunday afternoon at his home.
   ``Someone called and said if you want your stuff go to the fence
and get it before someone else does,'' Foxx said. ``My neighbor, Dan
Parker, went outside and a garbage bag was hanging from the fence.''
   According to a police report, the burglary occurred sometime
between Thursday, when Foxx, who starred as junk dealer Fred Sanford
on the television series ``Sanford and Son,'' left the city, and
Saturday, when he returned.
   Jewelry, furs and $107,000 in cash was taken.
   ``It has four lion heads on it with diamonds around the necks and
was designed by Elvis and engraved on the inside of it,'' he said of
the watch.
   Prince Spencer, Foxx's manager, said the burglars used an
electric saw to get into the side entrance of the house.
   ``They knew what they were doing because they cut through two
entrances so that they could enter and exit without the alarm going
off,'' Spencer said. ``Once they were inside, they got through a
sealed alarm closet and then they found a camouflaged safe and took
the money out without a forced entry. They bypassed all of the
alarms in the house.''
