<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Scotus-GagOrder     11-07 0552</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus-Gag Order,490</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Rejects Free-press Challenge in Biaggi Trial</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today rejected a free-press
challenge to a judge's order that barred participants in the
criminal trial of ex-Rep. Mario Biaggi, D-N.Y., from talking to news
reporters.
   The court, over three dissenting votes, turned away arguments
that the ``gag order'' a federal judge imposed during the
since-completed Wedtech Corp. corruption trial was an unlawful prior
restraint.
   Justices Byron R. White, William J. Brennan and Thurgood Marshall
voted to hear arguments in the case. But the votes of at least four
justices are needed to grant such review.
   White, in an opinion joined by Brennan and Marshall, said the
high court should resolve a conflict among federal appeals courts
over the issue of gag orders.
   Biaggi, who has given up the congressional seat he held for 20
years, was convicted of extortion, tax evasion, bribery and
conspiracy last August.
   Prosecutors said Biaggi extorted money from Wedtech, a defense
contractor in his south Bronx congressional district, in exchange
for his political clout.
   Biaggi stood trial with six others criminally charged in the
Wedtech scandal.
   Before the much-publicized trial began, U.S. District Judge John
M. Cannella ordered the defendants, their lawyers and the federal
prosecutors to refrain from making public statements about the case
other than to repeat what already was a matter of public record.
   Various news organizations objected to the order, contending that
it imposed a constitutionally impermissible prior restraint on the
press and on the free-speech rights of the trial participants.
   Past Supreme Court decisions have said prior restraints on speech
rarely are justified, and may be used only as a last resort to
ensure fair trials.
   But the 2nd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals, in upholding the
Wedtech trial gag order last March 14, ruled that it was not really
a prior restraint.
   ``There is a fundamental difference between a gag order
challenged by the individual gagged and the one challenged by a
third party; an order objected to by the former is properly
characterized as a prior restraint, one opposed solely by the latter
is not,'' the appeals court said.
   The appeals court suggested that it would be a prior restraint on
the press only if the news media already had the information and
were barred from publishing it.
   The appeals court noted that Cannella was troubled by what seemed
to be leaked information about the Wedtech-connected prosecutions.
   ``The problem begins not with the publishing of news by a free
press, but with a hemorrhage of small leaks of secret grand jury
information,'' the 2nd Circuit court said. ``This leads directly to
prosecutor and defense counsel inciting trial by the press.''
   In the appeal acted on today, five news organizations argued that
the appeals court wrongly subjected the gag order to a less rigorous
standard of review simply because it was challenged by potential
recipients of speech rather than potential speakers.
   The appeal urged the justices to outlaw such judicial orders
``without a finding that there is a serious and imminent threat to a
defendant's right to an impartial jury.''
   The five news organizations that filed the appeal are Dow Jones &
Co., CBS, NBC, The Associated Press and Newsday.
   The case is Dow Jones vs. Simon, 88-229.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881107-0082 </DOCNO>
