<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Maldives     11-07 0396</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Maldives,0412</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Authorities Question 100 Suspects In Attempted Coup</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RAJU GOPALAKRISHNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MALE, Maldives (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities today questioned about 100
people suspected of sympathizing with or taking part in last week's
failed coup in this Indian Ocean archipelago.
   The handcuffed prisoners were questioned at the National Security
Service office in the capital of Male, Maj. Mohammad Zahir said.
   He said most of them spoke Tamil, the language used by Sri Lankan
mercenaries who raided Male on Thursday and tried to overthrow
President Maumoon Abdul Gayoom's government.
   Maldivian officials said 14 people were killed and 40 wounded in
fighting Thursday. Some of the attackers took 27 hostages and fled
on a ship Friday, but the Indian navy forced their surrender at sea
Sunday.
   Indian commandos rescued 20 of the hostages, but four were
killed. Indian officials reported the three others missing.
   Zahir said officials detained 100 people ``because they had no
valid identification papers or travel documents on them, we suspect
some of them were involved in the attack or sympathized with it.''
   Also today, Maldivian officials said prepartions were under way
to install Gayoon for his third term as president Friday.
   Gayoon, 50, was elected president in 1978 after his predecessor
Ibrahim Nasir resigned and fled to Singapore. The 62-year-old Nasir
has been accused of misappropriating $4.2 million in state funds
during his 10-year rule.
   There were allegations that the failed coup was backed by Nasir.
Nasir has denied involvement.
   Gayoom has vowed to try the mercenaries. Asked what punishment
the mercenaries could receive if convicted, Gayoon said: ``I can't
tell you at this point, but we do have capital punishment.''
   Gayoom requested Indian assistance to quell the coup in his
2,000-island nation.
   The mercenaries gave up Sunday after the Indian frigate Godavari
fired on their vessel 60 miles from the Sri Lankan coast, Indian
officials said.
   Abdullah Luthufi, a Maldivian accused of masterminding the coup
attempt, was among 46 people who surrendered to the Indian commandos
aboard the cargo ship Progress Light, officials said.
   Luthufi was once an aide to Nasir, whose followers also tried to
overthrow Gayoom in 1980 and 1983.
   The foreign minister, Fathulla Jameel, said Luthufi hired the
mercenaries and came ashore with them Thursday.
   Maldivian and Indian officials say most of the 150-member
mercenary force escaped by sea. Indian naval ships have been
searching the area.
</TEXT>
