<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Poland 1stLd-Writethru a0467 11-07 0564</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Poland, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0467,0575</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Official Media Attacks Walesa as Strike Threat Looms</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 8 grafs with media attack on Walesa; PICKS up 5th
graf pvs, `On Saturday ...' Minor editing to TRIM</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The official media today launched an attack
on Lech Walesa in response to the Solidarity leader's threat of
strikes unless authorities suspend the decision to close the Lenin
Shipyard in Gdansk.
   An editorial in the Communist Party daily Trybuna Ludu said, ``In
the past, it was alleged that when the authorities lacked arguments,
they resorted to repression. Today, when Lech Walesa lacks
arguments, he loads the strike cannon.''
   The editorial follows remarks by the leader of the banned union
federation Sunday that he was prepared to call a nationwide ``strike
alert'' to demand preservation of the 10,000-worker shipyard, the
birthplace of Solidarity.
   The commentary was unusual because the official press recently
had avoided criticizing Walesa by name while the government and the
opposition prepared talks on Poland's future.
   But the proposed talks have stalled and now the government and
opposition appear to be on a collision course over the scheduled
Dec. 1 closing of the shipyard.
   ``In a period when concrete decisions are being made about
reforms ... Lech Walesa has a different plan: Strike alert and
strikes. It happened before. The country does not need strike amok
but reconciliation.''
   A statement released Sunday by Solidarity's national executive
commission threatened broad protests, including strikes, if the
government does not rescind the shipyard decision.
   It was the strongest from Solidarity since Communist authorities
announced Oct. 31 that they intend to close the shipyard.
   On Saturday, Walesa said he would not meet with Interior Minister
Czeslaw Kiszczak to discuss plans for the talks unless the shipyard
decision is suspended and all workers fired for taking part in
strikes in August are rehired.
   Walesa aide Piotr Konopka said the Solidarity leader told
worshipers at St. Brygida's church in Gdansk Sunday that he would
call a national ``strike alert'' at a workers' rally scheduled
Tuesday in the Baltic port.
   ``If there is still great pressure on him from the side of the
shipyard and other enterprises as well, then on Tuesday he will
announce a strike alert for the whole country,'' said Konopka.
   A ``strike alert'' would mean organizing strike committees and
getting workers prepared to strike at any moment, said Solidarity
spokesman Wojciech Maziarski.
   The Solidarity statement denounced the decision to close the yard
as `a dangerous political act'' and ``an act of revenge against
Solidarity.''
   It said any closures should be preceded by a period of review of
economic performance, with workers and their representatives taking
part.
   Since promising Aug. 31 to meet with the opposition to discuss
legalization of Solidarity and how to revive Poland's limping
economy, the government has discouraged prospects by insisting that
Solidarity drop two alleged extremists from its delegation to the
talks.
   That condition, together with officials' decision to close the
shipyard and the failure to rehire at least 100 workers fired for
roles in the August strikes, has convinced Solidarity that the
government is no longer interested in talks.
   Solidarity, the only independent labor movement ever allowed in
the Soviet bloc, was born August 1980 during a nationwide strike
wave, crushed in a December 1981 military crackdown and outlawed the
following year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
