<1ST_LINE>u p PM-Reagan 2ndLd-Writethru a0526 11-07 0741</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Reagan, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0526,730</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Says Bush Victory Would Assure `New Beginning'</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release 3:15 p.m. EST</NOTE>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 2 new grafs after pvs 15th graf bgng, He was flying,
with Fitzwater comments.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONG BEACH, Calif.(AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan told fellow
Californians today their votes could be crucial in assuring ``a new
beginning for America'' by electing Republican George Bush as
president and staving off a late-hour drive by Democrat Michael
Dukakis.
   In a speech prepared for delivery at the Queen Mary, a former
luxury ocean liner converted to a waterfront hotel, the 77-year-old
president said he was returning to his home state at the end of the
Bush campaign just as he did in his own campaigns for the White
House.
   ``Today, of course, is the last day of this, my last campaign as
president,'' he said. ``But tomorrow launches a new beginning for
America.''
   ``Your votes tomorrow may be the most important ones cast in
America,'' the president said. ``They will determine how California
goes, and California may send the next president to the White
House.''
   California has 47 electoral votes as the most populous state.
   Reagan lavished praise on Bush, who has served under him for
nearly eight years as vice president.
   ``This year, one of the best qualified men to ever seek the
office of president is on the ballot,'' he said.
   Of Bush's personal qualities, Reagan said, ``He is strong,
decent, loyal, wise, capable and compassionate.''
   ``As for his opponent, we only really began to learn about him
during the last few months,'' the president said. ``He has been
vague as to what he would do in office, yet when we focus on his
record, he objects.''
   Reagan contended that the Democratic nominee ``is against
voluntary prayer in school ... appointed judges to his state Supreme
Court who have voted to strike down a ban on child pornography ...
and, in every case, even for the most brutal crimes, he opposes the
death penalty.''
   ``He's free to have these views, but is this the man we want
choosing the justices to sit on the Supreme Court of the United
States?'' he asked.
   The former movie actor recalled that it was from the Queen Mary,
then a British liner, that he first saw the Statue of Liberty on his
return from England, where he filmed ``The Hasty Heart.''
   ``This is my last campaign, and seeing all of you ... and seeing
the Queen Mary again, it's like closing a circle, like sailing into
harbor after a long and wonderful voyage to be greeted by old,
beloved friends,'' the president said.
   From Long Beach, Reagan, 77, headed to San Diego for a nostalgic
visit to the seaside city where he held his final campaign rally on
the eve of his landslide re-election in 1984.
   He was flying for 10 hours and 20 minutes during a roundtrip from
Washington just to make two speeches in three hours and five minutes
in his home state.
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said Reagan will have
traveled about 25,000 miles and made 30 political appearances in 16
states for Bush since Labor Day, including today's trip.
   He said Reagan was making his first roundtrip to California in a
single day at the request of the Bush campaign because GOP polls say
the presidential contest is ``nip and tuck'' in the state.
   The former Hollywood movie star, who spent two terms in
Sacramento as governor, made seven earlier political appearances in
California during the current presidential campaign.
   He spoke in Long Beach and Irvine on Aug. 23, in Thousand Oaks
and Santa Barbara on Aug. 27, in San Diego on Oct. 27 and in
Fullerton and San Bernardino last Wednesday.
   San Diego is a prime target because the county is one of
California's most heavily Republican, with more registered GOP
voters than Democrats, although the Democrats hold a statewide
registration edge of 50.4 percent to 38.6 percent. San Bernardino
County also has more registered Republicans than Democrats, as does
Orange County, in which Irvine and Fullerton are located.
   The latest California Poll, conducted by Mervin Field and
released Thursday, gave Bush an 8-point edge among likely voters.
   However, an administration official traveling with Reagan on
Saturday, speaking on condition he not be identified, said more
recent Republican tracking polls showed that Bush's lead had
narrowed. Dukakis spokesmen said their polls showed the same thing.
</TEXT>
