<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Mandela     11-07 0353</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mandela,0365</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Winnie Mandela Visits Husband Amid Speculation of Release</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GREG MYRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAPE TOWN, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Winnie Mandela today paid a
hospital visit to her husband, African National Congress leader
Nelson Mandela. The government denied media speculation that he or
his colleagues would be released.
   Several South African newspapers have been quoting government
sources for the past week as saying Mandela would be released before
the end of the year from his life prison sentence. He was imprisoned
in 1962.
   The Prisons Service and other government sources emphatically
denied that either Mandela or any of the other five men imprisoned
with him for plotting to overthrow the government would be released
today. The officials would not comment on the possibility of
releases at a future date.
   Mrs. Mandela's visit lasted 45 minutes and was described by Cape
Town attorney Essa Moosa as normal.
   Moosa and the Rev. Allan Boesak, president of the World Alliance
of Reformed Churches, accompanied Mrs. Mandela.
   Boesak, an anti-apartheid activist, said there was ``no
indication (Mandela) would be released today or in the near future.''
   One government source indicated his belief that the rumors
circulating today were being orchestrated by members of the
anti-apartheid movement to pressure the government into taking some
action.
   The rumors have been building since August, when the 70-year-old
Mandela was transferred from Pollsmoor Prison to a Cape Town
hospital for treatment of tuberculosis. He was later transferred to
the private Constantiaberg Clinic, where doctors say he has
recovered.
   President P.W. Botha said he hoped it would be possible not to
send Mandela back to prison.
   Mandela has rejected Botha's offers to release him in exchange
for a renunciation of violence, saying the government must make a
similar renunciation and lift restrictions on black political
activity.
   In addition to Mandela, African National Congress
Secretary-General Walter Sisulu and four lesser known ANC members
are still in prison from the 1964 trial.
   Under apartheid, South Africa's 26 million blacks have no vote in
national affairs. The 5 million whites control the economy and
maintain separate districts, schools and health services.
</TEXT>
