<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BodyFound     11-07 0277</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Body Found,0283</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Body Found In Iowa, Omaha Boyfriend Charged In New York</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OMAHA, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A truck driver has been arrested in New York
City and charged with second-degree murder in the death of his
girlfriend, whose body was found in an Iowa drainage ditch after a
six-week search.
   Charles Houser, 32, of Omaha, was arrested without incident
Saturday night after he arrived in Manhattan with a truckload of
meat, according to a statement issued by Omaha police Lt. Larry
Roberts.
   The body of Janice Ross-Patterson, 34, a North High School
secretary, was found that morning along a drainage ditch near Neola,
Iowa, about 20 miles from Omaha. An autopsy performed Sunday
confirmed the identity, the police statement said.
   Ms. Ross-Patterson was reported missing after she failed to
arrive at North High for work Sept. 27. Police said early in the
investigation that Houser was the last person known to have seen
her. Her car was found in a grocery store parking lot.
   According to Roberts' statement, the autopsy found that Ms.
Ross-Patterson was killed by several blows to the head with a blunt
object.
   Her body was found about 100 feet from where a man from the Neola
area reported that he saw the missing woman's car Sept. 27. The
Neola man told police that a man, later identified as Houser, had
come to his home asking for help in pulling his car from a ditch.
   Ms. Ross-Patterson's body was found by the sixth weekend search
by relatives and volunteers. About 120 people joined the search
Saturday.
   Recent frost had reduced weed cover, allowing searchers to locate
the body, the police statement said.
</TEXT>
