<1ST_LINE>u a PM-CadetFuneral 4thLd-Writethru a0570 11-07 0554</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Cadet Funeral, 4th Ld-Writethru, a0570,0564</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Color Guards, Fellow Cadets Attend Funeral</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 7 grafs to UPDATE with more details from
procession, quote from homily; CORRECTS church capacity to 1,500,
picking up 6th graf pvs, `Among the ....' Adds byline.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TRUDY TYNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PITTSFIELD, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nearly a thousand officers from around
the Northeast marched today in the funeral procession of a police
cadet who collapsed during a rigorous training program.
   Timothy Shepard, 25, underwent a liver transplant a week after he
fell ill on a running track at the state-run police academy in
Agawam, near Springfield.
   He lapsed into a coma for two weeks, emerged, then lost
consciousness last Monday. He died Wednesday at a Pittsburgh
hospital. His death and the hospitalization of several other cadets
has prompted a re-examination of the state's police training
programs.
   ``Despite his pain, despite his suffering, his wracked body
hooked to machines, he smiled and he shed the light of his life on
all of us,'' the Rev. Peter Gregory, a family friend and chaplain at
Mercy Hospital in Springfield, said in his homily. ``God was with
him in a special way.''
   Scores of Pittsfield officers led the 150-cruiser procession to
St. Joseph's Roman Catholic Church, followed by police on
motorcycles and horseback, color guards from 50 departments in all
six New England states and New York, and members of the Pittsfield
Boys' Club. Shepard had been named the club's Youth of the Year in
1981.
   After the funeral, the procession was to head to St. Joseph's
Cemetery, a half-mile away, for burial.
   Lines outside the 1,500-seat church began forming more than an
hour before the funeral, and loudspeakers were hung outside the
building.
   Among the mourners were state police troopers from western
Massachusetts and the 46 cadets still training at Agawam. State
police said they scaled back their presence at the funeral from six
cruisers of troopers after Shepard's family initially asked that
state police not attend at all. They withdrew the request Sunday,
according to Pittsfield Mayor Anne Everest Wojtkowski.
   More than 2,000 people turned out for Shepard's wake Saturday and
Sunday. The police department's teletype machine has received
messages of condolence from all over the Northeast and even from as
far south as Delaware, said Lt. Gerald Lee.
   The last Pittsfield officer to die in the line of duty was killed
in 1898 while pushing a woman and her child to safety off the tracks
of an oncoming train.
   Shepard was one of 16 cadets hospitalized in the first week of
training. The illness prompted at least three state investigations
and resulted in the resignation of the head of the state's police
training program.
   An autopsy Friday indicated Shepard died from infections that set
in because of his weakened condition from training and a liver
transplant.
   Shepard had collapsed from heat stroke Sept. 19 at the end of the
grueling first day of training. Other cadets reported that they were
put through a strenuous regimen for hours on just a few cups of
water.
   Shepard's death will be the subject of an inquest to determine
whether criminal charges should be brought against the state
troopers in charge of training.
   A month-long investigation into the illnesses found a ``massive
failure'' of the system that led to abusive training.
</TEXT>
