<1ST_LINE>r w PM-DrugReport     11-07 0248</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Drug Report,230</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Emergency Rooms Seeing Many More Drug Cases: Report</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hospital emergency room admissions for
incidents involving cocaine and other drugs have grown dramatically,
according to excerpts from a federal report released today by Rep.
Charles B. Rangel, D-N.Y.
   The report, prepared by the National Institute on Drug Abuse,
compares changes from 1986 to 1987.
   Among the findings:
   _Emergency room admissions for cocaine-related cases increased
185 percent in Philadelphia; 108 percent in Phoenix, Ariz.; 74
percent in Chicago; 158 percent in Buffalo, N.Y.; 39 percent in New
York; 100 percent in Texas, and 122 percent in the District of
Columbia.
   _Cocaine has become so available that prices are dropping in most
cities including Atlanta, Buffalo, Chicago, Detroit and Miami.
   _Heroin-related emergency room admissions were up 37 percent in
the District of Columbia, 51 percent in Newark, N.J.; 45 percent in
Seattle; 60 percent in St. Louis, and 486 percent in New Orleans.
   _Admissions for marijuana-related cases were up 165 percent in
the District of Columbia, 100 percent in Newark, 53 percent in New
Orleans, 69 percent in Seattle, 100 percent in Texas and 316 percent
in Phoenix.
   Rangel, who released key findings of a similar study last year,
again criticized the Department of Health and Human Services for
what he described as its ``failure to widely disseminate this
extremely significant data, which clearly demonstrate the failure of
the administration's anti-drug policies to stem an expanding drug
crisis that afflicts our nation's urban centers.''
</TEXT>
