<1ST_LINE>r i PM-People-RingoStarr     11-07 0257</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-People-Ringo Starr,0263</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Beatle, Wife Reported Undergoing Treatment For Alcoholism</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto LON1</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Beatles drummer Ringo Starr and his wife,
actress Barbara Bach, are being treated for alcoholism at an
American clinic, his former press officer said today.
   Derek Taylor, the Beatles' press agent for six years, said the
couple had undergone four weeks of an eight-week program at the
unidentified clinic in the United States. Taylor's comments could
not be independently confirmed.
   He said Starr telephoned his London office from the United States
to announce the couple's admission to the clinic.
   ``The message he left was: `We are doing fine, we are very well
and we are in recovery','' Taylor said.
   ``Ringo wanted this to go public because it was already seeping
out through fellow guests at the clinic,'' he said. ``I got the call
from Ringo's London office to put out a statement saying he wished
it to be known he is a recovering alcoholic.''
   Taylor said the location of the clinic was being kept secret but
added: ``It is not in Los Angeles or New York.''
   Starr, 48, and Miss Bach, 39, were receiving treatment for their
addiction ``as equal members of a larger group,'' he said.
   Taylor said he had known Starr for 25 years and last saw him at a
party six weeks ago, but had not known him to be an alcoholic.
   The Beatles _ John Lennon, Paul McCartney, George Harrison and
Starr _ broke up in 1970. Lennon was murdered in New York in 1980.
</TEXT>
