<1ST_LINE>d a AM-BRF--CokeBust     11-07 0156</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Coke Bust,0159</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Missouri Authorities Seize 1,100 Pounds of Cocaine</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SPRINGFIELD, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   State police stopped a car for speeding
and discovered 1,100 pounds of cocaine valued at more than $70
million, authorities said.
   The cocaine was in cardboard boxes on the rear seat of a car
stopped Sunday on Interstate 44 on the east edge of Springfield, the
State Highway Patrol said.
   Patrol spokesman Sam Kaunley said the cache had a wholesale value
of $70 million, but he could not estimate its street value.
   James D. McCarnes and Willie G. Childress, two Los Angeles men
who were in the car, were arraigned Monday on charges of
transportation and possession of cocaine, according to the Greene
County court clerk.
   In 1986 at Miami, officials found 6,237 pounds of cocaine behind
a false wall of a cargo container aboard a Venezuelan freighter. And
in 1982, 3,243.2 pounds of cocaine were seized at the Miami airport.
</TEXT>
