<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CabbieSlain     11-07 0484</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cabbie Slain,0498</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cabbies Pass Up Fares, Avoid Tough Areas After 5th Slaying</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TED DUNCOMBE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The fifth slaying of a cabdriver this year in
Philadelphia has made cabbies wary about whom they pick up, where
they go and when they work.
   ``I don't cruise the streets,'' said Napoleon Conner, 43, a
five-year veteran. ``You find out the drug places; you don't go
there.''
   William Jones, 47, was stabbed by a passenger six times in the
head and chest early Sunday and left to die behind his steering
wheel in north Philadelphia, police said.
   Officer William Eiler heard brakes screeching and a crash, then
saw that the taxi had jumped a curb and stopped under a railroad
bridge, homicide Detective Sgt. Dennis Murray said.
   The passenger jumped out and yelled at Eiler, ``He tried to rob
me,'' before the officer lost him in the darkness, Murray said. A
bloody knife was found in the cab, police said.
   No arrest had been made Monday, said Detective Edward Tenuto.
   The state Public Utility Commission, which regulates taxis, does
not require the city's 1,532 licensed cabs to have bullet-resistant
shields separating the front and back seats to protect the drivers,
said Bernard Axelrod, a former cabdriver and a board member of the
United Cab Association. The shields are required in several cities,
including New York, Detroit and Boston.
   ``I know a lot of people are scared. I'm scared myself,'' said
Reginald Chukwurah, 26, who has been robbed once since he began
driving cabs in December. He said he no longer drives at night and
just looks for fares at hotels, train stations and airports.
   He only picks up people on the street if they are office workers,
couples or people with children.
   ``If it was just a single person just walking, I wouldn't pick
them up, regardless if they were white or black or whatever they
were,'' said Chukwurah, who is black.
   Even so, the man who robbed him was dressed up and carrying a
briefcase, he said.
   Albert Wilson, 57, who said he has driven a cab for about a year,
said he refuses to take people to housing projects.
   ``They might take you to a project and there might be people
waiting on you to rob you and maybe steal the cab, the radio, the
meter,'' he said.
   Two people have been charged with murder in the Sept. 18 death of
a cabbie who was found with a bullet wound in the back of his head.
   One man has been charged with murder and robbery in the July 24
death of a cabbie whose body was found riddled with bullets.
   No one has been arrested in the deaths of a cabbie shot in the
head on June 26, or of one who was stabbed Feb. 2 and staggered
along a street knocking on doors for help before collapsing.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
