<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Brites     11-07 0361</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brites,0373</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bright and Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANCHORAGE, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police on the Kenai Peninsula are
keeping an eye peeled for the one that got away, and by all accounts
it's a real whopper.
   The Alaska state troopers said a thief or thieves swiped a
14-foot-long king salmon made of plastic foam and fiberglass.
   The fish had been installed in front of Lynn and Kathey Kennedy's
tackle and fish-mounting business in Ninilchik, about 100 miles
southwest of Anchorage. Troopers said it was removed from its
mounting poles sometime Friday or Saturday.
   The trout of trouts is valued at $2,300, troopers said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEBRASKA CITY, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tired of paying for expensive deer
repellent, some farmers have adopted a substitute that makes for an
unusual sight across the countryside _ deodorant soap dangling from
trees like Christmas ornaments.
   Dennis Adams, a University of Nebraska extension forester, said
many subscribe to the old folk remedy that uses small pieces of
scented soap to help prevent deer from damaging trees.
   ``The damage has been increasing every year because the deer
population has been exploding,'' said Adams, who has hundreds of
small bars of soap hanging from trees on his farm.
   ``Some deer rub right next to the soap bars, but compared to the
damage we used to get, it's less,'' he said.
   Farmer William Holdorff has rigged bars of soap throughout his
orchard of 645 black walnut trees about 30 miles southeast of
Lincoln. He said he doesn't mind sharing some of his corn and milo
with deer, but needs some form of repellent to protect his small
trees.
   ``Actually, the odor isn't that strong or that repulsive, but
apparently the deer don't like it,'' Holdorff said. ``Their sense of
smell is more developed than ours.''
   At about 6 or 7 cents for a motel-size bar of soap, the cost is
much less than commercial deer repellents, he said. The small bars
of soap last through a growing season, he said.
   September is the best time to place soap in trees, Adams said.
One bar per tree should be hung from a branch at about the height of
a deer's nose, he said.
</TEXT>
