<1ST_LINE>r p AM-BRF--Bush-Raisins 1stLd-Writethru a0689 11-07 0207</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Bush-Raisins, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0689,190</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Demos Raising Ruckus Over Bush Crack</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf to FIX spelling of `raisins'</NOTE>
<DATELINE>FRESNO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrats ``heard it through the
grapevine,'' and now they want everyone else in the San Joaquin
Valley to hear a crack Vice President George Bush made about their
dancing raisins.
   Democratic House Whip Tony Coelho and the California Democratic
Party on Monday aired radio advertisements in the Fresno region
slamming Bush for a derogatory remark he made after canceling what
would have been his fourth campaign trip to the area.
   Bush said he ``didn't want to see those damned dancing raisins
again,'' according to his press secretary, Sheila Tate, who told the
Fresno Bee that Bush was only kidding.
   But in Fresno, the cereal bowl of the nation's raisin production,
insulting the popular dancing raisins could be considered sour
grapes, reasoned Coelho, who represents the region's raisin ranchers.
   People dressed in purple raisin suits have danced at numerous
events, including past Bush rallies in Fresno.
   ``Now they're after our raisins,'' Coelho says in the radio spot.
``Let's elect leaders who stand up for us.''
   Bush's local campaign chairman, Charles Poochigian, called the
radio ad ``a last-gasp effort to exploit a minor quip.''
</TEXT>
