<1ST_LINE>r a AM-People-Fogerty     11-07 0227</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-People-Fogerty,0232</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Singer Cleared of Plagiarism</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A jury on Monday cleared rock star John
Fogerty of an accusation that he plagiarized one of his own
Creedence Clearwater Revival songs for the tune of a recent solo hit.
   The six-member U.S. District Court jury deliberated less than
three hours before ruling unanimously against the copyright
infringement claim by Fantasy Records, which owns the rights to most
of the Creedence songs.
   The suit claimed ``Old Man Down the Road,'' lead single from
Fogerty's comeback ``Centerfield'' solo album in 1985, copied the
melody of ``Run Through the Jungle,'' which Fogerty wrote for
Creedence in 1970.
   Fogerty's defense included two days on the witness stand with
guitar in hand, playing many of his compositions to demonstrate his
style. The 43-year-old musician contended any similarities between
the songs were part of his musical style, dubbed ``swamp rock.''
   Fogerty was lead singer and songwriter for Creedence, one of the
nation's top rock bands from 1967 to 1972. After the group broke up
in 1972, he had no major commercial successes as a solo artist until
``Centerfield.''
   The suit is one of several legal disputes between Fogerty and
Saul Zaentz, principal owner of Fantasy Records. Zaentz has sued
Fogerty for libel over two other songs on ``Centerfield,'' one
called ``Mr. Greed'' and the other originally titled ``Zanz Kant
Danz.''
</TEXT>
