<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ParoleBoardTrial     11-07 0360</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Parole Board Trial,0369</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Trial Begins in Woman's Suit Against Parole Board for Releasing
Inmate</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JACKSON, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Trial began Monday in the lawsuit of a
woman who was shot and paralyzed by a parolee and is now seeking $4
million in damages from three state Parole Board members.
   Opening arguments began in the suit of former bank executive
Linda Grantham, 46, of Florence, who was shot in February 1985 by
parolee Clem Jimpson. She remains paralyzed from the neck down.
   If Grantham wins her suit, ``not only the Parole Board, but any
public official or employee could face far-reaching liability in the
course of their duties,'' Deputy Attorney General Robert Gibbs said.
   On May 2, the state Supreme Court ruled that Grantham has the
right to sue the three Parole Board members who voted for Jimpson's
parole _ Ollie Sykes, James Figgs and Paul Carter. One other member
voted against parole while a fifth member was not at the meeting.
   The Supreme Court had overturned a 1986 ruling by Circuit Judge
William F. Coleman of Hinds County, who said members were immune
under state law because they had acted in their official capacity.
   Jimpson was paroled from the Mississippi State Penitentiary at
Parchman on Jan. 9, 1985, after serving 12 years and three months of
a life sentence for murdering a convenience store clerk.
   The lawsuit alleged the board did not review his case properly,
failing to take into account such things as his behavior in prison
and the nature of his original crime.
   Jimpson shot Grantham at a parking lot of a bank where she was an
assistant vice president. Prosecutors said he thought she was
carrying cash from the bank.
   The 60-year-old Jimpson is serving a sentence of life without
parole at Parchman for shooting Grantham.
   Grantham's attorney, Lisa Milner, said a victory by her client
could affect the way criminals are paroled.
   ``I think the outcome, if we win, will have an effect on the
process in the future,'' she said. Problems might not exist ``if the
Parole Board was doing what is required by law,'' she said. ``Our
position is they are not.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881107-0112 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-07-88 1635EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Gucci     11-07 0286</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gucci,0294</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gucci Heir Gets Suspended Sentence For Attempted Fraud</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MILAN, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Maurizio Gucci, an heir of the founder of the
Gucci luxury goods company, was convicted of attempted tax fraud
Monday and given a $750 fine and a one-year suspended sentence.
   Vittorio Ajello, the lawyer for Gucci, said the decision means
Gucci will regain control of shares that will give him half of the
company.
   Gucci was accused of having arranged the falsification of the
signature on the documents to avoid paying inheritance taxes by
making it appear that his father, Rodolfo, transferred ownership of
the shares before his death in 1983.
   Gucci's ownership of the shares was not in question, only when
the transfer was made. The court froze the shares to assure he could
pay any fine levied in the tax fraud case.
   He had faced a possible penalty of three years in jail and a fine
of about $23 million.
   However, the court fined Gucci only $750. It also gave him a
one-year suspended sentence and said his criminal record will be
expunged at the end of the year. Gucci also must pay the inheritance
tax on the shares.
   The court also convicted Gucci employees Gian Vittorio Pilone and
Ciro De Vincenzo, the notary that authenticated the signatures, of
the same charges. The two were given the same suspended sentence and
fine. The court also prohibited De Vincenzo from acting as a notary
for one year.
   The court also acquitted four others, including a woman accused
of actually signing the documents.
   Gucci is the great grandson of Guccio Gucci, who founded the
company in 1922. The company has 180 stores worldwide and its sales
last year totaled $170 million.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
