<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Reagan     11-07 0773</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reagan,750</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Bids Sentimental Farewell, Boosts Bush in California</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release 5:50 p.m. EST</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Election Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN DIEGO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan took his last,
sentimental bow on the campaign stage Monday with a plea for
California voters to assure a ``new beginning for America'' by
tipping the balance in favor of Republican presidential nominee
George Bush.
   In speeches delivered alongside the retired ocean liner Queen
Mary at Long Beach and at a rally near San Diego's performing arts
center, Reagan saluted old friends, ``freedom fighters'' and
political prisoners, and paid a rare public tribute to his parents.
   ``So now, we come to the end of this last campaign, and I just
hope that Nelle and Jack are looking down on us right now and
nodding their heads and saying their boy did them proud,'' Reagan
said.
   Likewise, he told his listeners he hoped they would tell their
children and grandchildren that ``a certain president came to town
at the end of a long journey'' and that ``a century of peace,
prosperity, opportunity and hope followed.''
   Climaxing 25,000 miles of travel to 16 states on Bush's behalf,
the president stressed that California, with its 47 electoral votes,
could provide the margin of victory for the GOP ticket in Tuesday's
election. Recent polls show Bush and Dukakis have fought virtually
to a draw in the nation's most populous state.
   ``Today, of course, is the last day of this, my last campaign as
president,'' he said in Long Beach. ``But tomorrow launches a new
beginning for America.
   ``Your votes tomorrow may be the most important ones cast in
America. They will determine how California goes, and California may
send the next president to the White House.''
   Reagan was returning Monday night to the White House, where he
will watch election returns Tuesday night with friends and political
advisers. Aides said Bush was expected to meet with Reagan there
Wednesday.
   On his arrival at Long Beach, reporters asked Reagan what the
polls were telling him. The president grinned and replied, ``I'm
going to wait and see what that last poll tells me tomorrow.''
   Asked if he had a hunch about the outcome, he replied, ``I'm
afraid to say what it is. I'm superstitious.''
   Although the Bush campaign clearly expected Reagan to provide a
crucial boost in California, his speech indicated that his reasons
for making the 14-hour round trip between Washington and the West
Coast on election eve were as much personal as political.
   ``I'm not doing this just for George Bush,'' he told GOP
stalwarts in San Diego in his most personal and introspective speech
in years. ``I'm doing it for the country of course, but for someone
else as well _ actually for two other people.''
   Reagan has inserted references to his mother in a few speeches
recently, but he has hardly ever spoken publicly of his father, an
alcoholic shoe salesman whom he described Monday as ``the best
storyteller I've ever heard _ and the strongest man of principle
I've ever known.''
   The president said Jack Reagan once nearly caught pneumonia
sleeping in his car instead of taking a room in the only hotel in
town because ``it discriminated against certain groups of people.''
   He said that even in the darkest days of the Depression, his
parents never refused a meal to anyone who knocked on their door.
   ``So, you see, I'm also campaigning this year for them,'' Reagan
said. ``A son of Jack and Nelle Reagan never walked away from a
battle on principle. This year's election is that kind of fight, and
by darn, we're going to win it.''
   At the get-out-the-vote rally in San Diego, Reagan sounded a bit
wistful when he noted that his name won't be on the ballot Tuesday.
But he said that didn't matter ``because something more important is
_ a principle, a legacy.''
   He added: ``No, this is not the end of an era; it is a time to
refresh and strengthen the `new beginning' we started eight years
ago.''
   He said the importance of Tuesday's balloting extended far beyond
U.S. shores.
   ``Tomorrow on the plains of Afghanistan and in jungles around the
world, freedom fighters will huddle close to their radios, hoping to
catch word that the administration in America will remain their
friend,'' he said.
   ``In cells across the globe, political prisoners will wait
anxiously for assurance that America has chosen strength over
weakness, because for many of them, our strength is all that keeps
their hopes alive. ... And so help me God, we won't let them down,''
Reagan said.
</TEXT>
