<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Sudan     11-07 0383</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sudan,0395</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sudan Receiving Military Aid From Libya, Premier Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMED OSMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KHARTOUM, Sudan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Sadek Mahdi said Sudan
received military aid from Libya to help quell a southern rebellion,
but he denied allegations that Libyan troops were fighting alongside
the Sudanese army.
   Mahdi spoke to reporters after a Cabinet meeting Sunday that
focused on Sudan's economic crisis, last week's riots against food
shortages and relations with neighboring Libya.
   Six days of riots that began Oct. 29 in Khartoum injured 58
police officers and five other people, Mahdi said.
   The rioting was started by high school students who were later
joined by university students and Moslem fundamentalists.
   Thousands of young people took to the streets of the capital to
protest shortages of staples such as bread and sugar, as well as
soaring prices. The protesters hurled stones at public buildings,
burned tires and clashed with police, who countered with tear gas
and batons.
   Mahdi said the rioters destroyed a police station and caused
minor damage to the Internal Trade Ministry building. Twenty
vehicles, including three private cars, were completely or partially
wrecked, he said.
   Elyaba James Surur, leader of the opposition Union of Sudanese
African Parties, said Sunday that Libyan troops were helping
Sudanese soldiers fight the southern rebels, who are mostly
Christians and animists demanding greater autonomy from the
Moslem-dominated government.
   Surur, whose union represents a group of southern factions, said
the Libyans operate from a headquarters at Juba, the capital of the
southern region of Equatoria.
   The rebellion, which began in 1983, is costing the government
about $1 million every day. Sudan suffers from a chronic shortage of
hard currency and has built up a foreign debt of about $13 billion,
defaulting on repayment.
   Mahdi acknowledged his government has received military aid from
Libya and other Arab countries, but he denied the presence of Libyan
troops in the south.
   ``Those fighting the (southern rebellion) are 100 percent
Sudanese troops,'' Mahdi said.
   In 1987, Sudanese officials said four Libyan-supplied MiG-23
warplanes flew combat missions against southern rebels. At least one
was reported to have crashed.
   The government repeatedly has charged that neighboring Ethiopia
provides arms and money to the Sudan People's Liberation Army of
rebels led by John Garang, a former Sudanese army colonel.
</TEXT>
