<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0632,0792</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Palestinian Kills Soldier and Is Shot to Death by Farmer</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 7 grafs UPDATING with more wounded, guerrilla
sentenced; PICKS up 6th pvs `According to' and minor editing
thereafter to TRIM.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto JRL1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN ALT POWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MASSUA, Occupied West Bank (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Palestinian worker angry over
unpaid wages killed a soldier on guard duty at a Jewish settlement
Monday and an Israeli farmer shot the assailant to death, witnesses
reported.
   The Palestinian shouted ``Allahu Akbar,'' an Islamic war cry
meaning ``God is great,'' as he stabbed the soldier, said settlers
at the Massua cooperative farm 26 miles northeast of Jerusalem.
   Army spokesmen confirmed a Palestinian woman was shot to death in
a West Bank village.
   Arab sources said 21 Palestinians were wounded by soldiers in the
West Bank and Gaza Strip, where a revolt against Israeli occupation
began Dec. 8, 1987, among the 1.5 million Palestinian residents.
   Hospital officials said two 9-year-olds were among the wounded _
one shot in the leg and the other in the chest.
   A military court in the Gaza Strip sentenced the leader of a
guerrilla squad to three consecutive life prison terms for murdering
three other Palestinians suspected of collaborating with Israel. A
second member of the guerrilla group was sentenced to one life term.
   Eleven Israelis and at least 309 Palestinians have been killed in
the Palestinian uprising, which enters its 12th month Tuesday. The
guard at Massua was the second soldier killed.
   According to the army, the 21-year-old attacker approached the
soldier about 9 a.m., drew a knife and ``stabbed him repeatedly, at
least a dozen times.''
   Tanya Ben-Ami reported seeing the attack from the nearby farm
office. ``In the beginning there was a struggle,'' she said. ``In
the end, (the Arab) just kept stabbing all the time. He didn't
stop.''
   She said a farmer on leave from army reserve duty was with her,
ran to get his gun and opened fire after the Palestinian picked up a
chair and threatened him. Ms. Ben-Ami said the farmer ``didn't have
a choice. He shot him.''
   Settlers said the Palestinian attacked after the soldier
requested additional identification. The army spokesman said he had
worked at the farm and and was angry about not receiving back pay of
170 shekels, about $100.
   The slain soldier was identified as Cpl. David Danieli and the
Palestinian's papers said he was Ahmad Hussein Abdullah Basharat of
Tamoun village, near Jenin.
   An area about five yards square was roped off by the time
reporters were allowed at the scene, with a chair in the middle
where the soldier had sat.
   A pool of blood was in front of the chair. Underneath it were an
overturned thermos, a radio and a book printed in Hebrew.
   Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin and Gen. Dan Shomron, army chief
of staff, visited Massua after the shooting. Settlers complained to
Rabin about lack of security and he told reporters in English: ``We
cannot go on without a proper response to what happened here today.''
   Igal Hanassy, a 41-year-old farmer, told Rabin as he left that
Palestinians working at the cooperative should be replaced with
Jewish volunteers. Rabin said he had nothing to do with arranging
for volunteers, Hanassy told reporters later.
   Asked about security, Hanassy replied: ``It's obviously not
enough. There was only one soldier at the gate. He was killed.''
   The Massua farm, about 18 years old, is a mile from the border
opposite a Jordanian village. The settlers grow bananas, grapes,
dates and flowers with the help of 100 or so Palestinians who work
as day laborers.
   In Jerusalem, Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir's right-wing Likud
bloc and the center-left Labor Party of Foreign Minister Shimon
Peres continued competing for the chance to form a government after
last week's inconclusive elections.
   Attacks on Israelis tend to boost the fortunes of hard-liners and
a firebomb attack on a bus Oct. 30 that killed a teacher and her
three young sons was believed to have cost Labor three seats in the
120-member Knesset, or parliament.
   Likud won 40 seats, one more than Labor, and is given the best
chance of making a coaliton with religious and rightist parties.
   Army spokesmen said soldiers went on the offensive Monday against
Palestinian rioters in the occupied territories, which Israel
captured from Jordan and Egypt in the 1967 war.
   They said a 23-year-old woman was killed when soldiers opened
fire during a large, violent protest at Salem village 3 miles east
of Nablus. A resident reached by telephone at a Salem hospital said
the dead woman was Ismat Jamil Mahmoud, 20.
</TEXT>
