<FILEID>AP-NR-11-07-88 1620EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Dail-A-Porn     11-07 0541</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dail-A-Porn,520</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Firm Agrees To Pay $50,000 Fine In `Dial-a-Porn' Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A California firm agreed Monday to pay a
$50,000 fine and stop transmitting obscene messages on interstate
telephone lines in a case which the government said signals all
``dial-a-porn'' services that they must act to keep their material
inaccessible to children.
   Audio Enterprises Inc., of Mill Valley, Calif., and operator
Wendy King signed the agreement, entailing one the first dial-a-porn
fines imposed by the Federal Communications Commission.
   ``The $50,000 payment that the dial-a-porn operator will have to
pay to the government ... shows that there will be a high price
attached to failure to obey the law scrupulously in this important
area,'' said Gerald Brock, head of the FCC's common carrier bureau.
   ``This sends a signal there are some teeth in the law,'' Brock
said. Enforcement of the civil penalty was done ``quickly and
efficiently compared with the alternative of extensive and costly
litigation,'' he said.
   FCC officials said Audio Enterprises is effectively out of
business. There was no current listing for the company in telephone
information.
   To resume operations, King or Audio Enterprises must tone down
the messages and use access codes, credit cards or scrambling
equipment to prevent children under 18 from dialing. Such operations
will be monitored by the FCC, according to the agreement.
   The FCC launched its investigation of Audio Enterprises after a
mother in California wrote that her 13-year-old son and his friends
spent $74 dialing a pay-to-listen 900-number for 211 minutes.
   Also listening was the woman's daughter, who was later molested
by two boys who had heard the tapes, the woman wrote. ``This phone
call has damaged our lives,'' the woman wrote.
   The FCC informed Audio Enterprises last December that it was in
apparent violation of FCC's rules that require companies to restrict
access of obscene material. The commission also informed Intercambio
Inc., of San Jose, Calif., that it was in violation of the law, and
that case is still pending.
   The FCC determined the material broadcast by the two companies
was obscene. Under a Supreme Court's test, material is obscene if it
depicts sexual acts in a patently offensive way, appeals to the
prurient interest of an average person and lacks serious literary or
artistic value.
   FCC officials estimated Audio Enterprises collected about
$250,000 in revenues over a two-year period.
   Altogether, the dial-a-porn industry produces about $54 million
annually in revenue for providers and phone companies, according to
the Information Industry Bulletin.
   The FCC has referred some complaints to the Justice Department.
In May 1987, two dial-a-porn providers pleaded guilty to failing to
comply with the commission's rule. The court fined them each $50,000.
   Earlier this year, Congress passed a sweeping dial-a-porn law
that bans obscene and indecent commercial messages. The law has not
been enforced because of legal challenges in New York and California.
   The principal issue centers around the definition of indecent
material. The FCC deems material indecent if it depicts or describes
sexual or excretory organs or activities in a patently offensive
way. The dial-a-porn industry says the definition is too broad and
unconstitutional.
   Congress passed another measure last month, but it has not been
signed yet by President Reagan.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881107-0121 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-07-88 1654EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Bentsen 1stLd-Writethru a0711 11-07 0787</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bentsen, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0711,760</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Precede HOUSTON</HEAD>
<HEAD>Bentsen Devotes Most Of Final Day To Texas</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Top three grafs new with Beaumont appearance, picking up 4th
graf pvs, ``Are we ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEAUMONT, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lloyd Bentsen stubbornly insisted an
election victory was in sight, telling voters there would be ``no
surrender'' as he capped his vice presidential campaign Monday with
a wild scurry across Texas and nearby swing states.
   ``No retreat, baby, no surrender,'' he said, quoting a Bruce
Springsteen song as he fired up supporters at an airport hangar in
this East Texas town.
   In Houston, Bentsen said he could ``remember how Jack Kennedy and
Lyndon Johnson carried Texas.'' Surrounded by family and political
allies, he asserted, ``We carry Texas and we carry it all.''
   About 3,000 people cheered the candidate as he spoke in the
Houston City Hall park where he and Dukakis had campaigned together
the day after the Democratic National Convention in July. The crowd
was even bigger then.
   ``Are we going to take Texas Democratic?'' he said. ``Are we
going to elect Mike Dukakis and Lloyd Bentsen president and vice
president of the United States?''
   Bentsen spent most of the day working in Texas despite polls
showing a double-digit lead for the Republicans there, and a recent
concession by one of Dukakis' top aides that the state was lost.
   ``Go flat out. ... Win Texas and then the United States,'' he
told supporters at a Dallas rally. ``It's in your hands to win it.
You can do it.''
   On the stage with Bentsen at Dallas' Union Station was a live
quail in a cage.
   ``How do you like the idea of George Bush as president and Dan
Quayle standing in the wings,'' he said, turning his thumb down as
the crowd hooted.
   Bentsen loaded his jet with Texas state officials, extra staff
and actress Lori Singer and took off with a loudspeaker in the cabin
blaring the theme song from the movie ``Top Gun.'' The unofficial
theme song for the former bomber pilot was repeated at rallies
throughout the day.
   He had the plane make a low-altitude pass of the runway before
landing in Shreveport, La. Then he strolled to the podium as the
high school band played, ``Where Is The Love.''
   ``The momentum is really going our way,'' he said, chiding
Republicans for
   ``popping their champagne corks'' too early.
   ``On Nov. 9, they're going to have one of the worst hangovers
they've ever had,'' he said.
   The 67-year-old candidate bounded back up the airplane stairs two
steps at a time.
   After Houston, Bentsen had two more stops in Texas _ Beaumont and
San Antonio _ before heading to Arkansas and Missouri. He planned to
return to the Texas capital city, Austin, when the campaign day was
to end only a few hours before the polls opened Tuesday.
   He planned to spend election day in Austin. He voted by absentee
ballot in Rio Grande City late last month.
   Bentsen continued to insist that Texas and its 29 electoral votes
are winnable for the Democrats, even though many polls show him and
Dukakis trailing by double digits.
   The Dukakis campaign's Boston headquarters added two more stops
outside of Texas to Bentsen's schedule for Monday: Little Rock,
Ark., and Kansas City, Mo. The campaign also considered sending
Bentsen back to California, where he has campaigned frequently.
   Although several state campaigns were trying to get him to appear
on the eve of the election, Bentsen said he insisted that he wrap up
his effort in Texas.
   For Bentsen, it was a day for hammering at the same themes that
he's used for weeks: attacking Bush's choice of Quayle as running
mate and echoing Dukakis' new populist theme of ``We're on your
side,and they're not.''
   He also jabbed at Bush, implying again that the vice president
was not a true Texan, as he claimed.
   Nearly 200 Texas banks have failed in the past few years, and
Bentsen accused George Bush of doing nothing for his claimed home
state while the Reagan administration was helping bankers in
Illinois and New York.``We want a Texan in there who's interested in
Texas,'' Bentsen said. ``We're going to help Texas.''
   Jim Hightower, the Texas state agriculture commissioner who
joined Bentsen's entourage Monday, said the senator was doing what
he needed to do even though the polls looked bad.
   ``We're not sitting and being poll watchers, but trying to be
pole vaulters,'' he said.
   Hightower said the populist message Dukakis was now using on the
stump should have come three months earlier and it may be too late.
``We're pedaling uphill with not very many minutes left,'' he said.
</TEXT>
