<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CadetFuneral     11-07 0608</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cadet Funeral,0623</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hundreds of Mourners, Police Attend Funeral of Police Recruit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TRUDY TYNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PITTSFIELD, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   With the blessings of a bishop and the
salutes of nearly 1,000 police officers, the city buried a police
recuit Monday who died 44 days after collapsing on his first day of
training, a session that sparked turmoil in the state's law
enforcement agencies.
   Hundreds of residents, unable to get in the packed 1,500-seat
church, lined both sides of the main street outside St. Joseph's
Church as the Most Rev. Joseph Maguire, Roman Catholic bishop of
Springfield, said the funeral Mass for 25-year-old Timothy Shepard.
   ``Timothy did not quite realize his desire to be a police
officer, but perhaps in God's mysterious plan he may have had a
higher role,'' the bishop said.
   Shepard's illness and the hospitalization of 15 other cadets in
late September led to at least three state probes, the resignation
of the head of the state's police training programs, and the
transfer of State Police instructors and the director of the Agawam
academy where the cadet collapsed.
   The service was broadcast on loudspeakers, and there was
bitterness and sadness on the faces of the residents who stood in
the chilly November drizzle for more than two hours.
   Many residents, such as Irene Kibbee, had not known the young
man, who was married in June and whose wife is pregnant. But they
knew he was the most seriously stricken of the cadets who were
hospitalized with exhaustion and dehydration following a grueling
regimen of laps and pushups on a few cups of water.
   ``It's so senseless. What did they think they were doing with
that training?'' Mrs. Kibbee said. ``Your heart can't help but go
out to that poor boy's family.''
   Pittsfield Police Officer Anthony Riello said Shepard's death has
created ambivalence in the force about training methods.
   ``The mood in the department is extremely sullen,'' he said.
``The problem we have in dealing with it (Shepard's death) is that
it is so senseless. It shouldn't have happened.''
   The last Pittsfield officer to die in the line of duty was killed
in 1898 while pushing a woman and her children to safety off the
tracks of an oncoming train.
   The funeral cortege, the largest ever in this city of 50,000
people, took nearly 15 minutes to pass. Two Pittsfield police
cruisers led the way, followed by motorcycle officers, mounted
police and more than 100 cruisers from Nantucket to Schnectady, N.Y.
Their lights flashed in a sea of twinkling blue and red as they
slowly passed the silent crowd.
   State Police were represented by three cruisers. They had scaled
back plans for six cruisers when Shepard's family asked that they
not attend because of bitterness over his training by state
troopers. The family withdrew the request Sunday, according to Mayor
Anne Everest Wojtkowski.
   ``They reconsidered and agreed that there are many fine and
compassionate state policemen and they should be made welcome,'' she
said.
   Shepard collapsed Sept. 19 from heat stroke and was flown to a
Pittsburgh hospital while still in a coma for a liver transplant.
   The cadet had emerged from a coma after two weeks and was slowly
recovering _ even writing his wife, ``I made it'' _ when he fell
unconscious again Oct. 31 and was rushed into emergency surgery to
remove a blood clot on his brain.
   He was pronounced dead Wednesday. An autopsy indicated he died
from infections that set in because of his weakened condition.
   His death is the subject of an inquest later this month to
determine whether criminal charges should be brought against the
instructors.
</TEXT>
