<2ND_LINE>AM-Election Day Weather,250</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Typical Fall Weather Forecast For Election Day</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Election Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's Election Day forecast calls for
typical fall weather that one meteorologist said means should-be
voters have no excuse not to ``get out there and have at it'' at the
ballot booths.
   The National Weather Service summary for Tuesday forecast rain
showers along the Great Lakes and from western Montana across Idaho
and the Pacific Northwest. High temperatures were expected to range
from the 40s to the 80s.
   ``There's nothing terribly strong out there, no blizzards or
downpours or flooding,'' said meteorologist Dan Mullen at the
National Environmental Satellite Data and Information Service.
``There's no bitter cold that might keep people in.''
   Mullen said his advice to voters was: ``Everybody get out there
and have at it.''
   Only about 50 percent or less of eligible voters were expected to
vote this year.
   High temperatures in the 40s and 50s were expected from New
England across New Jersey, over the northern Appalachians, the Great
Lakes, the upper half of the Mississippi Valley, the northern half
of the Plains, the upper Missouri Valley, the Rockies, the northern
half of the Plateau and the northern half of the Pacific Coast.
   Temperatures were expected to reach the 70s and 80s from the
southern Atlantic Coast across the Gulf of Mexico states, in Texas
except for the Panhandle, and in the inland Southwest.
   High temperatures for the remainder of the nation were forecast
to be generally in the 60s.
