<DOCNO> AP881107-0132 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-07-88 1902EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-UN-Afghanistan     11-07 0572</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-UN-Afghanistan,0591</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.N. Official Says Suspending Withdrawal Does Not Violate Agreement</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VICTORIA GRAHAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press WRiter</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet decision to suspend its military
withdrawal from Afghanistan does not violate the U.N.-mediated
Geneva accord, the chief U.N. spokesman said Monday.
   ``The Geneva agreements are being implemented. ... At the moment,
there is no violation of the agreement,'' Francois Giuliani,
spokesman for Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar, told
reporters.
   He was asked at the regular daily briefing whether Perez de
Cuellar had any comment on the Soviet announcement Friday that it
was suspending withdrawal because of Pakistani and U.S. aid to
Afghan guerrillas.
   Giuliani said: ``There is no comment because under the Geneva
agreements that is envisaged.''
   Asked to explain, he said: ``What is envisaged ... is that troops
be withdrawn by the 15th of February, 1989, and that half of them be
withdrawn by the 15th of August, and this has been done.''
   ``They have said they are suspending their troop withdrawal,''
Giuliani said. ``That is not a violation of the Geneva agreements.
... The Geneva agreements are being implemented. At the moment,
there is no violation of the agreement.''
   In its announcement Friday, the Soviet Union said it still hopes
to have its troops out by Feb. 15.
   Moslem insurgents began fighting after a Communist coup in April
1978 and Soviet soldiers entered Afghanistan in December 1979. An
estimated 115,000 were in the country when the withdrawal began last
May 15.
   When asked about a statement by the Soviet ambassador to
Afghanistan that the supply of arms to guerrillas by the United
States and Pakistan ``practically torpedoes'' the accords, he
replied:
   ``The secretary-general hopes and is confident that the Geneva
agreements would be implemented.''
   In an interview published Monday, Foreign Minister Abdul Wakil of
Afghanistan demanded a halt in U.S. and Pakistani aid to the Moslem
insurgents.
   Bakhtar, the official Afghan news agency, quoted him as saying:
   ``We have stated on more than one occasion that Afghanistan will
not remain indifferent to the incessant violations of the Geneva
accords. A joint Soviet-Afghan decision to suspend the withdrawal of
Soviet troops from Afghanistan was a response to it. The ...
opposition must stop the armed struggle.''
   He said new, heavier weapons brought in by the Soviets were for
defensive purposes, ``intended not for threatening anyone but for
suppressing the hotbeds of resistance of the armed opposition.''
   Sophisticated MiG-27 ground-attack jets and SS-1 Scud missiles
have been sighted in Afghanistan. The United States says their
presence raises questions of whether Moscow intends to comply with
the Geneva withdrawal agreement.
   Giuliani said Perez de Cuellar had not yet read the text of
statement the Soviet Foreign Ministry issued Friday. The Soviet
Union has criticized the 50-man U.N. observer force sent to monitor
the withdrawal and investigate possible violations by either side.
   The Soviets have asked for a report on the work of the observers,
who the Kremlin says are not doing their job.
   The agreement signed in Geneva in April by Afghanistan and
Pakistan, with the United States and Soviet Union as guarantors,
provides for troop withdrawal and non-interference in internal
affairs. The guerrillas were not a party to the negotiations and
continued to fight.
   Moscow says the arming of insurgents by Pakistan and the United
States violates the agreement. Washington says the Soviets violated
it by providing more arms to the Afghan army and introducing the new
weapons.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
