<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Lahd 2ndLd-Writethru a0737 11-07 0393</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lahd, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0737,0403</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Israeli-backed General in Lebanon Shot</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New throughout with details from Beirut and Israel, Lahd's
condition, identity of woman. CORRECTS Lahd's age to 61. Adds
byline. No pickup.</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Israel, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FAROUK NASSAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Lebanese woman shot and wounded Maj.
Gen. Antoine Lahd, a former army officer who commands Israel's
surrogate militia in south Lebanon, media reports and Israeli
spokesmen said.
   The Christian-controlled Voice of Lebanon said the woman shot
Lahd, head of the South Lebanon Army, on Monday at his home in
Marjayoun, provincial capital of Israel's self-proclaimed ``security
zone,'' an area 6 to 10 miles deep just north of the Israeli border.
   Lahd was flown by Israeli military helicopter to Rambam hospital
in the northern Israeli port of Haifa, where spokesman Zvi
Ben-Yishai said he was in stable condition and was undergoing
surgery to remove a bullet from his arm.
   ``He was hit in one of the blood vessels in the upper part of the
right arm,'' Ben-Yishai said.
   Voice of Lebanon radio, run by the rightist Christian Phalange
Party, an ally of Lahd's 2,000-man militia, identified the assailant
as Soha Bihara from Deir Mimas village in the security zone.
   Deir Mimas has a predominantly Christian population, but some
Shiite Moslems also live there.
   The Christian Lebanese Broadcasting Corp. television station in
Beirut said Ms. Bishara ``has been visiting Lahd almost daily in the
last two weeks, seeking a job. When she was walking out of his house
today, she opened her handbag, drew a pistol, turned around and shot
him.''
   It said Lahd's aides arrested the woman immediately and she was
being interrogated at his Marjayoun headquarters.
   In Israel, a military spokesman confirmed a woman shot Lahd, but
gave no details.
   Maj. Gen. Yossi Peled, head of Israel's northern command, visited
Lahd at Rambam Hospital Monday night, hospital officials said.
   Lahd, a Maronite Catholic, studied at the Ecole De Guerre in
France and Ft. Benning, Ga. He took command of the militia September
1984.
   Lahd and the SLA have been the target of Palestinian, pro-Syrian
leftist and Iranian-backed Shiite Moslem factions trying to drive
Israel from the zone established in June 1985, when it withdrew
nearly all its forces after a three-year occupotion to rout out
Palestinian guerrillas.
   Israel has about 1,000 soldiers in the zone.
</TEXT>
