<1ST_LINE>r p AM-BRF--Quayle-Brite     11-07 0189</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Quayle-Brite,190</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Quayle Happy To See Campaign End</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Election Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A playful Dan Quayle turned the tables on his
inquisitive press corps Monday as an often rocky campaign for the
vice presidency neared its end.
   The Republican vice presidential nominee, arriving at Dulles
International Airport to kick off his final day of campaigning,
approached reporters waiting at the stairway of his Baltimore-bound
jet.
   ``This is the last day,'' he exclaimed to a crowd poised to fire
questions at him.
   As Quayle, Secret Service agents and reporters gathered in a
circle, the senator grabbed one of the reporters and swapped places
with him, putting him in the line of fire.
   Then Quayle, scion of publishing giant Eugene Pulliam, proceeded
to play reporter:
   ``Why are you hiding out in Baltimore today?''
   ``Is this your hometown? Is that the reason you're going back to
Baltimore? Come on!''
   Quayle had been inundated in recent days with questions about his
late-stage campaign schedule that suggested George Bush's
presidential campaign was trying to hide him during the waning days
of the race for the White House.
</TEXT>
