<FILEID>AP-NR-11-07-88 1911EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-UN-GulfTalks     11-07 0439</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-UN-Gulf Talks,0450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Longest Direct Talks; No Progress Reported</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran and Iraq met for five hours Monday in their
longest face-to-face session since peace negotiations began Aug. 25,
but the Iranian delegate described it as ``long talks, no progress.''
   U.N. mediator Jan Eliasson described the encounter between Ali
Akbar Velayati and Tariq Aziz, foreign ministers of Iran and Iraq
respectively, as a ``helpful meeting'' in a ``businesslike
atmosphere.'' He said another session would be held Tuesday.
   Aziz said he would send a letter to Secretary-General Javier
Perez de Cuellar calling his attention to a statement by the
``commander of the Iranian guards'' who he said had urged that
reinforcements be sent to the front. He did not identify the
commander.
   ``We feel this statement is a very grave one,'' Aziz said. ``I
made it clear to the Iranian and the U.N. delegations that if the
Iranian side is using any threats nobody is afraid.''
   Iran and Iraq went to war in September 1980 and at least 1.5
million people were killed or wounded before a cease-fire began Aug.
20.
   Aziz said Iraq had not reinforced its positions on the 730-mile
border front but had new weapons to use ``against external
aggression.'' U.N. observers are stationed between the two armies
along the border.
   Velayati told reporters negotiations remained stuck on point one
of Security Council Resolution 598, which covers withdrawal of
forces to ``internationally recognized borders.'' The cease-fire
resolution also provides for prisoner exchange and peace
negotiations.
   In an interview with Iran's official Islamic Republic News
Agency, Velayati said no Iranian troops were left on Iraqi territory
but Iraqi forces occupy nearly 400 square miles of Iranian land.
   The southern border is the most contentious issue because it
falls in the disputed Shatt-al-Arab, Iraq's only outlet to the sea.
   Just before the war started, Iraq repudiated a 1975 treaty that
draws the line down the middle of the waterway. It wants the line
returned to the Iranian shore, as it was before the treaty.
   Iran considers the treaty still valid.
   Perez de Cuellar offered a compromise last month calling for
military disengagement and exchange of the estimated 100,000
prisoners, combined with dredging of the Shatt-al-Arab and an
Iranian pledge to stop searching ships in the Persian Gulf for
war-related cargo.
   The waterway, which Iran calls the Arvan River, is blocked by
ships stranded by the war, unexploded shells and silt that collected
during eight years.
   An IRNA dispatch from Geneva quoted Velayati as saying the U.N.
mediators must produce new ideas ``if they want the talks to move
ahead and out of the current relative deadlock.''
</TEXT>
