<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Cambodia     11-07 0400</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cambodia,0411</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cambodian Peace Talks Make No Progress</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHE CACHERA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   FERE-EN-TARDENOIS, France (AP) _ Peace talks among Cambodian
factions made no substantial progress Monday but the leaders agreed
to meet again and to establish a working committee of their
representatives, officials reported.
   The talks in this village 70 miles east of Paris are to end
Tuesday.
   Attending the conference are neutralist Prince Norodom Sihanouk,
leader of a loose alliance of three resistance groups fighting the
Vietnamese-installed Cambodian government; anti-communist Son Sann
and communist Premier Hun Sen of Cambodia.
   The fourth Cambodian faction, the Communist Khmer Rouge, had been
invited but the three other leaders rejected the Khmer Rouge's
proposed envoy, Ok Saukun who is Cambodia's ambassador to the U.N.
Educational, Scientific and Cultural Organization. They said he was
not qualified for a ``summit'' meeting.
   The three agreed to meet again in France early next year.
   The resistance groups fighting the government are Sihanouk's
supporters, Son Sann's guerrillas and the Khmer Rouge.
   Prince Norodom Ranariddh, Sihanouk's son and spokesman, said Hun
Sen's position had hardened. He said the Cambodian government wanted
to link the withdrawal of Vietnamese troops to an end to foreign aid
to the resistance groups.
   Son Sann and Sihanouk said the withdrawal of Vietnam's military
forces from Cambodia must take place before any aid to the
resistance is ended.
   ``It is unacceptable to put the foreign occupation of Cambodia
and the just resistance of the people on the same level,'' Ranariddh
told reporters. ``We will not compromise.''
   Another main point of disagreement is the dismantling of the
Cambodian regime. It was installed by the Vietnamese after they
invaded Cambodia in Decemer 1978 and ousted the Khmer Rouge that had
defeated the U.S.-backed government in 1975 at the end of the
Indochinese war. Hundreds of thousands of Cambodians perished during
the brutal Khmer Rouge effort to destroy all opposition and create a
rural society.
   Sihanouk is demanding the Hun Sen government be replaced by a
four-party administration. Hun Sen has indicated the status quo be
maintained until ``free and democratic elections'' can be held.
   Sihanouk and Son Sann believe that no agreement will work that
leaves out the Khmer Rouge, which has the strongest military force
in the resistance. Hun Sen's position is that the Khmer Rouge must
first be disarmed to avoid another civil war.
   ``On these essential points divergences remain,'' said Ranariddh.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
