<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Reagan-Homeless     11-07 0246</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reagan-Homeless,240</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Signs $1.2 Billion Homeless Bill</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN DIEGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan signed legislation Monday
authorizing a two-year, $1.2 billion program for the homeless,
saying it would permit the government to ``address effectively the
plight of those who do not have shelter.''
   The bill authorizes $633.8 million for the current fiscal year
and $675.8 million for the fiscal year that will begin next Oct. 1.
   ``It ensures that the federal government, directly and through
cooperative efforts with state and local governments and the private
sector, can address effectively the plight of those who do not have
shelter,'' the president said.
   Funds are authorized for the Federal Emergency Management Agency,
which aids the work of non-profit organizations and local
governments in providing shelter, food and other services. Money
also will go to the Department of Housing and Urban Development for
grants for renovation of buildings for use as emergency shelters and
for their operation.
   ``The act authorizes funds for a program of particular importance
that serves both the medical needs of the homeless and the national
objective of a drug-free America,'' Reagan said. He said he referred
to a Department of Health and Human Services program of grants to
public or private nonprofit organizations for health and substance
abuse services for the homeless.
   The act expands the job Training Partnership Act to assist
individuals in developing marketable skills, the president said.
   The measure amends legislation initially sponsored by the late
Rep. Stewart McKinney, R-Conn.
</TEXT>
