<1ST_LINE>r p AM-BlackVote     11-07 0574</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Black Vote,580</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Black Turnout Expected To Equal 1984 Level</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Election Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Black leaders expressed confidence Monday that
blacks would turn out to vote in large numbers, despite a
presidential campaign widely regarded as lackluster.
   They predicted get-out-the-vote efforts by Democrat Jesse
Jackson, black churches and other organizations will produce a
tunout as large or nearly as large as in 1984, when blacks turned
out in record numbers.
   Many analysts are predicting the overall turnout Tuesday will be
less than the 53 percent of American adults who cast their ballots
in 1984, and some believe blacks will not turn out for Dukakis as
strongly as they did for Walter Mondale, who got 90 percent of the
black vote in 1984.
   Blacks make up 11.1 percent of the adult population and have
voted overwhelmingly Democratic since the New Deal.
   Curtis Gans, executive director of the Committee for the Study of
the American Electorate, said registration is down among blacks and
``I can't conceive of black turnout not being lower than in '84.''
   Stephen Hess, a senior fellow at the Brookings Institution, said
black voters in 1984 ``had a feeling of affection'' for Walter
Mondale. ``I don't see that they feel that way for Michael
Dukakis,'' he said. ``He was the fellow who beat their man
(Jackson).''
   Many Jackson supporters were upset last July when Dukakis failed
to notify Jackson beforehand that he had chosen Lloyd Bentsen of
Texas for his running mate.
   But Jackson has crisscrossed the country on behalf of the
Dukakis-Bentsen ticket, logging 55,700 miles and addressing 745,000
people in 191 events in 29 states, according to Frank Watkins, a
Jackson spokesman.
   John E. Jacob, president of the National Urban League, said, ``I
think Jesse has done everything he could to say to black America
that he is not mad about that, and even if he were, that the states
are still too high for that to be a reason for blacks not going to
the polls.''
   Jacob predicted the black vote will be at least as large as it
was in 1984. ``There has been a tremendous amount of work going on
around the country on the part of the black infrastructure _ black
churches, black community organizations _ that is not getting
visible media attention,'' he said.
   The Rev. Benjamin L. Hooks, executive director of the NAACP,
said, ``We've had a fairly unexciting campaign in turning people on
to vote.''
   ``There was a period when many black people felt let down,'' said
Hooks, but he added that grassroots get-out-the-vote efforts and
Jackson's constant campaigning have turned that around.
   ``I think that black voter turnout will be substantial, but
perhaps not as large as it could have been had there been more
coverage of issues and of Jesse Jackson,'' said Hooks. He predicted
it would be ``very close to the '84 turnout.''
   Hooks said that in states with significant black populations,
``wherever Dukakis is running a tight race with Bush in the white
community, black voters ... could be the deciding factor.''
   Pollster Gordon S. Black said his organization, which conducts
polls for USA Today and Cable News Network, found no evidence in its
final pre-election survey of any likely drop in black turnout.
   After interviewing nearly 700 blacks in a survey group of 6,613,
Black said, ``we have absolutely no evidence that there's a (black)
turnout drop at all.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
