<1ST_LINE>u i AM-India-Sikh     11-07 0373</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-India-Sikh,0384</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sikh Gunmen Kill Hindu Army General</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HARBAKSH SINGH NANDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHANDIGARH, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sikh gunmen shot and killed an Indian
army general in Punjab state Monday, police said. Five days of Sikh
separatist violence left at least 79 people dead in the northern
Indian state.
   Maj. Gen. B.N. Kumar, a Hindu, was shot in the head by two Sikh
gunmen as he left his home in Chandigarh to go to his office, a
police spokesman said.
   The assailants, who were waiting in a car, fired 40 to 45 rounds
and escaped, said the spokesman, who under regulations cannot be not
identified.
   Kumar, 56, was serving on the Bhakra Beas Management Board, which
overlooks the work of the Bhakra Nangal Dam. The dam, one of the
largest in the world, is in neighboring Himachal Pradesh state but
provides irrigation water for a vast area of Punjab.
   Bhakra Nangal is 93 miles northeast of Chandigarh.
   The motive behind the killing was not immediately known, but
several sources said Sikh radicals had vowed to kill officers of the
board. The radicals have accused the board of suddenly releasing
water from the dam in September without any advance warning, causing
floods.
   Kumar denied the charge Oct. 17 in a statement issued in
Chandigarh.
   At least 702 people died and 192 are still missing in the floods
that forced tens of thousands of people out of their homes.
   Sikh radicals are campaigning for an independent Sikh homeland in
Punjab, claiming they are discriminated against by the Hindus,
India's religious majority, and need a way to maintain their
cultural and religious traditions.
   Sikhs account for only two percent of India's 880 million people,
while the Hindus make up about 82 percent. However, Sikhs are a
majority in Punjab.
   On Thursday, Sikh radicals ambushed a bus and killed 11 people in
Gujarpura. On Friday, they exploded seven bombs in a crowded market
in Batala, killing 28 people and wounding 50 others.
   Also Friday, a group of Sikh gunmen attacked a seed farm near
Lawdohwal, killing 20 Hindus. In other attacks, Sikh radicals killed
14 people across the state on late Friday and Saturday.
   On Sunday, Sikh radicals killed five people in the state.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
