<DOCNO> AP881107-0142 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-07-88 1907EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Amnesty-Applicant     11-07 0546</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Amnesty-Applicant,0561</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Amnesty Applicant Proud of Resident Status</HEAD>
<BYLINE>With AM-Amnesty-Residency, Bjt
^By HOLDEN LEWIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>EL PASO, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Shane O'Neil ignored the blinding lights of
television cameras and passed his oral English and civics tests with
flying red-white-and-blue colors Monday, becoming the first amnesty
recipient in West Texas to earn permanent U.S. residency.
   The 31-year-old San Angelo ranchhand, wearing a blue bandana
around his neck and clanking spurs on his dusty boots, calmly
recited the colors of the U.S. flag, explained what the flag's 13
stripes symbolize, told how many states are in the union, identified
Ronald Reagan as the president and defined the Constitution as the
supreme law of the land.
   After filling out a short test with similar questions and having
his fingerprints taken, the Yugoslavian was given his permanent
residency card.
   ``I wasn't scared of ... any questions,'' O'Neil said as he gazed
at the card. ``It's just exciting, I guess, getting something like
this. It's liberty for me.''
   Joining O'Neil as first-day permanent residency recipients were
Juan Helguera Segovia and Feliciana Gutierrez.
   All three entered the United States illegally and were among the
first in line in May 1987 to apply for amnesty from deportation
under the Immigration Reform and Control Act of 1986. That allowed
them to be among the first to apply for permanent residency under
the second phase of the amnesty program.
   All three entered the United States for different reasons and all
three qualified for permanent residency under different criteria.
   O'Neil, who took that name after he got to the United States 15
years ago, refused to divulge the name he was born with. He said he
was born in a town about 25 miles from Belgrade called Golubinci
Stara Pazova.
   At 16, he joined the merchant marine and got work aboard a ship
that cruised up the St. Lawrence Seaway to Chicago. He got off the
ship in Chicago and never got back on.
   ``I left for political reasons,'' he said. ``I believe in
liberty, and I've always believed in God. I'm Catholic.''
   Helguera, a well-service worker in Odessa, got permanent
residency by showing that he had taken English and civics classes at
Odessa College. The 28-year-old native of Durango, Mexico, came to
the United States nine years ago to seek work.
   ``In the nine years, they (the Border Patrol) stopped me only
once,'' he said. ``They gave me 15 days to leave, but I didn't
leave.''
   His wife, Dolores, said she plans to apply for permanent
residency in a few months, when she becomes eligible.
   Mrs. Gutierrez moved to El Paso with her daughter, Ofelia Haller,
in 1978. The 88-year-old native of Hidalgo de Parral, Mexico, was
exempt from the English and civics requirement because of her age.
   ``I'm glad and very thankful,'' she said of getting permanent
residency.
   All three said they plan to apply for citizenship. O'Neil, a
staunch supporter of the Republican Party, seemed the most eager to
become a citizen. Because he is married to an American citizen, he
most likely will be able to vote for president in 1992.
   Asked if he wished he could vote in the 1988 presidential
election, O'Neil said: ``Oh, you bet, of course. I sure hope Mr.
Bush will win tomorrow.''
</TEXT>
