<2ND_LINE>AM-Burma-Press,0222</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lawyer Accused of Providing Sensitive Information to BBC</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RANGOON, Burma (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A lawyer appeared in court Monday charged
with violating national emergency laws by providing sensitive
military and political information to a foreign news agency, Burmese
state radio reported.
   It said Nay Min, 42, gave the information, described by the
broadcast as ``false rumors,'' to the British Broadcasting Corp.
   Nay Min also is accused of defaming the government and inciting
unrest. If convicted he could be sentenced to a maximum of seven
years in prison.
   The broadcast did not give any deatils of Nay Min's court
appearance but said the hearing was adjourned until Nov. 21.
   Nay Min was arrested at his home in Rangoon on Oct. 21. after
providing sensitive information by telephone to a BBC correspondent
based in Dhaka, Bangladesh, according to the report.
   It said the lawyer, who reportedly used the codename ``Eastern
Star,'' also made telephone calls to London on a regular basis.
   Nay Min was not an accredited BBC correspondent, the broadcast
said.
   Burma went through months of violent street demonstrations by
people demanding democratic reforms until Gen. Saw Maung seized
power in a military coup on Sept. 18.
   More than 450 people have been killed as Saw Maung's security
forces cracked down on anti-government protests.
