<FILEID>AP-NR-11-07-88 1957EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SpyStrike     11-07 0409</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Spy Strike,0419</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>One-day Strike Disrupts Government Offices</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tens of thousands of civil servants struck for one
day Monday to protest dismissal of union workers at an intelligence
headquarters, disrupting such government offices as welfare and
driving-test centers.
   Neil Kinnock, leader of the opposition Labor Party, told a mass
rally of civil servants in London: ``We believe that solidarity,
like liberty, must be indivisible. And we believe that solidarity,
like charity, begins at home.''
   The rally was one of about 60 held to protest the firings of five
men at the Government Communications Headquarters, a huge facility
at Cheltenham in southwest England that monitors transmissions from
the Soviet Union. Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher says its work is
too sensitive to risk disruption by strikes.
   In London, Kinnock greeted 2,500 civil servants in Polish and
said: ``I do it in that way because we have solidarity with the
belief that the freedoms of organization, assembly and expression
must know no boundaries.
   ``We don't just want freedom in Gdansk, we want it in GCHQ. We
don't just want dialogue and freedom to choose in Poland, we want it
in Cheltenham.''
   Mrs. Thatcher visited Poland last week and met with Lech Walesa,
founder of the outlawed independent union movement Solidarity.
   After Labor made the comparison again later Monday, in
Parliament, Civil Service Minister Richard Luce responded: ``Don't
you understand the difference between true democracy, with freedom
under the law, with a freely elected parliament?
   ``National security has to come first, and the GCHQ needs to
operate on a continuous basis if they are to be effective.''
   The five men were fired for flouting a 1984 ban on unions at the
facility. Twelve other men face retirement, compulsory transfer or
dismissal.
   They were the holdouts among one-third of the 7,000 employees who
were union members in 1984. Others accepted payment of 1,000 pounds
each (then worth $1,400) for quitting their union.
   None of the rebels was fired until this year, but union officials
said the government tried to freeze them out with such tactics as
refusing pay raises.
   The Council of Civil Service Unions, an umbrella for Britain's
eight civil service unions, said ``80 percent-plus walkouts'' closed
many employment and welfare offices, state-run job and driving-test
centers.
   Civil servants also walked off jobs in customs offices, prisons,
airports and magistrate courts, and spokeswoman Anne Kenefeck said:
``We're thinking 200,000 is not a bad estimate'' for the number of
strikers.
</TEXT>
