<2ND_LINE>AM-Quayle, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0659,620</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Precede ROANOKE, Va.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Bush Running Mate Ready For Voters' Verdict</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Election Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Top eight grafs new with Quayle's homecoming; picks up 3rd
graf pvs, The 41-year-old ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   FORT WAYNE, Ind. (A ) _ Sen. Dan Quayle, ``finally at home'' in
his native Indiana, got a hero's welcome Monday night as he
concluded an occasionally rocky campaign for the vice presidency.
   In a boisterous rally that took on the flavor of a political
convention, Quayle, thanked a crowd of about 2,000 for supporting
him through times of tribulation.
   ``There have been weeks of wild exhilaration along with personal
testing, and we knew you were there,'' Quayle said, without
referring specifically to the controversy that swirled about him in
the days following his Aug. 17 nomination by the Republican National
Convention to be George Bush's running mate.
   ``My fellow Hoosiers, I am finally at home,'' he said. ``It is
here, with your help, that I entered public service.''
   Quayle had been besieged by questions from news organizations
about the circumstances surrounding his enlistment in the Indiana
National Guard at the height of the Vietnam war in 1969 and the
question of whether he benefited by undue influence in getting
admitted into the Indiana University law school with a ``C'' average
on undergraduate work at Depauw University.
   Earlier, Quayle said Americans must ``say good night'' to
Democratic presidential candidate Michael Dukakis if they want to
save the changes wrought during President Reagan's eight years in
office.
   During a rally at an aiport hangar in Roanoke, Va., nestled in
the Blue Ridge Mountains, he declared: ``Let me say to the citizens
of Virginia: Michael Dukakis is not on your side.''
   The 41-year-old Indiana senator, confident about the GOP ticket's
election prospects Tuesday, told reporters he was satisfied with the
way he handled his role as George Bush's vice presidential running
mate and is ready for the voters' verdict.
   Borrowing a slogan used by Virginia's tourist industry, Quayle
said Dukakis ``knows that Virginia is for lovers, not liberals.''
   Quayle mocked Dukakis' populist ``on your side'' campaign theme.
``He's on your back,'' the senator said. ``He's in your pocket. And
on Tuesday night, he's out of luck. And that's when we'll be saying,
`Say good night, Mike'.''
   Touring a Westinghouse electronics plant near Baltimore earlier,
Quayle told reporters the Republican ticket had ``a really good
shot'' in heavily Democratic Maryland, ``and if we can win Maryland,
we're gonna be well on our way to victory come this Tuesday.''
   ``It's been an exhilarating campaign,'' Quayle said, ``but it's
time to come to an end and let the people make their decision.''
   He told reporters he was pleased with his campaign role, which he
saw as a ``lightning rod'' for attacks by Dukakis and his running
mate, Lloyd Bentsen.
   ``Actually, that's part of our strategy,'' Quayle said. ``We want
them to attack the vice presidential candidate and to leave George
Bush alone. We want George Bush to go out and be able to speak to
the people.''
   ``He's running for president, and all the fire they want to
direct at me _ we're delighted,'' Quayle said.
   He ducked a question whether he was concerned about polls
suggesting that voters have lingering doubts about his fitness for
the vice presidency.
   ``The true test is, how does George Bush do in the election,''
Quayle replied. ``That's the only test I'm interested in.''
</TEXT>
