<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Chile 1stLd-Writethru a0731 11-07 0363</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Chile, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0731,0371</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pinochet Replaces Army's Representative On Junta</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 8 grafs UPDATING with Gordon's replacement
appointed, Gen. Siebert resigns from army. PICKS up 6th graf pvs
bgng: The junta also ...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The army's representative on the ruling
four-man junta resigned Monday and his replacement was named, as
part of changes wrought by President Augusto Pinochet in the
military branch that is the backbone of his power.
   Pinochet, the army's commander, accepted the resignation of Gen.
Humberto Gordon from the junta, said a statement issued by army
headquarters. No reason was given for the resignation.
   Gordon, 61, served on the junta since December 1986.
   Hours later, another communique announced thar Gen. Santiago
Sinclair, 58, an officer noted for his fervent personal loyalty to
Pinochet, had been picked by the 72-year-old president to replace
Gordon.
   The move apparently prompted the retirement of Gen. Bruno
Siebert, public works minister and a Pinochet loyalist, who had more
seniority than Sinclair. Although leving the army, Siebert woul kept
his Cabinet post, the government said.
   Until last week, Sinclair had been the army's deputy
commander-in-chief, the man who handles the day-to-day business in
the service, as Pinochet devotes most of his time to the presidency.
   Sinclair was replaced by Gen. Jorge Zincke, 54, considered less a
hardliner than this predecessor.
   Last week, Pinochet reshuffled the highest ranks of his army,
sending 13 generals into retirement. He also promoted 10 brigadiers
to the rank of general.
   The junta also includes the commanders-in-chief of the navy, air
force and national police. It has served as a legislature in the
absence of a congress, which was disbanded when Pinochet seized
power in a bloody 1973 military coup that ousted the elected leftist
government of Salvador Allende.
   Pinochet last month lost a referendum in which citizens refused
to extend his rule to 1997 and voted for a transition to democracy.
   Elections for a civilian congress and a successor to Pinochet are
scheduled for December 1989.
   Since the 1973 coup, the army's representative on the junta has
changed four times. The navy's representative, Adm. Jose Merino, has
been a junta member since the coup.
</TEXT>
