<1ST_LINE>r a AM-WeatherpageWeather     11-07 0284</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0294</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Winter Settles In The Upper Great Lakes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Snow fell on Upper Michigan and across west central Minnesota
into southeastern North Dakota on Monday, but much of the nation has
fair weather.
   Snowshowers extended from southern New York state into northern
Pennsylvania, becoming rainshowers from central Pennsylvania and the
lower Great Lakes into central New England.
   Winter weather also has a firm grip on part of the Northwest,
with a snow advisory posted through Tuesday for the higher
elevations of the Washington Cascades
   One inch of snow fell at Fargo, N.D., and Mount Washington, N.H.,
during the 6 hours ending at 1 pm EST.
   Temperatures were warmer than normal over much of Texas, with
Fort Worth reaching 88 degrees, a tie for their 1963 record for the
date.
   Temperatures around the nation at 2 p.m. EST ranged from 32
degrees at Houghton and Marquette, Mich., to 90 degrees at Junction,
Texas. The low temperature for the nation Monday was 12 degrees at
Lake Yellowstone, Wyo.
   The national weather forecast for Tuesday called for rain
extending along the Great Lakes and from western Montana across
Idaho and the Pacific Northwest.
   High temperatures will be in the 40s and 50s from New England
across New Jersey, over the northern Appalachians, Great Lakes, the
upper half of the Mississippi Valley, the northern half of the
Plains, upper Missouri Valley, the Rockies and the northern half of
the Pacific Coast.
   Temperatures will reach the 70s and 80s from the southern
Atlantic Coast across the Gulf of Mexico states, Texas except for
its Panhandle, and the inland Southwest. High temperatures over the
remainder of the nation will generally be in the 60s.
</TEXT>
