<1ST_LINE>r a AM-HomelessProtest-Phila     11-07 0440</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Homeless Protest-Phila,0455</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Protesters Arrested Attempting Occupation Protest</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Stands for AM-Homeless Protest listed on the News Advisory.</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Homeless-Protest</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto PX8</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE LINDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Twenty-nine homeless people protesting a lack
of housing were arrested across from the Liberty Bell on Monday when
they tried to occupy a federal office building and an adjoining
courthouse.
   Nearly 50 men and women, a few holding children, sought to enter
the William Green Federal Building on the edge of Independence
National Historic Park.
   Group members said they planned to sit-in at the ninth floor
offices of U.S. Sen. John Heinz, R-Pa., and set up a temporary
homeless shelter, but they were barred at the main entrance, and a
scuffle ensued.
   Two federal policemen were pushed to the ground but were not
injured.
   Federal marshals and building police brought out 3-foot riot
sticks and plexiglass shields and massed in front of the inside
lobby. The equipment was never used.
   Protestors then circled the building, to the courthouse side,
where only people with a government ID card or who could show they
had business inside were allowed in.
   The protesters distributed leaflets that demanded the government
restore $25 billion for housing programs that was cut from the
federal budget.
   Peter Coles, director of the federal security officers, said his
plan was to keep the building open for business but to prevent any
occupation _ and he ordered all but two doors left open so people
could get in or out.
   The chants outside increased _ ``What do we want? Houses. When do
we want them? Now'' _ and the demonstrators, some locking hands in a
tight chain, began pushing and shoving, Cole ordered all the doors
locked inside.
   Outside the demonstrators chained the doors shut.
   Hundreds of federal workers, jurors and attorneys blocked from
going to lunch crowded into the cafeteria on the second floor of the
Green building. Others who got out had to use the basement garage
entrance to get back in.
   That's when U.S. Attorney Michael Bayleson, on behalf of the
General Services Administration, went to U.S. District Judge Edward
Cahn who issued ``under the urgent circumstances'' a temporary
restraining order directing that those blocking the doors provide a
path for people to get in and out.
   When the protestors refused to budge, federal marshals and local
police moved in and carried 29 people to vans that took them to a
federal detention center in the courthouse basement.
   All were later released on their own recognizance and ordered to
appear for hearings.
   Last week, seven people were arrested at a sit-in at Heinz's
Washington office.
</TEXT>
