<1ST_LINE>u p AM-CampaignTV 2ndLd-Writethru a0781 11-07 0874</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Campaign TV, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0781,850</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis, Bush End TV Campaign With Half-Hour Appeals</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 11 grafs new material on Bush, Dukakis programs;
picks up 10th graf pvs, In the course</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Election Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrat Michael Dukakis and Republican George
Bush made half-hour network appeals for votes Monday night, the
final chapter in a long, often nasty television war that played a
key campaign role.
   Dukakis, the underdog, hit on traditional Democratic themes in a
program featuring him on the stump, dancing with his wife, playing
the trumpet and answering questions from voters at town meetings.
   Much of the program featured questions posed by people taped at
locations all around the country, asking questions about Dukakis'
seeming coldness during the campaign, his reluctance to respond to
attacks and his positions on defense.
   ``Maybe I don't wear my heart on my sleeve, but my passion is in
my service to the public,'' said the Massachusetts governor,
appearing in a red pullover sweater in a room filled with books.
   Dukakis spent much of the half hour responding to issues raised
by Bush, among them his crime record and his defense positions. If
elected, he told one questioner, ``you can bet your life ... that
this nation will be defended and defended well.''
   The Bush film included sizable chunks of his nomination
acceptance speech and clips from debates as well as a number of his
campaign commercials, dropped virtually unedited into the middle of
the program.
   President Reagan, Barbara Bush, the Bush children and the Bush
grandchildren all appeared in the program, and Bush's media adviser,
Roger Ailes, played a brief offscreen role as interviewer. But vice
presidential nominee Dan Quayle, whom polls have shown to be a drag
on the ticket, was nowhere to be found.
   Bush said at one point that he respected his opponent. But the
program included reiterations of his criticism of Dukakis for
opposing the death penalty, school prayer and a law requiring
teachers to lead the Pledge of Allegiance, and for supporting a
liberal prisoner furlough program.
   In one of the only new segments, Bush contended: ``My opponent
has no experience in national security affairs. I don't believe we
can take a risk on an issue as important as our national security.''
   In the final days before the election, Dukakis intensified his
television drive in key medium-sized and small states while Bush
added a slashing five-minute attack ad to his TV mix. The lengthy
Bush commercial is a reprise of his attacks on Dukakis' record on
crime, the economy and the environment.
   Dukakis, whose program prominently featured vice presidential
nominee Lloyd Bentsen, opened his network appeal with footage from
an Oct. 26 town meeting in Naperville, Ill.
   In the course of the broadcast he addressed questions about
family, jobs, senior citizens, hunger and farmers. He also attacked
the Republicans' agricultural policy and charged that they would
balance the budget by cutting Social Security.
   Dukakis touted his management of the Massachusetts economy,
saying he had inherited ``a financial and economic basket case''
that is now an economic success story. And he belittled what he
called ``the only new idea George Bush has had since this campaign
began _ a new $40 billion, five-year capital gains tax giveaway for
the very rich.''
   ``Now who is going to pay for that tax break?'' Dukakis demanded.
``Look beside you. Look behind you. Look in the mirror and ask
yourself, is George Bush on your side?''
   It was left to Bentsen to complain about Bush's hardball media
strategy. ``The people of Texas have been outraged by the
distortions the Republicans have made with their commercial TV,'' he
said. And he contended that voters are also ``deeply concerned''
about the choice of Quayle.
   Bush did not appear in his five-minute broadside against Dukakis.
Instead, state residents, officials and others were shown charging
that Dukakis was responsible for budget deficits, tax hikes, job
losses, Boston Harbor pollution and a prison furlough program.
   ``It's a broad overview of everything that Michael Dukakis stands
for, according to his record,'' Bush ad director Sig Rogich said
Monday.
   He said the ad was running in selected markets and denied it was
introduced in response to narrowing poll margins. ``It was planned
long ago,'' Rogich said.
   Dukakis intensified his media drive over the final weekend in
eight states where polls showed the race was tightening, as a hedge
against potential losses in one or two large industrial states. The
expanded buys were in Arkansas, Colorado, Kentucky, Louisiana,
Missouri, Montana, New Mexico and South Dakota.
   All told, Dukakis was running eight ads in spot markets in 30
states as his campaign ended, according to spokeswoman Lorraine
Voles. Most of them stressed his ``on your side'' slogan. Another
attacked Bush's record as head of a drug interdiction task force and
his choice of Quayle and there was also a spot that featured
Bentsen's famous ``You're no Jack Kennedy'' retort to Quayle during
their debate.
   Among the ads running for Bush in spot markets across the country
and on various networks were a musical appeal and a spot saying he
is the only candidate experienced enough to negotiate with Soviet
leader Mikhail Gorbachev.
</TEXT>
