<FILEID>AP-NR-11-07-88 2153EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Bush 4thLd-Writethru a0800 11-07 0755</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush, 4th Ld-Writethru, a0800,770</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Confident Bush Says Election in ``Hands of Gods and American
People''</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: To UPDATE with 30-minute campaign commercial, SUB four grafs
for 4th and 5th pvs, Bush also..., picking up 6th pvs, On the</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Election Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A buoyant George Bush ended his presidential quest
Monday night in his adopted home state of Texas after declaring,
``It's in the hands of the gods and the American people.''
   Addressing 6,000 enthusistic supporters in a downtown shopping
mall, the vice president said, ``Most Americans believe our best
days are still ahead.''
   With that line, borrowed from Democratic rival Michael Dukakis,
Bush ended a presidential campaign he formally begun in this city
nearly 13 months ago.
   ``It's great to be back where it all began, right here in
Texas,'' said Bush, who maintains a legal voting residence here in a
hotel suite.
   Bush also addressed the nation in a 30-minute prime time
commercial that combined footage from his convention acceptance
speech of last August with parts of early commercials, clips of
members of his family and a direct election-eve appeal to voters
that was taped last week.
   In the ad, Bush echoed President Reagan 1980 campaign line,
saying, ``If you elect me president you will be better off four
years from now than you are today.''
   In that campaign, Reagan had asked, ``Are you better off today
than you were four years ago.''
   The film may have been as notable for what it did not include as
what it did, any mention of Bush's sometimes controversial running
mate, Sen. Dan Quayle.
   On the way to the gala finale in Houston, the Republican
presidential nominee barnstormed three battleground states in the
Middle West _ Michigan, Ohio and Missouri _ which have a combined 54
electoral votes.
   Bush told rallies in rural Ashland, Ohio, and in the Detroit
suburb of Southfield, Mich., that he felt momentum building in his
favor.
   ``That adrenalin is flowing,'' Bush told a cheering crowd in the
Ashland College gymnasium. ``Our family's together. The country's
coming in behind our candidacy, and I want to win this election.''
   Bush appeared with members of his family and campaign at the
Houston rally, where he couldn't resist delivering several final
vollies at Dukakis.
   ``Don't play recession roulette with the liberal governor of
Massachusetts,'' and said. But the line getting the biggest cheer
was the oft-repeated campaign refrain which Bush said ``can be
summed up in three short words: no new taxes.''
   Earlier, in St. Louis, at his Missouri campaign headquarters, he
said, ``I feel good, but we're not going to let up until we finish
tonight. ... It's in the hands of the gods and the American people.''
   He told volunteers there that he hoped the harsh campaign talk of
the past few months was over. ``Today is for looking over the
horizon and into the future,'' he said.
   Earlier, standing before a huge American flag in a Southfield
shopping mall, the GOP nominee said he was heading for the finish
``not in a power walk but in a sprint.'' It was a mocking reference
to Dukakis' favorite form of exercise, a fast-paced walk with
weights in each hand.
   Bush and Dukakis crossed paths during the last hours of their
campaigns, but Bush spokeswoman Sheila Tate insisted that the vice
president was not stalking his opponent.
   ``Is Dukakis shadowing us?'' she asked.
   Ms. Tate said the Midwest was crucial to Bush's election hopes
and that he was seizing the opportunity for ``a final presence'' to
boost his chances of carrying each state.
   She said the campaign's overnight tracking polls showed Bush's
nationwide leading holding at eight to 10 percentage points and that
no further slippage was detected.
   ``He's in really good spirits'' and unconcerned by Dukakis'
all-night campaign effort, Ms. Tate said.
   ``He slept like a baby,'' Barbara Bush, the candidate's wife,
told reporters on Air Force Two.
   She reacted philosophically to the end of the campaign. ``What
will be will be,'' she said, and expressed surprise at the Dukakis'
non-stop final day of campaigning. ``That's brutal,'' she said.
   Bush told the Michigan rally that ``what it all boils down to is
that my opponent and I have a fundamentally different view of the
future of America.'' He said, ``This is no time for the United
States to turn dramatically left.''
   ``We don't want to return to my opponent's favorite song: For all
you do, this recession is for you, '' Bush said.
</TEXT>
