<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Britain-Broadcasting     11-07 0271</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Broadcasting,0279</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Unveils Plans for Broadcast Deregulation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government announced Monday it would introduce
a package of legislation to create a fifth TV channel and
de-regulate the country's entire broadcasting network.
   Home Secretary Douglas Hurd, the government minister responsible
for broadcasting, said the legislation to be put before Parliament
next year would lead to a huge expansion of choice for viewers and
listeners.
   Britain now has two non-commercial channels run by the publicly
funded British Broadcasting Corp. and two independent commercial
channels.
   Hurd said the plans included a fifth channel, to start
broadcasting in 1993, two new satellite stations and three
independent national radio networks.
   Independent radio currently is confined to regional networks, and
plans for three satellite stations already have been approved by the
government.
   Because the franchises for the new channel would go to
competitive tender, the plan has aroused concern that there would be
less stringent quality control than now exists.
   Hurd said the BBC would be expected to continue ``high quality''
programming in both television and its network of national and
regional radio.
   Although TV watching is a top leisure activity among Britain's
population of 56 million, change in the country's viewing
opportunities has come slowly.
   Recent government figures show that 95 percent of the population
watches some televison and the average is 25 hours a week.
   A survey by the Independent Broadcasting Authority, which is
responsible for commercial television, showed only one in three
British adults had ever heard of the advent of direct satellite to
home TV broadcasting, and only one-third were interested in renting
or buying the receiving equipment.
</TEXT>
