<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Italy-Bomb     11-07 0232</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Italy-Bomb,0240</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Defendant Tosses Homemade Bomb In Courtroom</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TURIN, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A defendant in a Mafial trial tossed a
homemade bomb in the courtroom Monday, and the explosion sent
lawyers diving for cover but caused no injuries and only minor
damage, news reports said.
   The Italian news agency ANSA, quoting prosecutor Francesco
Saluzzo, said the bomb was made out of gunpowder hidden in a
cigarette package.
   Saluzzo said defendant Antonio Marano, 44, shouted a warning and
then tossed the explosive in the direction of a cell occupied by a
group of other defendants in the trial.
   The court was convened Monday morning to hear the deposition of
Salvatore Parisi, a Mafia informer who has confessed to 20 murders
and already has been sentenced to 22 years in prison.
   Marano was among 18 defendants who face charges of homicide in
connection with a war between rival gangs for control of the drug
market.
   The same court last Friday convicted 130 people, including two
judges, of belonging to a Mafia group that committed crimes
throughout Italy.
   The court sentenced 26 of them to life in prison for their roles
in the gang, which is blamed for 61 killings, four abductions and
hundreds of robberies.
   Seven relatives of informants in the trial were killed.
   The court on Monday immediately ordered an investigation into how
the defendant obtained the explosives and made the bomb.
</TEXT>
