<1ST_LINE>u a AM-HijackSentence     11-07 0420</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hijack Sentence,0434</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Albany Woman Sentenced to 6 Months, 5 Years Probation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>UNIONDALE, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman who admitted holding a gun to the
head of a 2-year-old boy and threatening to kill him during a 1969
skyjacking was sentenced Monday to six months in jail and five
years' probation.
   Linda Joyce Grinage, 39, in a tearful plea for leniency,
expressed remorse for her role in the 1969 hijacking of a plane to
Cuba from Kennedy International Airport.
   ``I realize I endangered the lives of innocent people and I
frightened them,'' said Mrs. Grinage, who lived in the Albany area
for about 10 years under the name Haziine Eytina, with her second
husband, Mylo Eytina, and five children.
   She was arrested in July after the FBI received an anonymous tip.
   She already has served all but 33 days of the six-month jail term.
   Mrs. Grinage pleaded guilty Aug. 17 to a charge of interfering
with the crew of the Eastern Airlines jet bound for Miami from New
York on Jan. 2, 1969.
   She admitted helping her first husband, Tyrone Ellington Austin,
force the plane to Havana by taking the boy hostage. The child, his
mother and 146 others on board were freed unharmed when the plane
landed in Havana.
   At her sentencing, Mrs. Grinage said that she understands the
feelings of Beverly Levi of West Islip, the mother of the 2-year-old.
   ``Over the last twenty years, I have suffered greatly,'' Grinage
said. ``I've been forced to abandon my two children by my first
marriage and I've been forced to live a double life with my husband
and five children.
   ``I'm now an honest, hardworking woman.''
   After U.S. District Court Judge Jacob Mishler pronounced the
sentence, she thanked him. ``I think you earned it,'' the judge
said. ``I hope you prove it.''
   She had been held in the Metropolitan Corrections Center in
Manhattan since her arrest.
   When she pleaded guilty, she claimed she had been beaten and
terrorized by her husband, who was killed by New York City police in
a 1971 gunfight following a bank robbery.
   ``I knew what my husband had planned,'' Mrs. Grinage said then.
``I was terrified of my husband. If he told me to walk off the side
of a building I would have done so.''
   Grinage also was indicted on charges of air piracy and
interference with a flight crew with a deadly weapon, which were
were dismissed. She admitted to the least of the charges,
interference without the use of a weapon.
</TEXT>
