<DOCNO> AP881107-0162 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-07-88 2232EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Peru     11-07 0399</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Peru,0410</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Guerrillas Kill Five in Attacks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LIMA, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Maoist guerrillas killed two policemen, a
soldier and two children in attacks in Peru's Andean highlands,
officials said Monday.
   Police said about 30 guerrillas of the Shining Path movement
attacked a on a police post in San Agustin de Cajas on Sunday
evening. The village is 10 miles north of Huancayo, an important
trading center in the central Andes 135 miles east of Lima.
   A wedding was under way in the second floor of the building,
which also serves as municipal headquarters, when the rebels
attacked with explosives and automatic rifle fire.
   Two girls, ages 12 and 14, who were among the guests were killed
during the attack and a woman was severely wounded, police said.
   Police defenders were unharmed during the attack and after 15
minutes of heavy shooting, the rebels escaped from town in a stolen
truck, police said.
   Another group of insurgents shot and killed an off-duty soldier
caught in a rebel roadblock Sunday night near Huancayo, police said.
   Elsewhere in the highlands, another Shining Path column of 25
rebels attacked two rural police posts before dawn Sunday 55 miles
northeast of Puno, a city on Lake Titicaca 610 miles southeast of
Lima.
   A Puno official, Victor Urbiola Garrido, told The Associated
Press by telephone that the rebels killed two policemen, wounded two
more and burned one of the posts before withdrawing.
   In Peru's jungle region, rebels of the pro-Cuba Tupac Amaru
Revolutionary Movement bombed half a dozen governnment and private
buildings Sunday night in Pucallpa, 350 miles northeast of Lima,
police said.
   The rebels hurled bombs at the offices of a state development
corporation, the municipal headquarters, the water company, a
school, a state agricultural agency and a large grocery store,
causing damage to the buildings but no injuries, according to police.
   The Shining Path launched an insurgency against Peru's elected
government eight years ago, and the death toll in the violence since
then has surpassed 12,000.
   The Tupac Amaru group, a much smaller band, became active in
1984, concentrating on late-night bombings in Lima. A year ago it
opened a front in Peru's northern jungle with about 100 armed
rebels, but the army moved into the area and quickly broke up the
column.
   Police said the attack in Pucallpa may indicate the group is
trying to re-establish a base in the jungle.
</TEXT>
