<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Myerson     11-07 0521</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Myerson,0539</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Prosecution Contends Myerson Tried to Buy Off Witness</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER ALAN HARPER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Miss America Bess Myerson may have offered
a job to a witness who was to testify against her, a prosecutor said
Monday in a conference with the judge hearing the divorce-fixing
case.
   Walter Canter, a former journalist who worked as a speechwriter
for Miss Myerson over a 15-year period, testified he heard from her
last month for the first time since she fired him in 1983.
   Miss Myerson, the former commissioner of the Department of
Cultural Affairs; her companion, Carl ``Andy'' Capasso, 43; and
former state Supreme Court Justice Hortense Gabel, 75, are on trial
on charges stemming from Capasso's divorce case.
   Miss Myerson, 64, is accused of giving a $19,000-a-year city job
to Mrs. Gabel's daughter, Sukhreet Gabel, to influence the judge's
decision in the divorce case.
   The judge's daughter was hired in August 1983 and Mrs. Gabel
slashed Capasso's temporary alimony and child support payments to
his estranged wife less than a month later.
   Moments after Canter's testimony Monday, the defense objected,
and U.S. District Judge John Keenan excused the jury and held a
private conference with prosecutors and defense attorneys.
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Stuart Abrams said Miss Myerson told
Canter ``that she was thinking of starting a foundation and that she
thought he would be a good person to head the foundation,''
according to a transcript released at the end of the day's hearing.
   ``Is there anything more?'' the judge asked. ``Is it that the
inference is to be drawn that she was trying to buy him off by
offering him something at a foundation?''
   ``I think that is a fair inference,'' Abrams said, adding that
Canter ``sort of made light of it ... he essentially sloughed it
off.''
   Miss Myerson's lawyer, Frederick Hafetz, said: ``I think it's an
ambiguous conversation.''
   Keenan agreed that the situation was ambiguous and that the
testimony might be prejudicial to the other defendants. He ruled it
could not be allowed as testimony.
   The lawyers and defendants are operating under a gag order and
could not be asked for comment.
   However, Canter, in a telephone interview Monday evening,
discounted what prosecutors said.
   ``I explained it to those guys (federal prosecutors) there. It's
a joke, a longstanding joke between us,'' Canter said.
   ``The only interpretation to it, I guess, was she was trying to
have her sense of humor come out. That is something, when you are
between a rock and a hard place, to have your sense of humor,''
Canter said.
   ``Believe me, it's a non-story.''
   Canter also testified that when he went to work for Miss Myerson
at Cultural Affairs, he did not have to go through a city interview
process, his resume was not submitted for review and he did not have
the stated qualifications for the job title he operated under.
   ``I wasn't aware of titles,'' Canter testified.
   ``Miss Myerson was familiar with my background and the work I had
done,'' he added. ``I knew what I had been brought in to do and I
did it.''
</TEXT>
