<1ST_LINE>r a AM-PastoriusPlea     11-07 0280</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pastorius Plea,0288</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reduced Charge Agreement Reached In Jazz Musician's Death</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A nightclub manager who confessed to
the beating death of jazz musician Jaco Pastorius pleaded guilty
Monday to a reduced manslaughter charge that can bring a maximum of
21 months in prison.
   Prosecutors said they reached the agreement with Luc Havan, 26,
after conflicting evidence weakened the first-degree murder case,
which could have brought life imprisonment.
   Havan, a Vietnamese immigrant, is scheduled for sentencing in
Broward Circuit Court on Dec. 5 and could also receive five years
probation.
   Havan contended he pushed Pastorius, 35, as he tried to enter the
club in an intoxicated state. But a medical examiner's report
indicated Pastorius suffered massive head injuries before falling
into a coma.
   Pastorius died nine days after the Sept. 11, 1987, incident at
the Fort Lauderdale club.
   Pastorius, born in Fort Lauderdale, was one of the nation's
pre-eminent bass players in the late 1970s, when he toured with
Blood, Sweat and Tears, Joni Mitchell and Weather Report. He was
nominated for three Grammy Awards.
   Pastorius over the past five years gradually fell into alcohol
and drug abuse and was homeless at the time of his death.
   Hours before the fatal incident, Pastorius had jumped on stage
and disrupted a Carlos Santana concert in suburban Sunrise.
   Ingrid Pastorius of Deerfield Beach, the victim's former wife,
said she was satisfied with the plea.
   ``I feel this man pleaded guilty from the heart,'' she said. ``As
the mother of Jaco's two sons, I feel good that I can tell them
there's a man who admitted hitting and killing their father. So I
can live with this deal.''
</TEXT>
