<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Reagan-Cake     11-07 0269</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reagan-Cake,280</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Ends Farewell Campaign Trip</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As President Reagan and his aides returned
Monday from a 14-hour, election-eve campaign blitz trip to
California, White House officials treated the president to a glass
of champagne, a campaign cake and a record album including the tune,
``Michael Row the Boat Ashore.''
   Dropping all pretense of avoiding any predictions about the
possible election of Vice President George Bush, White House chief
of staff Kenneth Duberstein offered Reagan a toast as Air Force One
sped back to Washington.
   ``It's been a privilege to work for you the past eight years and
in this campaign. We feel you've done what no other president has
done in 150 years _ elect your vice president,'' White House
spokesman Marlin Fitzwater quoted Duberstein as saying.
   Because it was the last leg of the final campaign trip of his
presidency, the president's aides also presented him with a large,
white cake, decorated in red and blue with the words:
   ``Win One for the Gipper. Victory 88, We are the change,'' all
well-used GOP campaign slogans.
   The staff then gave Reagan an album of Pete Seeger songs, which
included the selection, ``Michael Row the Boat Ashore,'' one of the
quips Reagan has regularly included in his stump speech in order to
poke fun at Democratic candidate Michael Dukakis' defense policies.
   Fitzwater reported that Reagan not only joined in eating a bit of
the cake, but had a glass of champagne to celebrate his trip.
   Reagan, Duberstein later said, ``is feeling really upbeat...He
feels he gave it his best shot for George Bush in California.''
</TEXT>
