   A new Iran-Contra grand jury is conducting what
appears to be an investigation of possible perjury by witnesses
questioned by Congress or another grand jury about the
arms-for-hostages affair.
   The new grand jury has viewed videotaped recordings of testimony
given to the House and Senate committees that investigated the
Reagan administration's arms deals with Iran and the diversion of
money to the Nicaraguan rebels, said sources speaking on condition
of anonymity.
   Independent counsel Lawrence E. Walsh took measures to isolate
his staff and the original Iran-Contra grand jury from news coverage
of the congressional hearings. He wanted to avoid defense
accusations that he relied on evidence given to Congress under
limited grants of immunity to bring charges against former White
House aide Oliver L. North and others indicted earlier this year by
the first Iran-Contra grand jury.
