<2ND_LINE>BC-History, Adv13,0511</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv13</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Nov.13</NOTE>
<HEAD>Today in History</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Today is Sunday, Nov. 13, the 318th day of 1988. There are 48
days left in the year.
   Today's highlight in history:
   On Nov. 13, 1940, the Walt Disney movie ``Fantasia,'' which
featured animated sequences set to famous works of classical music
by composers including Bach, Beethoven and Tchaikovsky, had its
world premiere at New York's Broadway Theater.
   On this date:
   In 1775, during the American Revolution, U.S. forces captured
Montreal.
   In 1909, 250 miners lost their lives following a fire and
explosion at the St. Paul Mine at Cherry, Ill.
   In 1927, the Holland Tunnel -- the first underwater tunnel for
vehicular traffic -- opened to the public, providing access between
New York City and New Jersey beneath the Hudson River.
   In 1937, NBC formed the first full-sized symphony orchestra
exclusively for radio broadcasting.
   In 1941, during World War II, the British aircraft carrier ``Ark
Royal'' sank in the Mediterranean, one day after it had been
torpedoed by a German U-boat.
   In 1942, President Franklin D. Roosevelt signed a measure
lowering the minimum draft age from 21 to 18.
   In 1956, the U.S. Supreme Court struck down laws calling for
racial segregation on public buses.
   In 1969, speaking in Des Moines, Iowa, Vice President Spiro T.
Agnew accused network television news departments of bias and
distortion, and urged viewers to lodge complaints.
   In 1971, the U.S. space probe ``Mariner Nine'' went into orbit
around Mars.
   In 1974, Karen Silkwood, a technician and union activist at the
Kerr-McGee Cimarron plutonium plant near Crescent, Okla., was killed
in a car crash.
   In 1981, the first manned balloon flight across the Pacific Ocean
ended as the ``Double Eagle Five,'' skippered by Ben Abruzzo, landed
in the Sanhedrin Mountains near Covelo, Calif.
   In 1982, the Vietnam Veterans Memorial was dedicated in
Washington following three days of ceremonies and marches in the
nation's capital.
   In 1985, some 23,000 residents of Armero, Colombia, died when a
gigantic mudslide, triggered by the Nevado del Ruiz volcano, buried
the city.
   Ten years ago: The Iranian capital of Tehran remained calm under
the watch of heavily armed troops in key districts of the city as
Shah Mohammed Reza Pahlavi attempted to weather weeks of violent
anti-government protests.
   Five years ago: During his visit to South Korea, President Reagan
made an unprecedented trip to the demilitarized zone separating the
south from Communist North Korea, where he praised U.S. soldiers as
a shield against ``tyranny and deprivation.''
   One year ago: Nicaraguan President Daniel Ortega unveiled an
11-point proposal in Washington for a cease-fire that called for the
Contra rebels to lay down their weapons and accept an amnesty.
   Today's birthdays: Actress Madeleine Sherwood is 66. Actor
Richard Mulligan is 56. Producer Garry Marshall is 54. Actor Dack
Rambo is 47.
   Thought for today: ``When words leave off, music begins.''
--Heinrich Heine, German poet and critic (1797-1856).
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881107-0174 </DOCNO>
