<DOCNO> AP881107-0177 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-07-88 0755EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a BC-History Adv17   11-07 0513</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-History, Adv17,0533</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv17</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Thursday, Nov. 17</NOTE>
<HEAD>Today in History</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Today is Thursday, Nov. 17, the 322nd day of 1988. There are 44
days left in the year.
   Today's highlight in history:
   Twenty years ago, on Nov. 17, 1968, broadcasting's ``Heidi
Incident'' took place. Outraged football fans jammed NBC
switchboards after the network cut away from the final minutes of a
game between the New York Jets and the Oakland Raiders in order to
begin a TV adaptation of ``Heidi'' on schedule. Viewers in the
eastern United States were prevented from seeing Oakland come from
behind to beat the Jets, 43-32.
   On this date:
   In 1558, Elizabeth I ascended the English throne upon the death
of Queen Mary.
   In 1800, Congress held its first session in Washington in the
partially completed Capitol building.
   In 1869, the Suez Canal opened in Egypt, linking the
Mediterranean and the Red Seas.
   In 1887, Field Marshal Viscount Montgomery of Alamein, Britain's
top field commander in World War II, was born in Moville, Ireland.
   In 1917, sculptor August Rodin died in Meudon, France.
   In 1925, actor Rock Hudson was born in Winnetka, Ill.
   In 1934, Lyndon Baines Johnson married Claudia Alta Taylor,
better known as Lady Bird.
   In 1948, Britain's House of Commons voted to nationalize the
country's steel industry.
   In 1962, Dulles International Airport, outside Washington D.C.,
was dedicated by President John F. Kennedy.
   In 1970, the Soviet Union landed an unmanned, remote-controlled
vehicle on the moon, the ``Lunokhod One.''
   In 1973, President Richard M. Nixon told Associated Press
managing editors meeting in Orlando, Fla., that ``people have got to
know whether or not their president is a crook. Well, I'm not a
crook.''
   In 1980, President-elect Ronald Reagan arrived in Washington for
his first visit to the nation's capital since his November victory.
   In 1982, South Korean boxer Duk Koo Kim was declared legally dead
by a judge in Las Vegas four days after he was left in a coma
resulting from a boxing match against Ray ``Boom Boom'' Mancini.
   Ten years ago: William Kampiles, a former CIA employee, was
convicted in Hammond, Ind., of stealing a top-secret government
document and selling it to a Soviet official for $3,000 dollars.
(Kampiles was sentenced to 40 years in prison.)
   Five years ago: Greyhound, struck two weeks earlier by more than
12,000 employees, resumed limited service with non-union drivers,
resulting in violent confrontations across the country.
   One year ago: Retiring Secretary of Defense Caspar W. Weinberger
received an elaborate send-off, complete with a 19-gun salute, on
the grounds of the Pentagon, where President Reagan praised him as a
``trusted friend and adviser.''
   Today's birthdays: Olympian-turned-politician Bob Mathias is 58.
Actor-comedian Peter Cook is 51. Singer Gordon Lightfoot is 50.
Movie director Martin Scorsese is 46. Actress Lauren Hutton is 44.
Actor Danny DeVito is 44. Baseball pitcher Tom Seaver is 44.
   Thought for today: ``History is worth reading when it tells us
truly what the attitude toward life was in the past.'' -- Dorothy
Canfield Fisher, American author and essayist (1879-1958).
</TEXT>
