<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An investor group led by the buyout firm
Forstmann Little & Co. and that includes the consumer products giant
Procter & Gamble Co. emerged as a possible ``white knight'' in the
fight for RJR Nabisco Inc.
   Forstmann Little said late Friday the group was considering a bid
for the food and tobacco products company that would surpass a $20.7
billion offer made by Nabisco management and a competing $20.3
billion bid by the investment firm Kohlberg Kravis Roberts Inc.
   In a statement, Forstmann Little said a special committee of the
RJR Nabisco board set up to review the offers ``had welcomed the
interest'' of the group, which also included the food companies
Ralston Purina Co. and Castle & Cooke Inc. and the investment firm
Goldman, Sachs & Co.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Universities and research centers have turned computers back on
after sweeping out a ``virus'' epidemic that infected machines
across the country.
   Specialists said Friday the virus proved to be a nuisance and
slowed computers but apparently caused no damage.
   The virus is a sort of rogue program that reproduced in computers
and apparently instructed them to send copies of itself to other
machines through a research network, ARPANET.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Maxwell Communication Corp. PLC said it plans to
sell its British commercial printing business and is considering
selling other assets following its takeover of the U.S.-based
publishing and information services concern Macmillan Inc.
   The company, which is headed by Robert Maxwell, said the moves
are part of a restructuring that will enable it to focus more on
publishing and less on printing following the Macmillan deal.
   Maxwell was also elected Friday to replace Edward P. Evans, who
resigned as Macmillan's chairman.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Poland's national airline said it will acquire
its first non-Soviet aircraft, three Boeing 767 widebody jets, in a
deal that will make Boeing Co. the first supplier of modern, Western
jets to a Soviet bloc nation.
   The deal announced Friday is worth $220 million to Boeing and
General Electric Co., the engine supplier.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chubb Corp. has offered another $43.7 million
in coverage to some farmers whose applications it had rejected this
year.
   Chubb's offer comes as the insurer faces a class-action lawsuit
by farmers in 10 states who say they were unfairly denied drought
insurance.
   The company said Friday it is willing to proceed to reach a
settlement with farmers who applied for drought insurance, but were
rejected and filed suit against Chubb.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal regulators have announced that a
financially troubled New Jersey savings and loan institution was
being acquired by a California institution.
   Officials said Friday the acquisition of Lincoln Federal Savings
and Loan Association of Westfield, N.J. represented the 140th
troubled S&L case resolved this year. Lincoln Federal is being
acquired by First Nationwide Bank of San Francisco.
   The Federal Savings and Loan Insurance Corp. said it was
providing $145.7 million in assistance as part of the deal.
</TEXT>
