<1ST_LINE>r f PM-BusinessHighlights 1stAdd   11-07 0528</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Highlights, 1st Add,0552</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Unemployment fell to 5.3 percent in October _
matching a 14-year low _ the government said, as employers added
325,000 new jobs and floored the accelerator on an economy that had
been slowed by the summer drought.
   Friday's report was the last major economic report before
Tuesday's presidential election.
   The Labor Department said the 0.1 percentage point drop from
September's 5.4 percent jobless rate was accompanied by 99,000 new
manufacturing jobs, the biggest monthly increase in that employment
category since February 1984.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Policymakers at the Federal Reserve, viewing
evidence that U.S. economic growth was slowing, decided at their
September meeting to leave interest rates unchanged, according to
minutes of the session.
   The Federal Open Market Committee, which establishes monetary
policy for the central bank, voted 12-0 to make no further moves to
tighten credit conditions, a report made public Friday said.
   But officials let it be known the central bank still considered
higher inflation a greater threat to the economy than a possible
recession.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rent control will be on the ballot in four
northern California communities: Santa Cruz wants to ban it,
Berkeley and San Francisco want to expand it and Sonoma wants to
limit it to certain low-income residents.
   In Santa Cruz County, voters will consider a proposal banning
future rent control measures. In San Francisco, Measure U would
extend existing rent control to vacant residential units.
   Current law limits rent increases on occupied residential units
to 4 percent to 7 percent annually.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's largest defense contractors are
routinely billing the Pentagon for hundreds of millions of dollars
spent on outside consultants, frequently without justifying or
explaining the work they perform, a special audit has found.
   The Defense Department is itself partly to blame because its
procurement regulations are so vague, according to the report
released Friday by the Defense Contract Audit Agency.
   But the internal business discipline one would expect at a large
company for hiring outsiders is, ``in most cases, non-existent,''
the auditors added.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. officials say Britain's investigation of
Minorco SA's $4.7 billion takeover bid for Consolidated Gold Fields
PLC makes it unnecessary for the United States to look into whether
a merger of the two companies would endanger the supply of strategic
minerals.
   Under British law, Minorco's bid for Consolidated Gold Fields, a
British company, lapsed on Oct. 25 when it was referred to the
British Monopolies and Mergers Commission.
   The British government decided to investigate the offer after a
federal judge in New York issued an injunction against the deal
because it might violate U.S. antitrust law.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market fell as the Dow Jones average of 30 industrials
lost 24.54 points to close at 2,145.80.
   Bonds tumbled as the Treasury's 30-year bond lost nearly two
points while its yield rose to 8.90 percent.
   Meanwhile, the dollar rose and gold prices were nearly flat.
Crude futures prices gained, along with cocoa futures, livestock and
meat; precious metals were mixed while grains and soybeans were
mostly lower and stock-index futures retreated.
</TEXT>
