<DOCNO> AP881107-0183 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-07-88 0746EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-PurchasingManagers     11-07 0509</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Purchasing Managers,0526</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Purchasing Managers Say Economic Growth Quickened In October</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Continued growth in production and orders helped
the economy accelerate in October after slowing the previous month,
according to the nation's purchasing managers.
   The Purchasing Managers Index rose to 56.8 in October from 54.8
in September, remaining below the year's peak of 59.3 in June, the
National Association of Purchasing Management said in a report
released Monday.
   An index above 50 percent generally indicates the economy is
expanding.
   In addition to the growth in production, new orders grew at a
slightly faster pace than in September, while new export orders rose
again and employment rose sharply, the group reported.
   ``Despite the apparent slowing in the growth rate of new export
orders, the continued high level of new orders, coupled with a
reduced inflation rate, suggests the fourth quarter economy will be
as good as the previous three,'' stated Robert J. Bretz, chairman of
the organization's Business Survey Committee.
   A number of economists closely watch the purchasing managers'
report because it gives solid clues to the direction of the economy.
   Production rose in October for the 27th consecutive month. The
index for production rose to 60.3, up sharply from September's 56.0,
which marked a slowdown from the 58.2 reading in August.
   The index for new orders rose to 58.9 from September's 58.4,
narrowly reversing a three-month string of declining growth rates
but trailing the 62.1 level of July.
   New export orders, a major element of recent economic growth,
grew in October but the pace slowed for the third straight month.
Among respondents who export, 26 percent reported higher export
orders, down slightly from 27 percent in September and sharply lower
than the 37.8 percent average for the first seven months of 1988.
The proportion reporting lower export orders rose to 8 percent, the
highest percentage this year and up from 6 percent in September.
   Employment rose sharply during the month, considering normal
seasonal variations, with the index jumping to a new 1988 high of
53.7 from September's 50.2 and reversing two consecutive months of
slowing growth.
   The employment index echoes the Labor Department's report on
Friday that U.S. unemployment fell to 5.3 percent in October,
matching a 14-year low as employers added 325,000 new jobs.
   Deliveries from vendors slowed for the 25th straight month _ an
indication that suppliers can't keep up with strong demand _
although a rise in the index to 55.6 from 55.0 in September
continues signaling that the rate of slowing is declining.
   Inventories declined slightly during October, after accounting
for normal seasonal variations, with the index dropping to 49.4 from
49.6.
   Prices rose during October, with more purchasers reporting price
increases than decreases for the 27th straight month. The index
dipped to 70.7 from 72.2 in September, however, indicating that the
rate of price increase slowed for the fourth straight month.
   The report is based on surveys of purchasing executives in more
than 250 industrial companies in 21 industries in all 50 states. The
organization has nearly 30,000 members.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881107-0184 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-07-88 0749EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Dollar-Gold     11-07 0281</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dollar-Gold,0293</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Drifts Lower, Gold Rises</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar drifted lower in cautious late-morning
European trading today, but traders said they were not expecting
further major losses for the dollar ahead of the U.S. election
results. Gold prices rose in Europe.
   Traders in Italy said the dollar would remain fairly stationary
until the first indications of the result of the U.S. presidential
election Tuesday.
   One trader in Milan predicted a victory for Republican Vice
President George Bush should boost the dollar to around 1.82 West
German marks this week. But he said a win by Democratic candidate
Michael Dukakis would make the market immediately bearish toward the
dollar.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar rose 0.44 Japanese yen to closing at 125.07 yen. Later in
London, it fell back to 124.85 yen.
   Other dollar rates at mid-morning, compared with late Friday's
prices, included: 1.7888 West German marks, down from 1.7955; 1.4990
Swiss francs, down from 1.5060; 6.1035 French francs, down from
6.1215; 2.0195 Dutch guilders, down from 2.0253; 1,328.75 Italian
lire, down from 1,332.50; and 1.2300 Canadian dollars, up from
1.2223.
   In London, the British pound rose to $1.7705 from $1.7655 on
Friday.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $421.75 a troy ounce, up
from $420.25 bid late Friday. At midmorning today, the city's five
major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $422.00.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $422.30, up from $420.50 bid late
Friday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell 32 cents to close at $423.69.
   Silver bullion was quoted in London at a bid price of $6.43 a
troy ounce, up from Friday's $6.40.
</TEXT>
