<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Japan-Markets     11-07 0216</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Markets,0226</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Stocks Down, Dollar Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices declined across the board today on the
Tokyo Stock Exchange while the dollar closed higher against the
Japanese yen.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues lost 180.39
points, or 0.64 percent, to close at 27,866.36.
   The dollar opened at 125.28 yen, and ranged between 124.95 and
125.33 yen before closing at 125.07 yen. That was up 0.44 yen from
Friday's close of 124.63 yen.
   Securities dealers attributed the Nikkei's decline to
profit-taking following bullishness last week and the worsening
condition of Emperor Hirohito.
   The Nikkei index gained 85.74 points last week, surpassing the
28,000-mark for the first time in three months. The news that
Hirohito's condition worsened Sunday apparently discouraged bullish
sentiment of the market.
   ``The emperor's condition is once again making investors
nervous,'' said a dealer at Nikko Securities Co., speaking on
condition of anonymity. ``Many investors were profit-taking today
because they thought the bullishness of the market will not last
long because of the emperor's worsening illness.''
   The world's longest-reigning monarch has been gravely ill since
Sept. 19.
   On the foreign exchange market, exchange dealers said general
market sentiment showed the dollar is still bearish, but added many
players were remaining on the sidelines because of Tuesday's U.S.
presidential election.
</TEXT>
