<1ST_LINE>u f BC-Britain-Stocks     11-07 0161</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Britain-Stocks,0168</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>London Shares Broadly Lower at Midday</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices were broadly lower in thin trading at
midday Monday, with many investors waiting on the sidelines ahead of
Tuesday's U.S. presidential elections.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index was down 11.3
points, or 0.6 percent, at 1,823.0 around 12:30 p.m. local time. The
index moved down a maximum 13.7 points at mid-morning. At its best,
the index was down 7 points shortly after the start of business.
   Volume was scant, with just 186.4 million shares changing hands
by midday compared with 351.1 million shares at the same time Friday.
   Most traders said they expected the U.S. Republican candidate,
Vice President George Bush, to beat out his Democratic rival,
Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis, based upon Bush's favorable
showing in U.S. public opinion polls.
   But they said they weren't taking anything for granted, and
predicted a Bush victory would likely give the market a temporary
lift later this week.
</TEXT>
