<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street 10am,0269</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market opened lower in quiet, early
trading today, as Wall Street awaited the presidential election and
continued to focus on last week's unexpectedly strong unemployment
figures.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials was down 15.47 points at
2,130.33 after a half-hour of trading at 10 a.m. EST.
   Declining issues outpaced advancing ones by about 3 to 1 on the
New York Stock Exchange, with 578 issues down, 186 up and 412
unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board totaled 18.29 million shares after the
first 30 minutes of trading.
   Market analysts said Friday's low jobless rate continued to
influence this morning's market. The stronger October unemployment
data fueled concern that the economy is not slowing, as analysts had
predicted, and that the Federal Reserve could move to curb
inflationary pressures by tighening credit.
   In addition, analysts said the market is uneasy and is likely to
remain quiet before Tuesday's presidential election.
   ``Investors are watchful, waiting for the election and hoping
there won't be anything upsetting,'' said Larry Wachtel, a market
analyst with Prudential-Bache Securities.
   The New York Stock Exchange composite index was off 0.93 at
154.77. At the American Stock Exchange, the composite market index
fell 1.84 to 295.68.
   On Friday, The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials fell 24.54
points to 2,145.80.
   Declining issues edged out advances by around 5 to 2 on the New
York Stock Exchange.
   Big Board volume totaled 143.58 million shares, down from 152.98
million in Thursday's session.
</TEXT>
