<FILEID>AP-NR-11-07-88 1115EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Omnicom-Management     11-07 0292</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Omnicom-Management,0304</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rosenshine Steps Down as Head of Ominicom To Head a Subsidiary</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Allen Rosenshine, who was selected to head
Omnicom Group Inc. at its formation two years ago with the merger of
three advertising agencies, announced Monday that he is stepping
down to head one of its subsidiaries.
   The 49-year-old former ad copywriter said that, at his own
suggestion, he would become chief executive of BBDO Worldwide, an
Omnicom agency whose clients include Pepsi-Cola soft drinks, Apple
computers and General Electric lighting.
   Rosenshine will replace Norman W. Campbell, 54, who is retiring
as BBDO's chief executive. Rosenshine headed BBDO before the Omnicom
merger.
   Rosenshine said in a statement that the Omnicom board had
accepted his recommendation to name Bruce Crawford, 59, to succeed
Rosenshine as chief executive of Omnicom.
   Crawford had once headed BBDO but left at the end of 1985 to
become general manager of the Metropolitan Opera in New York.
   The changes will take effect as soon after Jan. 1 as possible,
depending on time required for orderly transitions within Omnicom,
BBDO and the Metropolitan Opera, the statement said.
   Rosenshine said Campbell had expressed a desire to retire as soon
as the post-merger transition could be completed.
   He told the board that since Crawford had indicated a desire to
return to the ad business, he felt it would be a good time to make
the changes.
   Omnicom was created in August 1986 with the merger of BBDO, Doyle
Dane Bernbach Group and Needham Harper Worldwide.
   As it is now set up, Omnicom oversees three separate agency
groups _ BBDO, DDB Needham and Diversified Agency Services _ which
have combined billings of more than $6 billion, making Omnicom one
of the world's largest ad companies.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
