<DOCNO> AP881107-0198 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-07-88 1622EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-WallStreetClosing     11-07 0298</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street Closing,0318</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices declined sharply in light to
moderate trading today, as concern about Tuesday's presidential
election and what could come afterward dominated the market.
   The market opened lower and continued to decline as skittish
investors withdrew from buying and selling in anticipation of
Tuesday's outcome.
   ``We're not seeing a lot of selling but just a lot of people not
buying,'' said Philip Puccio, senior vice president at Dillon, Read
& Co.
   Early in the day, analysts said some investors had decided to
reduce their stock portfolios before Tuesday's vote.
   ``People came in in a selling mood today,'' said Charles Jensen,
an analyst with MKI Securities Corp.
   But while the presidential election appeared to be the dominating
force in today's market, some observers said the market's weakness
suggested that many investors were already looking beyond the
election and to wat could come afterward.
   Late last week, the stock market lost ground as new economic data
indicating the economy might be growing faster than expected revived
fears of higher inflation and interest rates.
   Some analysts had predicted that the Federal Reserve would wait
until after the election to put the skids on inflation by raising
interest rates.
   ``What is happening today is an extension of the anxieties that
hit the market last week,'' said Michael Metz, an analyst with
Oppenheimer & Co.
   Weaker bond prices and lower transport stock prices also weighed
heavily on today's stock market, analysts said.
   ``The bond market is leading our market...,'' Puccio said. ``I
would be worried if I saw a bigger trading volume, but it's very
slow...''
   The stronger October unemployment data renewed concern that the
economy may be heating up, signaling higher inflation and interest
rates if the Federal Reserve moves to tighten credit.
</TEXT>
