<FILEID>AP-NR-11-07-88 1638EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f BC-PresidentialCDs     11-07 0363</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Presidential CDs,0381</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>CD Investors Pick Bush To Win</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIVIAN MARINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A landslide victory for George Bush is already in the bank, so to
speak.
   In a gimmick to attract deposit dollars, a handful of banks and
thrifts nationwide have offered investors bonus interest rates on
certificates of deposits based on the outcome of Tuesday's
presidential election.
   And if that money talks, Bush wins.
   At the Regency Savings Bank in Naperville, Ill., customers with a
minimum of $2,000 to invest had three months to put their money in
either a one-year CD for Bush or his Democratic challenger,
Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis.
   Holders of the winning ``Presidential Election CD'' would receive
an extra 0.5 percent interest, which would mean a jump to 7.75
percent from 7.25 percent when the CD was first offered.
   Marketing assistant Carol Johnson said that as of Saturday, the
purchasing cutoff date, a whopping 93.75 percent of all $3 million
in sales were for Bush CDs, with Dukakis getting the rest.
   ``Bush has always been ahead, but it seems to me it's gone up
quite a bit over the last couple of weeks,'' Ms. Johnson said.
   Not too surprisng for Naperville, an affluent Chicago suburb that
is heavily Republican.
   In the Washington, D.C., area, Perpetual Savings Bank had similar
results for its ``Presidential Certificate of Deposits.''
   Robert Barton, senior vice president of investor relations, said
that as of the Saturday cutoff, 63 percent of the thrift's
approximately $3 million in sales of two- and four-year CDs were
Republican.
   Barton said the margin was a lot narrower when the CDs were first
offered in September and widened in recent weeks.
   At Perpetual, depositors of both persuasions are eligible for a
bonus regardless of who wins the election. The thrift will award
bonus interest to all depositors, up to a maximum of 0.5 percent,
based on the winner's margin of victory in the popular vote.
   Robert K. Heady, publisher of the North Palm Beach, Fla.,
newsletter Bank Rate Monitor, said these special CD sales have
broken some new ground.
   ``Politics has replaced the toaster as the hottest bank premium
of the fall of 1988,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881107-0201 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-07-88 1641EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     11-07 0529</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dollar-Gold,0542</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Falls; Gold Prices Rise</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede LONDON BC</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar finished sharply lower Monday against
all major currencies except the Canadian dollar as traders were
reluctant to take positions ahead of the presidential election.
   Gold prices rose. Republic National Bank of New York said gold
bullion was bid at $422.25 a troy ounce as of 4 p.m. EST, up
slightly from $421.50 on Friday.
   The dollar finished lower in European trading and continued to
drift steadily downward as activity shifted to the United States.
Despite the depth of the currency's drop, the tone in the currency
markets was quiet.
   Traders said the dollar was undermined by new polls that showed
Democratic presidential candidate Michael Dukakis narrowing the lead
held by Republican Vice President George Bush.
   The market perceives a Bush win would be mildly bullish for the
dollar, although traders are at a loss for a clear explanation as to
why such a victory would support the currency.
   ``Regardless of who is becoming president, the market feels the
dollar should go lower,'' said Stephen Flanagan, an assistant vice
president at Manufacturers Hanover Trust Co.
   Traders around the world predicted there would be no substantial
move in the dollar until after the election.
   ``There will be no major position-taking before the election,
although the market retains its bearish tint,'' said Jeff
Mondschein, manager of foreign exchange at Chicago-based Continental
Illinois National Bank & Trust Co.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar fell 0.44 yen to a closing 125.07 yen. Later, in London,
it was quoted at a lower rate of 124.68 yen. In New York, the dollar
fell to yen 124.63, from 124.93 yen on Friday.
   In London, the dollar fell against the British pound. It cost
$1.7755 dollars to buy one pound, more expensive than $1.7655 late
Friday. In New York it cost $1.7804 to buy one pound, more expensive
than Friday's $1.7661.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late Friday,
included: 1.7772 West German marks, down from 1.7910; 1.4887 Swiss
francs, down from 1.5013; 6.0675 French francs, down from 6.1188;
1,320.38 Italian lire, down from 1,330.50, and 1.2358 Canadian
dollars, up from 1.2231.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Friday,
included: 1.7840 West German marks, down from 1.7955; 1.4965 Swiss
francs, down from 1.5060; 6.0815 French francs, down from 6.1215;
2.0148 Dutch guilders, down from 2.0253; 1,327.75 Italian lire, down
from 1,332.50, and 1.2374 Canadian dollars, up from 1.2223.
   Gold prices moved higher. On New York's Commodity Exchange, gold
finished at $422.80 a troy ounce, up from $421.50 on Friday.
   In London the metal rose to a late bid of $421.75 a troy ounce,
compared with late Friday's $420.25. In Zurich, gold rose, closing
at a bid $420.65, compared with $420.50 late Friday. Earlier in Hong
Kong, gold was bid at $421.95 a troy ounce, up from $420.25 on
Friday.
   Silver bullion prices finished at $6.490 a troy ounce on New
York's Comex, up from $6.425 on Friday. On the London market, the
metal was trading at a late bid of $6.45 a troy ounce, compared with
Friday's $6.40.
