<1ST_LINE>u f AM-CommodityRdp     11-07 0788</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Commodity Rdp,0817</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Copper Futures Fall Sharply On Rise In London Inventory</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Copper futures prices fell sharply Monday on New York's Commodity
Exchange after the London Metal Exchange reported an increase in its
warehouse stocks of copper for the first time in two months.
   It was the third price decline in as many sessions but analysts
were divided on the significance of the buildup in copper stocks in
London.
   On other markets, precious metals gained; grains were mostly
higher while soybeans finished lower; livestock and meat were mixed;
energy futures rose and stock-index futures retreated.
   U.S. copper futures traders had been expecting the London Metal
Exchange to report a decline of 5,000 to 10,000 metric tons last
week in the amount of copper stored in exchange-sanctioned
warehouses.
   Instead, the exchange said stocks rose 125 metric tons to 70,925
metric tons. It was the first increase since Sept. 5, when the
exchange reported inventories totaling 122,125 metric tons.
   The report startled copper traders on New York's Comex who had
grown jittery after bidding the metal's spot price to an all-time
high of $1.538 a pound last week.
   Copper for spot delivery settled 3.35 cents lower at $1.4565 a
pound Monday on the Comex while the most active futures contract,
for December delivery, was 3.1 cents lower at $1.389 a pound.
   The report of a 125-ton rise in copper stocks ``really caused the
market to move lower,'' said Bette Raptopoulos, metals analyst in
New York with Prudential-Bache Securities Inc.
   But Ms. Raptopoulos said the bull market's fundamental
underpinnings _ tight supplies, strong demand and a 3-week-old
copper miners' strike in Peru _ remained in place, suggesting prices
could recover and advance to new highs.
   Craig Sloane, an analyst with Smith Barney, Harris Upham & Co.,
said the unexpected rise in copper inventories should be viewed as a
caution light.
   ``It is significant in that it breaks the trend of sizeable
declines that's been going on for two months,'' Sloane said.
   ``The slight increase should not be thrown out as something
meaningless,'' he said. ``It could very well be the start of
something new _ but I wouldn't bet the whole farm on it.''
   Precious-metals prices advanced on the Comex amid strong overseas
buying spurred by the dollar's decline against other currencies,
analysts said.
   Gold settled $1.20 to $1.60 higher with December at $424.70 a
troy ounce; silver was 6.5 cents to 7.6 cents higher with December
at $6.53 a troy ounce.
   Grain and soybean futures finished mixed on the Chicago Board of
Trade with grains mostly higher and soybeans mostly lower.
   The soybean market settled near the day's highs, though, on
speculation that the Soviet Union was planning large purchases of
U.S. soybeans and soybean meal, experts said.
   After the close, the Agriculture Department confirmed that the
Soviet Union had purchased 300,000 metric tons of U.S. soybean meal.
   The grain markets had opened lower on disappointment about the
lack of new export business. But most prices rebounded late in the
session on a news report that the No. 2 official in the Soviet
grain-buying agency had said the Soviet Union would need to buy 1
million metric tons of U.S. soybeans or soymeal for both February
and March delivery, said Victor Lespinasse, a trader with Dean
Witter Reynolds Inc. in Chicago.
   ``There was just an explosion in the meal market in the last
minute or so,'' he said.
   Wheat settled 1\ cents lower to 3\ cents higher with December at
$4.19 a bushel; corn was unchanged to 2\ cents higher with December
at $2.78} a bushel; oats were 6 cents to 8 cents higher with
December at $2.25 a bushel; soybeans were 3{ cents lower to 2 cents
higher with November at $7.88{ a bushel.
   On the Chicago Mercantile Exchange, live cattle settled .15 cent
lower to .28 cent higher with December at 73.60 cents a pound;
feeder cattle were .05 cent lower to .35 cent higher with November
at 81.45 cents a pound; hogs were .30 cent lower to .37 cent higher
with December at 42.12 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were .22
cent lower to .13 cent higher with February at 46.12 cents a pound.
   Energy futures posted moderate gains on the New York Mercantile
Exchange.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil was 2 cents to 15 cents higher
at $14.06 barrel; heating oil was .05 cent to .37 cent higher with
December at 44.13 cents a gallon; unleaded gasoline was .17 cent to
.91 cent higher with December at 47.25 cents a gallon.
   Stock-index futures retreated moderately on the Chicago
Mercantile Exchange, where the contract for December delivery of the
Standard & Poor's 500 settled 1.55 points lower at 274.70.
</TEXT>
