<HEAD>Stock Prices Tumble</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JULIA MARTINEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices tumbled in light trading Monday as
weary investors awaited the outcome of the presidential election.
   The Dow Jones Industrial average lost 21.16 points to close the
day at 2,124.64.
   In the broader market, declining issues outpaced advances by
nearly 4 to 1 in nationwide trading of New York Stock
Exchange-listed stocks, with 1,200 issues down, 314 up and 444
unchanged.
   Volume on the floor of the NYSE came to 133.87 million shares,
down from 143.58 million in Friday's session. Nationwide,
consolidated volume in NYSE-listed issues, including trading at
regional exchanges and on the over-the-counter market, totaled
171.01 million shares.
   Analysts said investors withdrew from the market early, neither
buying nor selling, to await the outcome of Tuesday's vote. Analysts
said that while Wall Street felt relatively certain of a George Bush
victory, investors were cautious after weekend polls suggested
Michael Dukakis had narrowed the gap in some areas.
   In addition, leftover concern from last week's unexpectedly
strong unemployment data also kept investors watchful. The drop in
the jobless rate revived concern that the economy is stronger than
expected, signaling the possibility of higher inflation and a move
by the Federal Reserve to tighten credit by raising interest rates.
   Later in the day, many observers said a no-win sentiment seemed
to grip the market as investors turned to post-election concerns.
   ``The market has so baked George Bush into the pie that if he is
victorious, it will be anti-climactic and the market will say `So
what,''' said Larry Wachtel, an analyst with Prudential-Bache
Securities Inc. ``The big story will be after the election.''
   Another analyst said investors worried that regardless of who
wins the elections, concerns about the economy will persist.
   ``Even with a Bush victory, we're faced with rising inflation,
higher interest rates, concerns about the federal deficit _ the same
questions about the economy,'' said Alfred E. Goldman, vice
president for A.G. Edwards & Sons Inc. in St. Louis. ``You'll have
trouble finding anyone who thinks either Bush or Dukakis has
developed a sense of coming to grips with these things.''
   The NYSE composite index of all its listed common stocks lost
1.42 to close at 154.28.
   Among actively traded issues on the NYSE, Sears Roebuck dropped ~
point to 43}, IBM fell 1[ to 119[ and Pillsbury was off 1] at 59.
Pillsbury said it was spinning of its Burger King unit.
   RJR Nabisco, in the middle of a takeover battle, rose 1} to 87],
and Ford gained 1] to 51.
   Standard & Poor's industrial index closed down 2.73 to 315.36,
and S&P's 500-stock composite index lost 2.38 to finish at 273.93.
   The NASDAQ composite index for the over-the-counter market
declined 4.51 to 376.51.
   At the American Stock Exchange, the market value index was down
4.05 to close at 293.47.
   As measured by Wilshire Associates' index of more than 5,000
actively traded stocks, the market was $2,700.163 billion Monday off
26.089 billion or off 0.96 percent from Friday.
</TEXT>
