<2ND_LINE>AM-Church's, 1st Ld - Writethru, f0258,0553</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Church's Board Rejects Popeyes' Takeover Offer</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 4 new grafs to restore dropped word `and' in lede,
UPDATE with Church's also saying it will explore alternative
suitors, add stock price. Picks up 3rd graf pvs, Church's also...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID SEDENO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN ANTONIO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Church's Fried Chicken Inc.'s board of
directors on Monday rejected as inadequate a $290 million takeover
offer by rival Popeyes Famous Fried Chicken and Biscuits and said it
would file a federal court suit to block the bid.
   The board of San Antonio-based Church's, the nation's
second-largest fried chicken chain behind Kentucky Fried Chicken,
also indicated it had instructed management to explore alternatives
to the $8 a share Popeye's offer, including a possible leveraged
buyout, merger with another suitor or major acquisition by Church's.
   Church's had been studying the offer Popeyes' parent company, A.
Copeland Enterprises Inc. of New Orleans for about two weeks.
   Church's shares dipped 25 cents to $7.75 a share Monday on the
New York Stock Exchange.
   Church's also announced a shareholder protection plan aimed at
making a hostile takeover more difficult and said it would file a
counterclaim in Louisiana federal court to stop Popeyes from
pursuing the takeover offer.
   Popeyes spokesman Mark McKinnon said the company would stand by
its offer.
   ``We are disappointed. We still want a friendly deal and would
sign a confidentiality agreement to get more information about the
company,'' McKinnon said. ``The bottom line is we are not going
away.''
   McKinnon said the company believed Church's legal motions were
unfounded and company officials believed they could lead Church's to
greater profitability.
   Church's officials also have filed motions in federal court in
San Antonio seeking a declaratory judgment upholding the shareholder
rights plan.
   The shareholder rights plan, commonly known as a poison pill,
enables Church's shareholders to sharply increase their holdings in
the company in the event a hostile bidder acquires a stake of 20
percent or more, and to buy at a discount stock in the hostile
bidder if it wins control of Church's. Such plans are aimed at
making a hostile buyout prohibitively expensive.
   ``This is a program that's designed not to prevent a takeover,
but to encourage a potential buyer to negotiate properly for the
benefit of the shareholder,'' said Ernest Renaud, Church's president
and chief executive officer.
   ``It makes the potential buyer go back and do his homework on the
offer and allows the board time to look at the takeover offer and
not to stampede into it,'' Renaud said.
   Church's also said it would be filing an answer and counterclaims
in Louisiana federal court against Copeland and other individuals.
   The counterclaims hope to keep Copeland from continuing its offer
on charges that it would violate securities and antitrust laws and
also alleges former Church's employees used confidential information
regarding Church's.
   Church's, which has gone through management changes the last
several years, expects sales of around $520 million this year from
its more than 1,500 restaurants, down from about $570 million in
1986 and $633 million in 1984.
   Popeyes, the No. 3 chicken restaurant, expects sales of $485
million this year. There are 725 Popeyes restaurants nationwide, 100
of them company-owned.
</TEXT>
