<FILEID>AP-NR-11-07-88 2123EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-SearsRestructuring     11-07 0468</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sears Restructuring,0484</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Brennan Says Sears Stores Will Change, But Not Become `Discount'
Stores</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BERNARD SCHOENBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sears, Roebuck and Co. may be adopting a
``low-cost mentality'' under its recently-announced restructuring,
but that doesn't mean it will be running a chain of discount stores,
Sears' chairman said Monday.
   A new policy of ``every day low pricing,'' plus other changes,
will instead mean far fewer promotional sales, and in some cases
fewer choices of products in Sears stores, said company Chairman
Edward Brennan.
   ``We intend to take our current mix of merchandise and go to a
low, every-day price strategy with that mix,'' Brennan told a group
of securities analysts and reporters at Sears Tower in Chicago.
   ``Don't feel like we are going to be something that looks like a
discounter,'' with shopping carts and check-out counters at the
doors, he said.
   A ``significant increase'' in the number of Sears retail stores _
now about 825 _ also could occur in coming years, he said.
   Sears officials announced last week they would revamp
merchandising and sell the 110-story Sears Tower, the world's
tallest building, in a bid to improve the company's earnings. No
buyers for the building have been announced.
   Company officials also revealed plans to move the company's
Merchandise Group out of Sears Tower, meaning 8,000 jobs could be
relocated.
   ``We would like to keep the organization here in Chicago and we
will do everything possible to make that happen,'' Brennan said
Monday. But he added, ``We think it's our responsibility to the
shareholders to explore all options.''
   The restructuring is intended to have Sears employees adopt a
``low-cost mentality,'' and ``the signal of moving our headquarters
is a huge, huge step in that direction,'' Brennan said.
   Michael Bozic, chairman of the Merchandise Group, said at the
meeting that lessening the number of promotional sales on individual
items, could save the company up to $200 million a year through
reduced paperwork, inventory handling and related costs.
   Brennan said the marketing strategy also should mean better
return for advertising dollars.
   Sears has said that under the restructuring, it also would buy
back up to 10 percent of its stock, divest its Coldwell Banker
commercial real estate subsidiary and take $425 million in after-tax
fourth-quarter charges.
   Brennan said last week that the restructuring is designed to
enhance Sears' value to shareholders immediately and to concentrate
its resources over the longer term on consumer-oriented businesses:
retailing, insurance, real estate and financial services.
   Sears also plans to continue trying out other new marketing
techniques, including offering more national brands of some types of
products and opening specialty stores.
   Sears net income in the third quarter was $344.2 million, or 90
cents per share. That compared with $409 million, or $1.08 a share,
for third-quarter 1987.
</TEXT>
