<FILEID>AP-NR-11-07-88 2251EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>d f BC-Kroger-Lawsuit     11-07 0311</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Kroger-Lawsuit,0325</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kroger Settles With Some Shareholders in Restructuring Suit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kroger Co. said Monday it had reached an
out-of-court settlement with 11 of 14 shareholders who sued to block
the company's $4.6 billion restructuring program, although three
shareholders will fight the deal.
   The shareholders filed six class-action lawsuits after Kroger on
Sept. 15 announced plans to restructure to discourage two
unsolicited takeover proposals.
   The suits, consolidated into one, accuse Kroger executives of
trying to protect their jobs by the restructuring.
   Under the plan, shareholders will get a special $40 cash dividend
and a bond with a trading value of about $8 for each share they own.
   Kroger officials said they decided to settle to ``avoid further
expense, inconvenience and distraction.''
   The settlement, if approved by the Hamilton County Common Pleas
Court, would accelerate the maturity of the bonds by two years to
Oct. 15, 2006, and make other changes in how quickly Kroger must
redeem the bonds.
   It also would prohibit the company from redeeming bonds before
Oct. 15, 1993.
   Kroger will pay a premium _ in the form of a percentage of
between 1 and 3 points more than face value _ on bonds it redeems
between 1993 and 1996. The premium would be paid in addition to any
accrued interest.
   Kroger spokesman Paul Bernish said a court hearing on the
settlement should be set for mid- to late-December.
   Attorney Gene Mesh, representing three shareholders, said he
would file formal objections to the settlement because it does not
give shareholders any additional benefits.
   He said he wants further restrictions on when Kroger may redeem
the bonds and wants the company to pay a higher premium for
redeeming them early.
   Mesh contended that the settlement, in which Kroger has agreed to
pay $1.27 million to the plaintiffs' lawyers, was ``carved out only
to satisfy the attorney fees.''
</TEXT>
